(283, 347, 'Prof. James Tanaka', 'In a single glance of a face, we know the person’s identity, their gender, their race, andeven their emotional state. For most of us, these face perceptions are spontaneous,effortless and executed with little forethought or deliberation. However, for individuals with autism, finding the meaning conveyed in the face is not always easy. How do we recognize a face and what happens when the face recognition system breaks down? Is it possible to improve face recognition abilities through training? In my talk, I will discussrecent work exploring the cognitive and neural mechanisms of face recognition anddemonstrate innovative computer treatments for improving face recognition skills ofchildren with autism.', 1302780600, 1302784200, 73, 56, NULL, 'ProfessorDepartment of PsychologyUniversity of Victoria'),
(284, 348, 'Mr. Aleksandr Kogan', 'The topic of love has puzzled philosophers, poets, writers, laymen, and scientists alike forcenturies. Within psychology, numerous models have been proposed to understand love, with the bulk focusing on romantic love; however, some research suggests that romantic love is just part of much larger tapestry of love. Building upon theory from the social, developmental, and cognitive psychological traditions, I propose a dynamic systems approach to love. Through such an approach, the variable, dynamic, and multi-faceted nature of love across domains can be contextualized and understood along universalprinciples. Two studies are presented that used daily experience methodology toinvestigate people’s love priorities andexperiences of 12 different types of love in theUnited States and Hong Kong.', 1302694200, 1302697800, 73, 56, NULL, 'PhD candidateDepartment of PsychologyThe University of Hong Kong'),
(285, 349, 'Dr. Frans Verstraten', 'When we look at a scene, parts of objects may be occluded and only fragments ofobjects are represented on the retina. Yet, ourperceptual experience is that of whole objects in their environment. Clearly, the visual system fills-in information; it integrates the visible and the occluded parts. Representing an object isimportant, but as humans often act upon objects, it is as important to represent the orientation of the objects. It is still unknown how the visual system determines the orientation of an object that only has a fragmented representation on the retina. Doesit use information derived from visible local edges or does it use the perceptually completed object representation? I will try togive an answer making use of the well known oblique effect, in which observers are better at judging vertical and horizontal orientations as compared to oblique ones. We used an orientation discrimination task with subjective contours (Kanizsa figure) that evokes the percept of a square but provides no direct retina l information for its orientation. The orientation discrimination thresholds thatwe found are predicted from a perceptually completed object representation and not from the directly available local contours.', 1322998200, 1323001800, 73, 56, NULL, 'Professor of Experimental PsychologyUtrecht UniversityThe Netherlands'),
(286, 350, 'Prof. Anna Lau', 'Emotional attunement involves bringing one’s emotions into harmony with others. This requires both receptive (emotion perception) and expressive (emotion regulation) skills. Valuesin interdependent cultural contexts emphasize the importance of achieving attunement in interpersonal interactions, but do these values shape the development of requisites skills? I willpresent data suggesting that socialization strategies in East Asian cultural groups may helpchildren orient to the emotions of others and modulate their emotional expression. However,evidence also suggests that values emphasizing emotional attunement may not translate into therequisite abilities in emotion perception among Asian Americans. A resultant misfit betweenvalues and abilities in emotion perception may explain group differences in psychologicaldistress. I will present findings suggesting that the association between emotion perception abilities and distress is moderated by the degree to which Asian Americans hold interdependence values.', 1301484600, 1301488200, 73, 56, NULL, 'Associate Professor of PsychologyUniversity of California, Los AngelesUSA'),
(287, 351, 'Dr. Merideth Gattis', 'Studies of infant attention suggest a paradox: Although in fants are able to disengage attention from a visual stimulus from around 2 or 3 months, they do not follow the shifts of attention displayed by their social partners until late in the first year. I will present the results of two longitudinal studies investigating attentional abilities in early infancy. In doing so, I will evaluate i) whether observed infant abilities demonstrate evidence of the ability to follow the attentional focus of other people and ii) how early attentional abilities are related to the emergence of social cognition.', 1297855800, 1297859400, 73, 56, 0, 'Senior LecturerCardiff University'),
(288, 352, 'Dr. Susana Chung', 'Our ability to recognize an object in clutter is often impaired in a crowded environment. This is the crowding effect. Many theories have beensuggested to account for crowding, ranging from low-level to high-level factors. This talk will review some of the psychophysical evidence obtained from our lab in relation to several hypothesesof the underlying mechanisms of crowding.', 1297769400, 1297773000, 73, 56, NULL, 'Associate Professor of Optometry & Vision ScienceUC Berkeley'),
(289, 353, 'Dr. Patrick Wong', 'The links among genotype, endophenotype andphenotype—and their interactions with theenvironment—have intrigued theoretical pillarsof our discipline from Piaget and Vygotsky toHubel and Wiesel, among others. Together with psychologists, practitioners (and our fundingagencies!) ask how knowledge of such links and interactions might translate into clinical andpedagogical practices. In this presentation, I discuss some preliminary attempts by my research group that explore not only the biological and cognitive fundamentals of human learning, but also how learning can be altered based on knowledge of these fundamentals. We focus our efforts on language learning. Language, especially the sound and grammatical aspects, is notoriously difficult to master when learning begins in adulthood. The considerable individual differences we see in this domain provide a tremendous opportunity for identifying neurogenetic and neural markers for learning success. With these biomarkers, we can then attempt to modify training so that at least some of the learners’ learning can be optimized. This “Personalized Learning” approach has the potential to improve not only language teaching and treatment of communication disorders, but also other kinds of learning and behavioral therapies. [Work supported by NIH and NSF, USA]', 1293967800, 1293971400, 73, 56, NULL, 'Associate Professor of CommunicationSciences, Otolaryngology, and NeuroscienceNorthwestern UniversityU.S.A.'),
(290, 354, 'Dr. Kunlin Wei', 'In recent years computational approaches have been gaining popularity in the area of psychology. As a particular area of psychology, sensorimotor control studies focus on investigating how humans perceive relevant sensory information and control their motor actions. Theories fromoptimal control and Bayesian statistics have been successfully applied in explaining variousphenomena in sensorimotor control. In the present talk, I will review some of my finished studies. The research questions explored include:how does uncertainty in the sensory feedback and state estimation impact the rate of human motor adaptation? How are multimodal sensory inputs optimally combined statistically during the process of maintaining an upright posture? How can causal inference, a cognitive concept, be used to explain complex cue combination phenomena? Is there an optimal error size to facilitate motor learning? I wish to convince you that these seemingly diverse questions in psychology can be better understood with computational models based on Bayesian statistics.', 1292326200, 1292329800, 73, 56, NULL, 'Department of PsychologyPeking UniversityChina'),
(291, 355, 'Prof. Shaul Hochstein', 'I review Hochstein & Ahissar’s Reverse Hierarchy Theory, dividing explicit (conscious)perception into two modes: rapid vision at a glance and slower vision with scrutiny. The dichotomy encompasses a wide variety of phenomena, including our ability to perceive complex images even when these are presented at very rapid rates (RSVP) but a surprising inability to note seemingly large changes in flashed pictures (change blindness), the number of similar items in a scene (repetition blindness), or the relationship between properties and parts (illusory conjunctions). Our innovative viewattributes rapid conscious vision with spread attention to the large receptive fields of high-level cortical areas, where neurons respond to complex images but generalize over – i.e. are insensitive to – precise object location,orientation, size, lighting or the particular details that originally formed the recognized category. In contrast, slower perception with focused attention is seen as a conscious return to lower cortical levels serially following reverse-hierarchy feedback connections to the ultimate sources of high-level activation, recovering detailed information available in the specialized receptive fields found there. This dual correspondence is especially apparent in the two modes of visual search: Spread-attention feature search (”what” without ”where”) derives not from low-level cortical areas as previously assumed, but from higher-level position-insensitive receptive fields. On the other hand, scanning-attention difficult or conjunction search derives from explicit perception''s return to low-level position-encoding receptive fields. New physiological and psychophysical, behavioral data will be discussed, supporting this Reverse Hierarchy Theory view.', 1276344000, 1276347600, 73, 56, NULL, 'Neurobiology Departments & InterdisciplinaryCenter for Neural ComputationHebrew University, Jerusalem, Israel'),
(292, 356, 'Prof Heinrich Buelthoff', 'The question of how we perceive and interact with the world around us has been at the heart ofcognitive and neuroscience research for the last decades. Despite tremendous advances in thefield of computational vision made possible bythe development of powerful learning techniquesas well as the existence of large amounts of labeled training data for harvesting - artificialsystems have yet to reach human performance levels and generalization capabilities. In this talk Iwant to highlight some recent results from perceptual studies that could help to bring artificial systems a few steps closer to this grand goal. In particular, I focus on the issue of spatio-temporal object representations (dynamic faces), face synthesis, as well as the need for takinginto account multisensory data in models ofobject categorization. Having understood the important role of haptic feedback for human perception, we also explored new ways of exploiting it for helping humans (pilots) in solving difficult control tasks. This recent work on human machine interfaces naturally extends to the case of autonomous or intelligent machines such as robots that are currently envisioned to be pervasive in our society and closelycooperate with humans in their tasks. In all of these perceptual research lines, the underlying research philosophy was to combine the latest tools in computer vision, computer graphics, and virtual reality technology in order to gain a deeper understanding of biological information processing. Conversely, I discuss how the perceptual results can feed back into the design of better and more efficient tools for artificial systems.', 1290684600, 1290688200, 73, 56, NULL, 'Max Planck Institute for Biological CyberneticsTuebingenGermany'),
(293, 357, 'Dr. Lothar Spillmann', 'A common notion holds that the visual system detects, filters, analyzes, and represents stimulus features to produce a facsimile representation of the visual world. However, the physical stimulus cannot always explain the phenomenology of what we see. Just think of visual illusions. Also, many stimuli are ambiguous and yet we see only one percept. Furthermore, in a complex scene, the retinal stimulus does not specify the relativecontributions by illumination, reflection, and transmission. The fact that percepts cannot be fully accounted for by knowledge of the stimulus is called the inverse optics problem. Nevertheless, we see sufficiently well in order to navigate, find food, and escape danger. The Gestaltists were well aware of these achievements and assigned visual perception an active role in parsing the visual input. Their approach is best captured by Koffka’s question:Why do we see the way we do and not differently? Furthermore: What is it that phenomenology is trying to tell us? Can we deduce the structuralfactors that govern figure-ground organization and grouping from simple observations?Numerous examples suggest that our perception is structured by inherent “laws” that are responsible for the way in which scenes are segmented, figures are segregated on the ground, and stimuliare grouped. These lawsof seeing (Metzger) are the so-called Gestalt factors of closure, smooth continuation, proximity, symmetry, and similarity under the overarching principle of good Gestalt or Praegnanz. The strongest factor is the factor of common fate that governs grouping in moving stimuli. All these factors were shown to be effective both in adults and children, although to different extents, and also in many species of animals. They are assumed to be largely innate and are considered laws of nature. While the Gestalt factors enable us to see, they are equally suited for hiding, for example, in camouflage.Powerful measures for hiding an object from perception are tearing up the uniformity of its surfaces, wrongly partitioning it and breaking up the borders through inappropriate continuations. The universality of the Gestalt laws in man and nonhuman species implies that the visual brains of such species are similar to ours. Today’sneuroscience aims at finding neuronal correlatesand mechanisms for the descriptive categories of the Gestaltists. The talk will discuss the emergent role of such mechanisms for the perception of border ownership, completion of real and illusory contours, and grouping of coherently moving patterns.', 1284204600, 1284208200, 73, 56, NULL, 'NeurozentrumUniversity Klinikum FreiburgGermany'),
(294, 358, 'Prof. Gary S. Rubin', 'Reading difficulty is one of the chief complaints of low-vision patients who have lost foveal vision due to age-related macular degeneration(AMD). This difficulty persists even when text is magnified to compensate for loss of visual acuity. It has been suggested by several investigators that inefficient eye movements may contribute to the problem. I will review over 10 years of research on factors that limit non-foveal reading speed, paying particular attention to fixation stability, saccadic eye movements,and visual span. The implications of these findings for programmes of low vision rehabilitation will also be discussed.', 1273577400, 1273581000, 73, 56, NULL, 'Helen Keller Professor of OphthalmologyUCL Institute of OphthalmologyUK'),
(295, 359, 'Dr. Deborah M. Ko', 'Past research on face (Ting-Toomey &Cocroft, 1994), or dignity, has shown that cultures adopting an independent self-construal (i.e., from the West) are more concerned with self-face (personal dignity), while those adopting an interdependent self-construal (i.e., from Asia) are more concerned with other-face (another’s dignity). However, we propose that in social comparison, self-face and other-face play very different roles for Asians/Asian Americans. In Study 1, we primed other-face by having participants think about a close other’s success or failure. For Asian Americans, their self-esteem lowered when thinking about a close other’s failure whereas Europeans were unaffected. However, in studies 2 and 3, we found that social comparison primed self-face for Asian Americans, leading to opposite results. In study 2, when socially comparing with a close other, European Americans felt worse towards a close other’s failure than success. However for AsianAmericans, they felt better after a close other’sfailure than success. In study 3, participantsshowed similar responses in how they judged anagent in a story to react to the success or failure of their close other. This has implications on understanding the impact of social comparison on face-work in the East and provides an explanation to its paradoxically competitive yet collective nature.', 1265887800, 1265891400, 73, 56, NULL, 'Postdoctoral FellowDepartment of PsychologyThe University of Hong Kong'),
(296, 360, 'Dr. Z.G. Zhang', 'Electroencephalogram (EEG) is capable of measuring highly nonstationary brain activitiesin a non-invasive and low-cost manner, and it has gained significance in a wide range of clinical and research areas, such as psychology, neuropathology, cognitive neuroscience, etc.Signal processing techniques play a crucial role in identifying meaningful and representative patterns of brain activities from noisy and variable EEG recordings. In this talk, advanced EEG signal processing methods recently developed in the Department of Electrical & Electronic Engineering, HKU, will be introduced. The talk will cover a number of important issues in EEG-related studies, including single-trial analysis of evoked potentials, high-resolution time-frequency analysis, and identification of dynamic brain connectivity. We shall elaborate how these signal processing techniques enhance the utilization of EEG data and facilitate the understanding of underlying mechanisms of thebrain. A discussion session with Prof YS Hung and Dr CQ Chang in Biomedical EngineeringGroup at HKUEEE will be held after the seminar', 1288092600, 1288096200, 73, 56, NULL, 'Postdoctoral FellowDepartment of Electrical and ElectronicEngineeringThe University of Hong Kong'),
(297, 361, 'Dr. Wong Kwai Ling Yetta', 'Becoming a musician is challenging, as one has to efficiently integrate information from visual, auditory, somatosensory, motor and emotional domains during performance. While music reading is an essential skill to acquire in musical training, this visual skill has received little attention in the music literature. In this talk, I will review my recent work exploring how music reading expertise transforms the visual processes for musical notation. In the behavioral level, I will talk about two projects related to holistic processing and crowding, revealing how experts become highly sensitive to the relationship between musical notes, and yet retaining the ability to extract the identity of eachnote. These skills are likely central to the fast and accurate music reading performance in experts. In theneural level, I will describe fMRI and ERPdata showing how the brain processes musicalnotes differently with experience, from the initial visual processes of notes within 40-60ms to a large-scale multimodal network of brain activations specialized for musical notes. I willend the talk by discussing how these findings provide useful information for the understanding of visual perceptual expertise (e.g. recognizing faces, words, etc.), musical skills and the functional organization of the brain.', 1287487800, 1287491400, 73, 56, NULL, 'Postdoctoral FellowDepartment of PsychologyThe University of Hong Kong'),
(298, 362, 'Miss Bai Yu', 'The cognitive model of hope conceptualizes itas a goal oriented cognitive process with twocomponents: agency thinking (goal-directed determination) and pathways thinking (planning ofways to meet goals). Empirical studies have consistently demonstrated the negative association between hope and depression. The present presentation will focus on the moderating role of gender on the relationship between hope and prospective depression amongthe Chinese. Two independent longitudinal studies were conducted. In study 1, 114 college students (53 men and 61 women) were recruited from three cities in China (Beijing, Zhejiang, and Guangzhou). In Study 2, 303 participants (243 men and 60 women) were recruited from one of the top universities in Beijing. The two studies adopted similar design, but used different measurements to assess hope. Resultsdemonstrated that hope had significant effecton concurrent depression among both genders.However, hope showed significant relationship with prospective depression among female students only. High-hope female students, as compared to their low-hope counterparts,tended to exhibit less concurrent and prospective depressive symptoms. On the other hand, hope showed insignificant effect on prospective depression among male students, after controlling for baseline depressive symptoms. The results suggested that gender may serve as an important framework for understanding the effect of the positive thinking styles of hope ondepression, at least in a Chinese culture.', 1291980600, 1291984200, 73, 56, NULL, 'PhD CandidateDepartment of PsychologyThe University of Hong Kong'),
(299, 363, 'Prof. Gillian Rhodes', 'We have a remarkable ability to discriminate and recognize thousands of faces despite their perceptual similarity. This capacity depends on adaptive processes that code faces relative to perceptual norms abstracted from experience. Using work from my lab I will illustrate how the operation of these processes is revealed byperceptual aftereffects, how these processes are impaired in autism spectrum disorders (ASD), and how they contribute to our perceptions of beauty. Aftereffects have been dubbed the psychologist’s microelect rode because of their power to revealhow simple sensory attributes are coded. Our work suggests that they can alsoreveal much about the processing of more complex and socially relevant stimuli, such as faces.', 1285759800, 1285763400, 73, 56, NULL, 'Department of PsychologyUniversity of Western AustraliaAustralia'),
(313, 377, 'Mark Donohue', 'The spread of modern humans into and across Indo-Malaysia and the Pacific is significant for two reasons: firstly, the spread across Indo-Malaysia represents the earliest confirmed dispersal of humans across a marine environment, and involved numerous associated technologies that indicate sophisticated societies on the move. Secondly, the (much) later spread of Austronesian over such a wide region shows language replacement on a scale that is more reminiscent of the period of state-sponsored European colonisation than of a social landscape more than three millennia old.Standard views, still repeated, cast the Austronesian dispersal as involving the collision of a technologically advanced farming society with ''indigenous Mesolithic hunter-gatherer communities'': the pre-Austronesian populationsare assumed to have disappeared without a lasting impact on the linguistic ecologies that were taken over by the Austronesians. This talk problematises the association of Austronesian languages with ''Austronesian peoples'', and points out a number of dimensions in which thedispersal of Austronesian languages, originating in Taiwan, should not be equated with the technological and demographic steamroller that is often portrayed. This will involve discussion of the nature of pre-Austronesian society and language in the south-west Pacific, and the degree to which it has changed following ''Austronesianisation''.', 1377262800, 1377266400, 73, 57, NULL, 'ANU'),
(314, 378, 'One-Soon Her', 'In this talk, I will report on the findings from the first phase of the study. In total 100 classifier languages are identified from Greenberg(1990[1972]), Aikhenvald (2003), and Gil (2011). It is confirmed that 98 indeed have a multiplicative numeral system, while 2 only have restricted numerals. Among the 98 languages, C/M andnumeral bases are synchronized in 94. The relevant data of these languages are stored in a Geographic Information System (GIS) environment, so I will also present the results on a GIS world map and discuss the non-conforming languages in more detail. The second goal of the study is to explore the implications that the synchronization of C/M and bases have on C/M constituency, count/mass distinction, unification of C/M and bases, and evolutionary paths of numerals and C/M, and the ultimate ‘chicken-or-egg’ question between numerals and language. I will make tentative proposals on these issues.', 1370790000, 1370795400, 73, 57, 0, 'National Chengchi University'),
(315, 379, 'Peter Austin', 'In the last decade of the 20th century a new sub-field of linguistics emerged that has come to be known as ‘language documentation’ or ‘documentary linguistics’ (Himmelmann 1998, 2002, 2006, Lehmann 2001, Austin 2010, Grenoble 2010, Woodbury 2003, 2011a). In this paper we explore how it was defined in the seminal work of Himmelmann (1998) and others, including what were presented as significant characteristics that distinguished language documentation from language description. A focus on best practices, tools and models for documentary corpora appeared in the following years, along with more critical discussions of the goals and methods oflanguage documentation. The paper examines some current developments, including new approaches to archiving (Nathan 2010, Woodbury 2011b), and suggests that in the 21st century language documentation needs to adopt a more socially engaged approach to linguistic research.', 1379071800, 1379077200, 73, 57, NULL, 'SOAS'),
(316, 380, 'Yi Xu', 'How prosody is linked to meaning is along-standing issue. This talk explores the idea that prosodic functions such as focus, sentence modality and boundary marking are analogous to lexical morphemes, the smallest sound units that carry meaning. Four lines of evidence are presented, all based on experimental findings. First, similar to lexical morphemes, each prosodic function typically consists of multiple phonetic components. Second, like segmental phonemes, individual prosodic comonents are meaningless themselves but act jointly to mark both intra-and inter-functional contrasts. Third, like lexical morphemes, prosodic functions have allomorph-like variants whose occurrences are conditioned by interactions with othercommunicative functions. Finally, similar to lexical morphemes, prosodic functions arelanguage-specific with possible historical sources. This view of prosody has recently beentested on English and Mandarin with PENTAtrainers—aset of freely availablecomputational modeling tools developed forprosody research, with promising results.', 1380198600, 1380202200, 73, 57, NULL, 'University College London, UK'),
(317, 381, 'Martin Haspelmath', 'Prof. Haspelmath will present an overview of the recently published Atlas of Pidgin and Creole Language Structures (APiCS, Oxford University Press 2013) which provides a wealth of information on 76 pidgin, creole and other contact languages. It is based on collaborative work of 88 language experts, put together by four editors. The atlas contains 130 world maps of structural linguistic features, not unlike the World Atlas of Language Structures, and in fact quite a few of the APiCS features also occur in WALS, so that comparison of contact languages with the world''s languages is possible. In addition,there are over 15,000 examples and over 1500 bibliographical references. Most of the information is also freely available online. Of the 88 language experts, five are linguists from Hong Kong.', 1380540600, 1380546000, 73, 57, 0, 'MPI (Evolutionary Anthropology)'),
(318, 382, 'Hiram Ring', 'Pnar is an Austroasiatic language located in the northeast Indian state of Meghalaya, where it is in contact with Tibeto-Burman and Indic languages.Typologically unusual for Austroasiatic languages, in Pnar the default word order is for the verb to occur clause initially, with arguments (A/S, O) following immediately after the verb complex. Along with verbal TAM morphemes, Pnar morphology includes the agentive nominalizer nong-and stative nominalizers jing-and yu-, which prefix to verbs. Pronominal pre-clitics u, ka, and i, can also serve nominalizing functions, deriving non-finite verbs, resultatives and action nominalizations, respectively. The preclitic wa is another nominalizer, deriving adjectivals/attributives from verbs. This morpheme also functions as a relativizer, similar to the function of some nominalizers in nearby Tibeto-Burman languages (as identified by Matisoff (1972) for Lahu, and for other languages in the area by Noonan (1997); Bickel (1999); Watters (2008) among others). Unlike most TB languages, however, this relativizer is pre-verbal, more similar to constructions in other AA languages (ie. Middle Mon verbal cliticm ə). Similar in form is the wa ‘with/and’ coordinating conjunction that also occurs in Pnar. This presentation will give an overview of nominalizers in Pnar before focusing in more detail on the varied functions of wa, inviting discussion andcritique.', 1365604200, 1365607800, 73, 57, 0, 'Nanyang Technological University'),
(319, 383, 'Yuky Liu', '', 1385119800, 1385123400, 73, 57, NULL, 'University of Hong Kong'),
(320, 384, 'Alexis Michaud', 'This presentation examines brings out general tendencies on the basis of the analysis of detailed examples from narratives. Special attention is paid to cases that provide insights into how divisions into tone groups become habitual, and eventually become lexicalized, such as (i)the manner adverbials /ʈʂʰɯ˧ni/ ‘in this way, thus’ and /tʰv˧ni/ ‘in that way’, which constitut e a tone group on their own in the majority of cases, and (ii) compounds that resist the tendency towards integration into a single tone group. The data sets on which the analysis is based are available from the Pangloss Collection, at the following address: http://lacito.vjf.cnrs.fr/archivage/languages/Na_en.htm', 1385740800, 1385746200, 73, 57, 0, 'CNRS'),
(321, 385, 'Dr. Cathryn Donohue', 'In the paper I present an overview of case maeking data from a range of languages, with a special focus on Basque. In particular, I focus on data where three-place predicates, such as give, are causativized. This results in a four-place predicate, one more than ever occurs naturally. There is thus a maximum of only three structural cases to mark these four core arguments and it is not obvious how structural case should be assigned. I discuss how Lexical Decomposition Grammar (LDG; e.g. Kiparsky 1997, Wunderlich 1997 and others), Which takes the predicate and decomposes it into its core meaning, has many benefits for understanding and analyzing these data. Working with LDG in an Optimality Theoretic framework enables an analysis of the data in Basque that also extends across time and spce to capture the desired typology.', 1384878600, 1384884900, 75, 60, NULL, 'The University of Hong Kong'),
(322, 386, 'Prof. Lawrence Y. L. Cheung', 'Chinese has a special placeholder use of "demonstrative + wh-word" (or wh-placeholder) to substitute phrases, words or syllables that the speaker cannot utter for some pragmatic reason(s), i.e. a makeshift expression for something that the speaker does not immediately know how to express. The wh-placeholder is rather common in spoken discourse. Typical contexts include failure to recall somebody''s name and avoidance of taboo words. The speaker generally presupposes that the intended meaning is salient enough that the hearer(s) should be able to infer deictically in context. In this talk, the basic description of its morphology and syntax will be provided. An important observation is that the wh-placeholder can flexibly correspond to elements of different categories (e.g. nouns, verbs, adjectives, syllables, phrases and clauses) and positions that are not possible with interrogative wh, indefinite wh and universally quantified wh, etc. I propose that the wh-placeholder is a metalinguistic demonstrative that refers to the intended linguistic expression. The demonstrative is a definite operator that provides the quantification force for the wh-word, which gives rise to the definite reference to the intended linguistic object.', 1383064200, 1383070500, 75, 60, NULL, 'Department of Linguistics and Modern Languages, The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(323, 387, 'Prof. Charles Yang', 'From the comparative method to modern quantitative research on language variation, the study of language change has largely been influential in nature. The outcome of language change is subjected to structural and/or statistical analysis to identify general principles of change as well as the course of change for specific languages. We develop a new approach that complements there inferential methods. It projects well motivated mechanisms of language transmission over multiple generations to derive the expected dynamics of language change. This approach allows one to identify conditions in the linguistics environment--from historical corpora, dialectal surveys, etc.--under which certain linguistic changes would necessarily take place. We illustrate the utility of this predictive approach with a few empirical case studies, including the condition of dialect mixture that facilitated the /-n merger in Hong Kong Cantonese.', 1382007600, 1382014800, 75, 60, 0, 'Department of Linguistics and Computer Science, Institute for Research in Cognitive Science, University of Pennsylvania'),
(324, 388, 'Prof. Charles Yang', 'The hallmark of language is the combinatorial use of rules, but this may not be evident in the early stage of child development. Very young children''s language shows only limited degree of combinatorial diversity (Tomasello 2003), which bears similarities to the imitation based signs by primates such as Nim Chimpsky (Terrace 1979). Indeed, many accounts of language evolution build on the perceived continuity between the ontogeny and phylogeny of language (Bickerton 1996, Hurford 2011). It is worth noting that low combinatorial diversities in child language, the central piece of evidence for usage based theories of language, have never been shown to be inconsistent with a compositional view of grammar. In this work, we present a statistically rigorous demonstration that child language is based on abstract rules rather than the storage and retrieval of item-based expressions. Using the usage profiles of noun phrases, we show that young children''s syntactic diversity is statistically indistinguishable from the expectation of a fully compositional grammar once universal statistical laws of languages are taken into account. Furthermore, analysis of Nim Chimpsky''s production data shows that Nim''s sign combinations fail to reach the expected level of diversity; rather, they appear to bear hallmarks of memory and retrieval of holistic forms (Tomasello 2003).', 1381854600, 1381860900, 75, 60, 0, 'Department of Linguistics and Computer Science, Institute for Research in Cognitive Science, University of Pennsylvania'),
(325, 389, 'Prof. Mark ANTONIOU', 'In this colloquium, I will cover three areas in which language learning affects organisation in the mind and behavioral outcomes. 1. I will demonstrate the complex relationship between the phonetic categories of a bilingual''s first and second languages and how sensitivity to the sociolinguistic context can determine the degree of interaction between languages. In an initial speech production study, bilinguals produced words containing stop consonants differing in voice onset time in monolingual language modes, and matched the productions of monolingual native speakers. Such findings are typically interpreted as evidence that bilinguals maintain their two languages separately and free of interference. I demonstrated that such interpretations may be premature in a follow-up study six months later, in which the same bilingual subjects produce the same target words but this time they were required to do so by switching languages (code-switching). The bilinguals'' earlier acquired first language, Greek, exerted an influence on the later acquired second language, English, demonstrating that even fluent bilingual speakers do not maintain their two languages completely independently and interaction occurs when both languages are activated. 2. It is often claimed that bilinguals learn a third language easier that monolinguals acquire a second. We tested this claim in an artificial language learning experiment in which bilinguals and monolinguals learned words that use phonetic distinction that systematically differ in the degree of similarity to those found in the groups'' native language(s). The findings show that bilinguals enjoy a general learning advantage for ''easy'' phonetic contrasts, but language-specific experience boosts learning of contrasts that are universally ''difficult''. 3. Lifelong bilingualism is thought to result in cognitive advantages in in executive function, and these have been linked to improved cognitive outcomes in later life, including a decreased incidence of neurodegenerative diseases such as dementia. To end the colloquium, I will review the literature on cognitive training that aims to stem age-related cognitive decline, and propose that language learning may be a beneficial activity for promoting optimal cognitive aging in older adults. I will provide details of the research in two grants that we will be conducting over the next few years.', 1376152200, 1376158500, 75, 60, NULL, 'The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(326, 390, 'Prof. Margaret DEUCHAR', 'This talks follow up Poplack''s (1980) groundbreaking results on the factor favouring code-switching. I report on the result of an automatic analysis of 67,515 clauses from a Welsh-English corpus (http://talkbank.org/data.BilingBank/Bangor) collected fwhether proficiency in the two languages was as much a factor in our data as in Poplack''s, but also to identify the role of age, gender, the language of education, social network and attitudes to code-switching. We studied both intraclausal and interclausal code-switching, using a new automatic glossing mechanism to extract clauses and analysis by Rbrul relating social factor to the production of bilingual vs. monolingual clauses. Our results showed that both intraclausal code-switching were more common in younger speakers, those with positive attitudes to code-switching and those who has acquired Welsh and English simultaneously.', 1378719000, 1378722600, 75, 60, NULL, 'Director of the Centre for Research on Bilingualism, Bangor University'),
(327, 391, 'Prof. Michael Arbib', 'The Mirror System Hypothesis holds that the mechanisms that support language parity (the hearer tends to understand what the speaker intended) evolved atop an ancestral mirror system for manual actions that supported both the generation and recognition of such actions. The talks will summarize research that has enriched our understanding of the adaptability of mirror neurons and their role, in concert with other brain systems, in the evolution of the human language-ready brain via the brains of our last common ancestors with macaque monkeys (c.25 million years ago) and chimpanzees (5-7 million years ago).', 1377009000, 1377014400, 75, 60, 0, 'University of Southern California'),
(328, 392, 'Prof. Kenneth R. Pugh', 'The acquisition of fluent reading skill is an exercise in neuroplasticity. Reading disability (RD) is characterized as a brain-based difficulty in acquiring decoding skills, associated (in alphabetic languages at least) with problems in operating on the phonological structures of languages. We will present an update on new findings from an ongoing longitudinal study that reveals important gene-brain-behavior relations in young children at risk for RD including new findings on relationships between candidate genes, neurocircuits, and cognitive aspects of reading development. In addition, we present new findings on skilled adult readers on relative differences in brain organization for speech and reading in alphabetic and non-alphabetic orthographies.', 1376922600, 1376928000, 75, 60, 0, 'President and Director of Research. Haskins Laboratories'),
(329, 393, 'Dr. Gudrun Ziegler', 'Europe is at the forefront of multilingual practices, which challenge language theory building as well as methodologies for researching language learning and teaching. Drawing from recent studies conducted in Luxembourg, we discuss three areas of concern and their implications with regard to the use of multilingual resources in a monolingual foreign language classroom, the measurement of language development in plurilingual children and the issue of language teacher identify in the context of European policies promoting multilingualism.', 1362582000, 1362587400, 75, 60, NULL, 'University of Luxembourg'),
(330, 394, 'Prof. Wai Lan TSANG', 'This seminar presents a study on the acquisition of English nominal and verbal agreement by a group of L1Chinese-L2English-L3French (L1C-L2E-L3F) speakers, with the aim of answering the following question: will the acquisition of a third language exert any positive or negative influence over the previously acquired language(s)? The L1C-L2E-L3F speakers completed a free written recount and an acceptability judgement task, and their performance in the two tasks was compared with that of a group of L1 Chinese-L2 English speakers. Results showed that the two groups were similar in their use and judgement of English plural marking but they differed in the realm of English past tense marking. In considering their performance in the two tasks and the structural properties among the three languages concerned, it is suggested that there were traces of backward transfer among the L1C-L2E-L3F group.', 1366734600, 1366740900, 75, 60, 0, 'The University of Hong Kong'),
(331, 395, 'Prof. Yueguo GU', 'Situated discourse analysis (SDA) is a study of language use virtually with little abstraction or idealization. Language use is understood as being equivalent to the ways people live their everyday lives. Everyday lives are always lived by real-life people in real-life space-time for real-life activities. In other words, SDA is a study of real-life activities in real-life space-time. This talks presents an ecological model of SDA substantiated with data drawn from the Spoken Chinese Corpus of Situated Discourse (SCCSD), a multimodal corpus compiled by the author. Among the key concepts are (1) activity zones, (2) a web of activity trajectories, (3) an ecological chain, (4) urbanization and city-phenomenin, and (5) Social Space-Time vs. social space-time. Multimodal corpus data processing techniques are also touched upon.', 1366381800, 1366387200, 75, 60, 0, 'The Chinese Academy of Social Sciences'),
(332, 396, 'Prof. Yao YAO', 'What happens when two languages come into contact? This question is extensively explored in both second language acquisition (SLA) research and socio-historical linguistics, but with different perspective and approaches. While SLA studies focus on the interaction between two languages in a speaker''s mind, socio-historical studies are more concerned with the diffusion and transmission of the change in the community. In this study, we hope to (re)join the spirit of these two lines of research by examining an ongoing sound change in Shanghainese (Wu, Sinitic) that has been attributed to language contact with Mandarin. We focus our investigation on both the psycholinguistic basis and the sociolinguistic/acoustic status of the change. The change under investigation involves two vowels, [e] and [ ], reported to be merged three decades ago but produced distinctly in contemporary Shanghainese. Results of two production experiments showed that speaker age, language mode (monolingual Shanghainese vs. bilingual Shanghainese-Mandarin), and cross-language phonological similarity all influenced the production of these vowels. Innovative producation of [e] as distinct from [ ] was more advanced among younger speakers, when the production task required bilingual processing, and when corresponding Shanghainese and Mandarin forms were highly similar, suggesting that the recent sound change is indeed largely attributable to Mandarin influence. These findings provide evidence for language contact as a linguistic means of merger reversal and are consistent with the view that contact phenomena originate from cross-language interaction in bilingual individuals.', 1378312200, 1378318500, 75, 60, 0, 'The Hong Kong Polytechinic University'),
(333, 397, 'Prof. Sun Chaofen', '', 1364401800, 0, 75, 60, NULL, 'Professor, Department of East Asian Languages and Cultures Stanford University, USA'),
(334, 398, 'Prof. Lian-Hee WEE', 'When T''ong Ting-Ku compiled the Chinese English Instructor (henceforth CEI) in 1862, what he had in mind was a very practical volume that would allow his Cantonese-speaking compatriots to communicate effectively with the English-speaking traders at Canton (CEI, Chinese preface). The six-volume CEI covered a large range of topics, with the first two volumes dedicated almost solely to lexical items. The only transcription system available to T''ong was to represent the English words in Chinese characters intended to be pronounced by the Cantonese-speaking people. T''on used traditional Chinese fanqie and a few other diacritics of his own invention to overcome differences in phonotactics between Cantonese and English. Of particular interest to us is how T''ong cleverly used the tones of Cantonese to reflect the presence or absence of stress in the English words. Essentially, a study of lexical items recorded in the CEI revealed that the Cantonese transliterations of that period normally had higher tones, though not necessarily high tones, assigned to English syllables carrying stress. In modern basi- and mesolectal Hong Kong English (HKE) however, such ''stressed'' syllables now systematically are assigned high tones. Apparently, the use of higher tones to indicate stress has given way to a system where high tones are consistently used. Though it is unclear if modern HKE is tonal or pitch accentual, the stabilizing of tonal values suggests the potential evolution of HKE towards being a tone language. This process probably began with the contact between a tone language like Cantonese and a stress language like English, precipitating in a tone-stress hybrid like HKE. Evolution is a slow continual process with grey areas, and a comparison between CEI and modern HKE is about as clear a finding as one can ask for in identifying what might be two immediate steps in a long tenous process of language genesis.', 1363710600, 1363716900, 75, 60, 0, 'Hong Kong Baptist University'),
(335, 399, 'Prof. John Xuexin ZHANG', 'Whil English reading involves the recognition of 26 letters, Chinese reading involves the recognition of thousands of complex characters. Are the two scripts processed differently in the brain? Using event-related potentials, we recently reported a novel brain wave, the centro-parietal N200 reflecting early orthographic processing in Chinese word recognition. Strikingly, this N200 is specific to Chinese and has never been observed in English word recognition. N200 thus presents a strong piece of neural evidence that reading of Chinese and English are inherently different. This leads to a new theory conceptualizing Chinese as a meaning-spelling script that combines basic meaning-indicating units to construct new concepts, simulating the way the brain represents semantic knowledge. The theory argues that the meaning-spelling script and alphabetic scripts (i.e., English) are built upon different design principles capitalizing different human sensory modalities. Bridging over psychology and linguistics, the meaning-spelling theory represents the newest attempt to resolve a hundred-year controversy by positing that the Chinese script is in no way inferior to alphabetic scripts and shall never be Romanized.', 1367598600, 1367604900, 75, 60, 0, 'Department of Psychology, The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(336, 400, 'Prof. I-Fan Su', 'In the investigation of orthographic representation of Chinese characters, one question that has stimulated much research is whether radicals (character components) are specified for spatial position in a character, and to what extent the function of the radical impacts on the recognition process. In this talk we present two studies that capitalize on the excellent temporal resolution of ERP to investigate sub-lexical radical properties, namely radical position information, and phonetic radical regularity.', 1361896200, 1361902500, 75, 60, 0, 'The University of Hong Kong');
