(337, 401, 'Prof. Ovid J. L. Tzeng', 'The talk is about the history of establishing an integrated cognitive neuroscience laboratory in Taiwan. It has been a very difficult journey: I have to continuously face a hostile academic environment through all these years and a limited funding from the government. Those who reviewed our NSC (National Science Council) grant applications always turned down our applications by commenting that " Excellent research ideas but no one in Taiwan is able to carry out the proposed experimental project successfully.: So, in order to show those reviewers that i was the one who could run the projects and upgrade the research quality onto a higher new horizon in Taiwan, I built the first research-dedicated fMRI laboratory in Taipei''s VA Hospital, the first MEG system at Academia Sinica, many workable eye-movement tracking computer units at different universities, many ERP research laboratories across different institutions (universities and hospitals), and the first TMS and tDCS at the National Central University. Putting all these different neuro-imaging and neuro-physiological laboratories onto an integrated research platform and making it functional in probing the brain/mind connections have not been easy. I''ll trace the development step by step and give examples to show how the research field of cognitive neuroscience emerged and gradually became mature in Taiwan.', 1361545200, 1361552400, 75, 60, NULL, 'Academician and Distinguished Fellow of Institute of Linguistics, Academia Sinica, Taiwan'),
(338, 402, 'Prof. Ghil''ad ZUCKERMANN', 'This lecture will analyse the ethical, aesthetic and utilitarian benefits of language revival, and propose the establishment of REVIVALISTICS (including Revival Linguistics and Revivalomics), a new field of inquiry studying systematically the universal constraints and local peculiarities apparent in linguistic and cultural revitalizations across various sociological backgrounds. With coca-colonization and homogenization there will be more and more groups added to the forlorn club of the lost-heritage people. Language reclamation will become increasingly relevant as people seek to recover their cultural autonomy, empower their spiritual and intellectual sovereignty, and improve their wellbeing. There is an urgent need to offer perspicacious comparative insights relevant to language reclamation.', 1375439400, 1375445700, 75, 60, 0, 'The University of Adelaide'),
(339, 403, 'Prof. Shelley Xiuli Tong', 'Understanding how bilinguals can recognize and distinguish two speech sound systems has become a growing topic in speech perception and language acquisition. An important unresolved issue is about how Chinese-English bilinguals learn and characterize two distinct sets of pitch-based regularities - Chinese lexical tones and English lexical stress. This talk attempts to address this issue by bringing together two studies (monolinguals and bilinguials) to test whether the perception of Cantonese lexical tone and English lexical stress arise from the interactions of linguistic features and language learning experience. Two experiments were designed to test young children and skilled adults from Hong Kong. Both tone identification and AXB discrimination paradigm were used. We have found that the perceptual saliency of lexical tone arises from the interaction of the acoustic and phonetic constituents. Bilingual adults performed better in lexical stress than lexical tones perception, but no difference was found between tone perception and stress perception in children, Our findings suggests that some common perceptual mechanisms that support for the distinction of lexical tones and lexical stress may exist and they are shaped by language experience.', 1359477000, 1359483300, 75, 60, 0, 'Division of Speech and Hearing Sciences, The University of Hong Kong'),
(340, 404, 'Prof. Alan C. L. Yu', 'Linguists usually discuss language in terms of groups of speakers, even though it is often acknowledged that no two individuals speak alike. The focus on language as a group-level phenomenon can obscure important insights only apparent when systematic individual variation is taken into account. In this talk, I offer experimental evidence from Cantonese and English, showing that speakers vary significantly and systematically along certain individual-difference dimensions, including autistic traits, in their reponses to the effects of the lexicon and coarticulation in speech perception and production, I discuss the implications of individual difference studies for understanding the origins of language variation and change.', 1359124200, 1359130500, 75, 60, 0, 'University of Chicago'),
(341, 405, 'Prof. Janet Hsiao', 'In this talk, I will introduce two perceptual expertise markers in Chinese character recognition: reduced holistic processing and left side bias/right hemisphere (RH) lateralization. Holistic processing has been argued to be an expertise markers for face and object processing. In contrast, recent research in my lab showed that compared with non-Chinese readers (i.e. novices), Chinese readers who had limited writing experience showed increased holistic processing, whereas Chinese readers who were also proficient writers showed reduced holistics processing. This result suggests that writing/sensorimotor experience can modulate holistic processing effects, and that the reduced holistic processing effect observed in expert Chinese readers may depend on writing experience. The left side bias effect has been consistently observed in face perception. We recently found that Chinese readers also have a left side bias in the perception of mirror-symmetric characters, whereas non-Chinese readers do not, suggesting that left side bias is an expertise marker for Chinese character recognition. This phenomenon is consistent with the finding that Chinese orthographic processing typically involves more RH processing as compared with English orthographic processing. I will then present a computional model of visual word recognition that is able to provide a theoretical account for this lateralization difference between English and Chinese orthographic processing.', 1358872200, 1358878500, 75, 60, 0, 'Department of Psychology, The University of Hong Kong'),
(342, 406, 'Prof. Sherman Lee', 'When two languages belonging to a bilingual speech community compete for use in the same social domains, language shift is likely to occur, whereby the community gradually abandons the less dominant or prestigious language in favour of the other. This language contact phenomenon has been the subject of muxh sociolinguistic research, the ultimate goal of which is to advocate the preservation of minority languages. Language shift researcg has mainly been conducted from Western perspectives. Cases of ongoing language shift in local or Asian contexts, where numerous minority languages are endangered, are generally in need of more research attention. This talk presents a study on language shift among speakers of the Hakka variety in Hong Kong, a minority Chinese variety still found in the territory. These speakers were largely monolingual a few decades ago but are now primarily bilingual in Hakka and Cantonese. Figures from the 2011 census indicate that today, only 0.9 percent of the population in Hong Kong claim to use Hakka as their home language. While large-scale census surveys reveal overall trends indicating the rapid disappearance of the Hakka variety, smaller-scale enthnographic-based research in the community, as demonstrated in the current study, provides a richer insight into the actual dynamics of language shift. This study explores the language practices of individual speakers as the community shifts away from Hakka towards the use of Cantonese. Patterns of language choice and language use are examined using data collected through participant observation, informal interviews and conversational exchanges with members of the speech community in their homes. Patterns of conversational code-switching, a significant stage of individual language variation during the process of a language shift, are examined through the analysis of talk-in-interaction. The talk will include discussion of the future prospects of the Hakks variety in Hong Kong.', 1358267400, 1358273700, 75, 60, 0, 'Hong Kong Shue Yan University'),
(343, 407, 'Ms. Lone Petersen', 'The quest for defining the essential components of high quality written text, expertise in authoring, and the associated pedagogically supported pathway towards expert literacy has cultivated a rich variety of hypotheses and models regarding the nature of skillful writing and skillful writers. Whereas the majority of this ''theorizing'' around the nature of writing has been concerned with the teaching and learning of English as a First of Second/International Language, ESP, and EAL, this talk will be concerned with a distinctly different context of instruction, namely the teaching and learning of writing in university-level foreign language education. Highlighting a functional-semantic approach to the description of foreign language writing and its development, this talk will argue that increasing maturity of university level FL writing entails competency in writing in increasingly diverse contexts and that the extent of this competency is manifested in a variety of distinct linguistic dimensions of learner texts. One such dimension, the experiential dimension that is concerned with the construal of experienced reality through the systems of Transitivity and Logic, will be explored through analysis of learner texts deriving from a German as a Foreign Language curriculum that has articulated curricular practices for cultivating writing development towards advanced levels. Lastly, the connections between curricular aims for developing writing competency and the intricate fabric of student language at different levels will be discussed.', 1355848200, 1355854500, 75, 60, NULL, 'The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(344, 408, 'Prof. Leo Cheung', 'Ludwig Wittgenstein says in this Philosophical Investigations that ''[f] or a large class of cases--though not for all--in which we employ the word "meaning" it can be defined thus: the meaning of a word is its use in the languahe''. In thise cases, using a word or understanding the meaning of a word is a rule-governed activity . If one knows how to follow the rule governing the use of a word, one can understand its meaning. Following a rule is, therefore, not anything like mental process, but more akin to the exercise of ability. In this talk, I shall introduce Wittgenstein''s view concerning meaning and use, and examine some of the difficulties of such a view.', 1352737800, 1352744100, 75, 60, NULL, 'The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(345, 409, 'Prof.Suzanne K.Hilgendorf', 'One important factor contributing to the yet increasing functional range and depth of the English language in regions such as continental Europe, identified by Kachru (1990) as part of the Expanding Circle of English use given the language''s growing impact in spite of its historical status as a foreign code, is the especially dynamic and innovative phase the media are in at present. The advent of the Internet, the globalization of economics and business practices, and rapid advances in technology have had unprecedented influence, creating not only new media for communication, e.g., Twitter. Facebook, but also establishing new practices for traditional media, e.g., motion pictures, television, radio. One practice garnering increasing attention is that of the mass media reaching beyond national borders to address transnational, supranational, and even global audiences, in Europe as well as other parts of the world. The paper first reviews research in international Communication and Media Studies that is informative for linguistic study of transnational media, e.g., Chalaby''s (2006) American cultural primacy paradigm and Beck''s Cosmopolitan perspective (Chalaby 2007). It next outlines the transnational history of cinema and early international dominance of Hollywood, illustrated with the example of one European cinema market, Germany. The discussion considers language use in the industry and the introduction of localization practices. The final section is a detailed look at the linguistic practice of tilting Inner Circle films for release in the German cinema market, which reveals a continuum of language use between the two poles of English and German. Marketers and film executives do not view the two languages distinct categories with boundaries that cannot be crossed; in fact they deliberately choose and combine linguistic elements in innovative ways demonstrating great creativity and resourcefulness, with tilting practices occuring at numerous points along the continuum.', 1334248200, 1334254500, 75, 60, NULL, 'Simon Fraser University, Vancouver, Canada'),
(346, 410, 'Prof. Carine Yiu', 'In the last two decades, scholars have shon much interest in studying materials compiled in the 19th and early 20th centuries for Chinese dialects. These historical materials allow us to have a glimpse of the dialects spoken in the last two centuries and to trace the development that has taken place. In this talk, I will highlight some of the findings obtained from studies of early Cantonese grammar. Moreover, I will discuss my research into the expression of motion events in Cantonese with a special focus on the use of directional verbs in the last two centuries. Scholars suggest that the Chinese language has undergone a typological shift from a verb-framed to a satellite-framed language. However, I will show that the change is on-going with illustrations from Cantonese. Despite that Cantonese exhibits characteristics of verb-framed languages shown in Classical Chinese, statistical results illustrate that Cantonese was moved closer to become a satellite-framed language in the last two centuries. This talk will further propose that the change observed in Cantonese is a result of disyllabicization, a process which started in the standard language, from which it has spread to other dialects. The last part of the talk will provide a demonstration of the Early Cantonese Tagged Database.', 1354033800, 1354040100, 75, 60, NULL, 'The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology'),
(347, 411, 'Prof. David Li', 'Code-switching and medium of learning and teaching are traditionally seen as distinct research areas. Research has shown that code-switching is commonly used to index the bilingual''s social and/or ethnolinguistic identity, or various conversational meanings in ongoing discourse (e.g., selecting addressee(s), changing the topic, signaling despreference). In either case, referential meaning is generally regarded as more or less constant. To my knowledge there has been little empirical evidence of code-switching being attributed to the medium of learning and teaching. Empirical evidence was obtained from an experimental study involving 108 educated Chinese-English bilinguals in Hong Kong and Taiwan. The study, entitled ''One day with only Cantonese/Mandarin'', required student participants to use only their dominant community language for one day, and to avoid using any other language(s) (cf,''breaching experiments''/''revelation through disruption'', Harold Garfinkel 1967). Data arising from their rich and highly contextualized experiences were collected using two method: reflective diary and focus group. The primary objective of the project was to find out under what circumstances bilingual students would perceive a need to code-switch. A lot of instructive findings were obtained. This paper focuses on EMI-induced code-switching from Chinese to English by examining the code-switchers'' own accounts of the reasons why they found it so difficult to avoid instantiating field-specific terminologies when the conversation touched upon concepts that were learned and taught through English. Similarly difficult to avoid wre expressions belonging to what may be termed ''institutional discourse'', such as course and programme titles, administrative practices, academic departments and support services, etc. The tendency of cognitive dependence on English was clearly much stronger among participants in Hong Kong than in Taiwan. The findings point toward a psycholinguistic ''medium-of-learning effect'' on the development of bilinguality. The paper will end by briefly commenting on methodological concerns about the validity of self-reported data.', 1339432200, 1339438500, 75, 60, NULL, 'The Hong Kong Institute of Education'),
(348, 412, 'Prof. Helen Zhao', 'My recent works explores ways of teaching English article usage to intermediate and advanced proficiency English learners. For this, I designed a computer-based tutorial system with structured input, a large amount of practice opportunities, explicit feedback. Guided by the Competition Model (MacWhinney, 1997), I view the article system as a galaxy of cues determining article usage on the basis of form-function mappings. Cues compete with each other in terms of strength, as determined by availability, reliability, and complexity, Cues are categorized as either general or idiosyncratic, depending on how learners formulate metalinguistic explanations of their form-function mappings. In this talk I will elaborate on two experiments that tested the effectiveness of the article tutor. In Study I sixty-four advanced Chinese EFL learners received training on article cues presented in contrasting pairs. The participants were randomly assigned to one of the two feedback conditions that differed in terms of degree of explicitness: metalinguistic vs. exemplar feedback. Results showed that instruction promoted significant learning of article cues and particularly of idiosyncratic cues. There was no significant difference between metalinguistic and exemplar feedback. Study II had seventy-eight intermediate-advanced Chinese EFL learner participants. This experiment compared cue contrast with non-cue contrast instruction. It also examined whether the positive learning effects found in Study I could be enhanced through Bayesian Knowledge Tracing Model (Corbett and Anderson, 1995). Results indicated significant and retrained learning effects of article cues. There was no significant difference between different instructional conditions when all cues were considered. However, there was a significant interaction between cue contrast and the type of cues. Cue contrast promoted more learning of the poorly acquired cues, whereas non-cue contrast generated more balanced learning of all cues. Knowledge tracing served to enhance the other learning effects.', 1347294600, 1347300900, 75, 60, NULL, 'Department of English, The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(349, 413, 'Prof. San Duanmu', 'The lexicon is an extremely important aspect of language, For one thing, the lexicon embodies human knowledge, in the sense that it contains all the pieces (morphemes) with which human knowledge is expressed or represented. In addition, the lexicon interfaces with multiple components of grammar, such as semantics, syntax (e.g. part of speech), morphology (e.g. affixation and compounding), phonology (e.g. pronounciation, stress and truncation). Moreover, the lexicon offers a new perspective on two questions that are central to linguistics, namely, which aspects of language are universal and to what extent can languages differ from each other. In this talk, I report on a comparative study of the lexicons of English and Chinese. The study is of interest in several ways. First, English and Chinese are probably the two best studied languages, of which we have high-quality data that allow us to carry out quantitative analyses. Second, typologically, English and Chinese are quite different from each other, one being highly inflectional and the other hardly at all; therefore, they offer an ideal case for cross-language comparisons. Third, English and Chinese are probably two most widely used languages in the world; therefore, a better understanding them may have great pratical consequences. Compared with syntax, semantics, morphology, and phonology, theoretical linguists have paid much less attention to the lexicon. Therefore, I shall start with two simple questions, whose answers remain unclear: (a)What are the sizes of the English and Chinese lexicons? (b) In the lexicon, what are the percentages of the POS categories N, V, and A? For analysis, I shall use the CELEX lexicon for English (Baayen et al. 1995) and for Chinese. I shall show that (a) and (b) raise a number of other questions, such as what a lexicon is, the collection method, the definition of words, decisions on lexical entries and senses, word frequencies, and decisions on part of speech. I shall show that striking similarities are found between English and Chinese with regard to the structures and the sizes of their lexicons. Implications of the results will also be discussed.', 1331303400, 1331309700, 75, 60, NULL, 'University of Michigan'),
(350, 414, 'Prof. Rint Sybesma', 'This paper is about two inter-related topics. The first has to do with telecity and resultatives and the need for a structural account for these notions. This part will discuss Mandarin resultatives in the context of Lisa Travis''s recent work on "inner aspect": the idea that a number of aspectual issued are taken care of in the functional domain between (big) VP and (little) vP. The second topic deals with the differences and similarities between accomplishments and achievements. When we look at the literature on verb classes we see that achievements and accomplishments are both telic, but that they differ in that the latter involves a process, while the former does not. In this talk I want to see whether it its possible that these verb classes have different representations in "inner aspectual" terms.', 1337877000, 1337883300, 75, 60, 0, 'Universiteit Leiden'),
(351, 415, 'Prof. Li Yen-hui Audrey', '', 1337704200, 0, 75, 60, NULL, 'Professor, Department of Linguistics and Department of East Asian Languages and Cultures, University of Southern California, USA'),
(352, 416, 'Prof. Bryan Gick', 'Many untested common conceptions have persisted in the fields of speech production/perception, phonetics and phonology. Innovations in simulation and experimental methods have enabled testing of many of these conceptions, sometimes with unexpected results. Some of these conceptions include: (1) that a set of phonological featured corresponds to a single type of physical event; (2) that oral constrictions are made primarily with the tongue; and (3) that speech is perceived through the ears, and is based on past experience. These and other conceptions will be tested, and a model of speech will be proposed that can accomodate the results.', 1344184200, 1344190500, 75, 60, 0, 'University of British Columbia, Canada'),
(353, 417, 'Prof Carol PADDEN', 'Recent research in new sign languages such as Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language and Nicaraguan Sign Language (Sandler, et al., 2005: Senghas et al. 2004) among others, has revealed how language can emerge in as few as two or three generations. In this talk, I discuss studies conducted by myself and colleagues with hearing non-signing adults who are asked to create novel gestures for objects and for actions. Their responses are surprisingly consistent, suggesting that even within novel gestures, there are conventions for expression. I also include new work with young hearing children who are asked to provide responses to the same pictures and actions as adults. Interestingly, their gestural choices are consistently different from adults. This research into child and adult gesture yields insights into the role of gesture in language and communication. This work leads to proposing a continuum of convention and grammaticization from novel gesture to home sign, and to new sign language.', 1335520800, 1335527100, 75, 60, 0, 'University of California, San Diego'),
(354, 418, 'Dr. Leticia VICENTE-RASOAMALALA', 'Over the past several decades, there has been a long-standing controversy in second language acquisition (SLA) theories surrounding the roles of formal instruction and error treatment in foreign language (FL) acquisition. During the 1990s, a growing interest emerged, reconsidering the role of the external environment in FL acquisition (Consolo, 2006; DeKeyser, 1993; Doughty & Varela, 1998; Gardner & Wagne, 2004; Long et al., 1998; Muñoz, 2000; Wong Fillmore, 1991). The new SLA model views language acquisition as a social activity developed in interaction (Long, 2004; Mackey et al., 2003). Notably, a number of SLA studies suggest that teacher feedback provided during classroom interactions might facilitate the noticing, acquisition and retention of L2 forms (Ellis et al., 2006; Iwashita, 2003; Leow, 1997; Lyster & Saito, 2010; Mackey, 1999; Mackey & Philip, 1998; McDonough, 2005; Oliver & Mackey, 2003; Yang & Lyster, 2010). Such conversational feedback might create meaningful possibilities for the learners to modify their output, help learners become aware of their interlanguage gaps. By this understanding, making error might be crucial for developing learner competence. Consequently, a corresponding empirical SLA research trend has taken shape and has been labeled the ''Reactive Negative Evidence'' (Carroll & Swan, 1993; Ellis et al., 2001; Long. 2004; Oliver, 2000). Against this background, it is assumed that teacher reactions to FL learner output might facilitate language acquisition in FL classroom conversations. The present talk will review how various approached have analyzed teacher and student SLA classroom interactions. It will focus on the learner error, implicit negative feedback and modified output studies. It will also briefly consider the sociocultural or the Neo-Vygotskian perspective as one alternative novel psychological perspective for describing and explaining Teacher Reaction Episodes (Vicente-Rasoamalala, 2010). For the time being, on-going and growing empirical research from SLA approaches on negative feedback have not yet provided any conclusive results. In addition, this area of study seems having not developed a clear and unified researcg methodology ytet.', 1335285000, 1335291300, 75, 60, 0, 'The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(355, 419, 'Prof. LIU, Lening', 'This paper presents "grammaticalization" as both a phenomenon and a conceptual framework. It discusses the major linguistic theories and schools that modernized the tradition of grammarticalization, and pays tributes to the linguists who played the crucial roles in this process. Then, the paper shows how to apply grammarticalization theory to the study of Chinese conjunctive adverbs and futurity markers. It further raises the possibilities to apply the theory to teaching Chinese as a second language.', 1336149000, 1336155300, 75, 60, 0, 'Columbia University (USA)'),
(356, 420, 'Prof. Jackson Gandour', '', 1332865800, 1332872100, 75, 60, NULL, ''),
(357, 421, 'Dr. Chin Lung Yang', '', 1332261000, 1332267300, 75, 60, NULL, ''),
(358, 422, 'Prof Patricia Kuhl', 'The human capacity for language is considered a new frontier in brain science, one that is attracting a multidisciplinary team of scholars working in teams. Teams of psychologists, cognitive scientists, biologists, linguists, neuroscientists, speech and hearing scientists, and engineers working in "science of learning" centers are beginning to understand the biology underlying our linguistic capacities as well as the learning mechanisms that allow us to absorb the communication style of a particular culture. In this talk, I will describe what these science of learning teams are discovering: (i) that children bring innate skills to the language learning task, (ii) that the Critical Period for language learning may be the result of experience rather than merely time (maturation), (iii) that the brain mechanisms responsible for learning stem from an interaction between computational and social brain areas and (iv) that early bilingual language learning alters brain structure fundamentally, and improves certain cognitive skills. Understanding how children accomplish the feat of learning not only one but also multiple languages may result in new biomarkers for developmental disabilities such as dyslexia and autism, as well as technologues that allow humans to improve their ability to learn a new language at any age. An understanding of humans'' capacity for language may unlock the deepest mysteries and mechanisms of the human mind.', 1337005800, 1337009400, 75, 60, 0, 'Co-Director, Institute for Learning and Brain Sciences; Co-Director, NSF Science of Learning Center (LIFE); University of Washington, USA'),
(359, 423, 'Prof. Maria Zlateva', 'The lecture discusses the role of Pedagogical Grammer (PG) in language teaching in various academic settings. Definitions and conceptualization of PG are reviewed to demystify the evolving notion of PG and to establish a working base that encompasses content, pedagogy, and learning perspectives. Fresh orientations to the system of grammar (such as Functional Grammar, Action Grammar, Relevance Theory) are presented to show how applied linguistics research can inform grammar teaching to develop an account of language that reflects the way people actually learn and use it. This leads to the rationale for teaching grammar in context, using a task-based approach which aims to cultivate linguistic accuracy along with meaningful and appropriate use of grammar structures. The presentation provides examples of classroom practices and ends with a summary of implications for curricular design, teacher training, and further research.', 1338737400, 1338743700, 75, 60, 0, 'Boston University, USA'),
(360, 424, 'Prof. Chao Fen SUN', 'This is a study of the form-meaning co-variations of noun phrases in relation to the most frequently occuring morpheme de的inModernStandardChinese.UnlikeitscounterpartsinmanylanguagessuchastheEnglishof/''s,Chineselexicalitemswithuniqueandkindmeanings donotco-occurwithde.Ononeendoftheproposedlexical/grammaticalcontinuumarethesemanticallyuniquepropernounsandcommonnounsforbidden toco-occurwithde,andtheontheotherendarenounphraseswithindividualreadingsmarkedbyde.Uses,onnon-use,ofdeinthemiddleofthecontinuumincludeword-likeandphrase-likeexpressionsreflectingdifferentdegreesoflexicalizationandtheelusivenatureoftheChinesewordboundary.', 1330446600, 1330452900, 75, 60, 0, 'Stanford University, USA'),
(361, 425, 'Dr. Yi-ching Su', 'Previous studies on first language acquisition of quantifier scope showed that English-acquiring children demonstrated a general preference for the universal quantifier or negation to take wide scope, whereas Chinese-acquiring children tended to assign the existential/QNP wide scope reading (e.g., Lee 1986, 1996: Chien 1994; Philip 1995: Su 2001, 2008). In this study we used event-related potentials (ERPs) to investigate how singular/plural NPs are integtrated into ambiguous sentences ''every kid climbed a tree'' in on-line sentence processing. Dwivedi et al. (2010) examined ERPs elicited by the singular/plural nouns and verbs in the continuation sentences such as The tree(s) was/were in the park following ambiguous or unambiguous context sentences. Their results showed no effects of N400 or P600, but a sustained negative shift at the verb position in ambiguous sentences. They interpreted the lack of N400 and P600 effects as underspecified representations for the scopally ambiguous sentences. Similar design was adopted in the current study, with continuation sentences ''because the tree(s) was/were big and tall'' following the ambiguous or unambiguous sentences. Although previous off-line studies showed that for these sentences. Chinese-speaking adults prefer the universal wide scope reading (e.g., Lee 1986; Zhou & Gao 2009), the ERP results from the present study showed that despite the lack of N400 effect, the P200 and Late Positive Component found in the plural continuation of the ambiguous condition suggested a preference for the exitential wide scope reading in initial parsing. The child-adult parallel found in this study is in accord with recent findings of child-adult parallels in the interpretation of anaphora (e.g., Sturt 2003; Kazanina et al. 2007; Kazanina & Phillips 2010; Leddon & Lidz, 2005; Omaki et al. 2007).', 1329229800, 1329236100, 75, 60, NULL, 'National Tsing Hua University (Taiwan)'),
(362, 426, 'Dr. Hsu-Wen Huang', 'My research uses electrophysiological methods, which provide a direct, temporally-precise measure of brain activity, to explicate the cognitive and biological mechanisms underlying one of the most important and uniquely human activities - language comprehension. To successfully comprehend a message, information acquired through different sensory modalities must be rapidly combined and integrated with long-term knowledge. Although theories of language comprehension often assume that language comprehension arises along a single processing stream, leading to a single meaning representation for an utterance or text, there is an emerging understanding that comprehension arises along multiple, parallel processing streams in which the two cerebral hemisphere play complementary roles. In the resolution of sublexical ambiguity in Chinese two-character words, I have shown that the hemispheres respond similarly in a biasing context, but differ when no context is provided. I have further shown that the two hemispheres use context information differently. The left hemisphere is highly sensitive to contextual constraint and seems to use context information to anticipate upcoming words and their semantic features. In contrast, the right hemisphere processes in a more stimulus-driven fashion, but also plays a critical role in linking language input to sensory imagery. These functions, however, are susceptible to age-related decline, such that older adults are less likely to engage left hemisphere-dominant predictive processing mechanisms and use message-level meaning information to initiate controlled processing, including right hemisphere-initiated processes associated with imagery.', 1343899800, 1343906100, 75, 60, NULL, 'University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign'),
(363, 427, 'Dr. Janny Leung', 'This paper investigates how the equal authenticity principle, a core assumption in any balanced bilingual or multilingual jurisdiction, changes in value and function as its discourse travels across jurisdications and interacts with different sociopolitical realities. I will attempt to trace how the equal authenticity principle was framed when the idea was first conceived in Canada and later in international treaties (especially the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties); how it was then recontextualized and adopted by the Hong Kong judiciary when it became bilingual; and how the framing of the principle subtly shifted in the process of statutory drafting and interpretation, especially when discrepancies between two language texts are alleged (in cases such as HKSAR v Tam Yuk Ha and Chan Fung Lan v Lai Wai Chuen). I argue that the surface similarity between the equal authenticity principle applied in international treaties, Canada and Hong Kong can be misleading, and that the meaning of ''equal authenticity'' critically depends on the way it is framed in the linguistics and non-linguistic context.', 1341246600, 1341252900, 75, 60, 0, 'University of Hong Kong'),
(364, 428, 'Prof. Eric Zee', 'This talks presents the phonetic typologial facts about the vowels, vowel systems, consonants, and consonant systems of an areally and genetically balanced representative sample of 70 sub-dialects selected from ten Chinese dialect groups, namely Northern Chinese, Wu, Min, Yue, Xiang, Kejia, Jin, Hui, Ping, and Tu, and generalizations over the observed cross-dialectal patterns of the sounds, Vowels.', 1328027400, 1328033700, 75, 60, 0, 'City University of Hong Kong'),
(365, 429, 'Prof. Marina NESPOR', 'I will present arguments indicating that the grammatical diversity observed among the world''s languages emerges from the struggle between individual cognitive systems trying to impose their preferred structure on human language. Evidence from language change, grammaticalization, stability of order, parsing advantages, as well as theoretical arguments, indicates a syntactic preference for SVO. The reason for the prominence of SOV languages is not as clear. I will present experiments aimed at establishing the cognitive bases of the two most common word orders in the world''s languages: SOV (Subject - Object - Verb) and SVO. In two gesture-production experiments and one gesture comprehension experiment. I will show that SOV emerges as the preferred constituent configuration in participants whose native languages (Italian and Turkish) have different word orders. I will propose that improvised communication does not rely on the computational system of grammar. The results of a fourth experiment, where participants comprehended strings of prosodically flat words in their native languages, shows that the computational system of grammar prefers the orthogonal Verb - Object orders. Evidence for the two word orders in natural circumstances is found in atypical languages acquisition: SOV in Homesign, i.e. simple communication, and SVO in Creolization, i.e. grammaticalization.', 1326988800, 1326996900, 75, 60, 0, 'University of Milano-Bicocca, SISSA in Trieste, Italy'),
(366, 430, 'Prof. Cai Zhenguang', 'Bilinguals speak and comprehend two languages. Researchers have long be interested in the interaction of the two language systems in bilinguals. In this talk, I will mainly discuss the following question: What reconfiguration does bilingualism bring to the language processing system? Building on research of others and my own, I propose to address three aspects of bilingual language processing. First, how are the two lexica (especially translation equivalents) represented in bilinguals and how do these representations develop? Second, are the two production systems separate or (party) shared? Third, are bilinguals more sensitive to syntax in language processing? In the end, I will also touch upon the cognitive consequences of bilingualism (i.e., do bilingual minds work differently from monolingual minds) and propose some future studies along this line.', 1324459800, 1324465200, 75, 60, NULL, 'University of Manchester'),
(367, 431, 'Prof. Peng Gang', 'Current modern imaging techniques provide us powerful tools to examine the brain while it processes certain tasks. With help of such imaging techniques, we are now in a good position to contribute to knowledge about the biological infrastructures that make language possible. In this presentation, I will first discuss various imaging techniques, with focus on functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI) and Electroencephalography (EEG), showing how such techniques have been used to demonstrate the influence of language/domain experience on perception. Then I will discuss our experiments that examine (1) how language experiences influences pitch contour perception in the framework of categorical perception, (2) how imaging techniques help to discover the fine-grained perceptual consequence which cannot be uncovered via merely behavioral experiment, (3) finally, the Acoustics Density Hypothesis will be proposed to explain the above findings. Such experiments are helpful in undersranding how language shapes brain, and then brain produces language-dependent behaviors, building up our understanding of the biological infrastructures of language.', 1324391400, 1324396800, 75, 60, 0, ''),
(368, 432, 'Prof. Benjamin Munson', 'Recent work has shown that the distributional characteristics of sounds that learners are exposed to in novel-language learning tasks affect their eventual identification and discrimination of those sounds (Maye, Werker, & Gerken, 2002; Clayards, Tanenhaus, Aslin & Jacobs, 2008). These findings predict that groups of listeners that differ in the distributions of sounds to which they are exposed in real-world speech perception should differ in identification and discrimination, too. This talk examines this possibility by studying the role of expose to children''s speech on individual''s performance on speech perception task. Acoustic-phonetic distributions of children''s speech differ from those adults for at least two reasons: Children produce stereotypical error patterns (i.e., the ''fronting'' of /k/ and /g/ to [t] and [k], in English-acquiring children), and children''s correct productions are acoustically more variable than those of adults. The first study (Munson, Johnson, & Edwards, submitted) examined relationships between experience interacting with children and the perception of fine acoustic detail in children''s speech. Individuals who self-reported more experience interacting with children (more-experienced listeners) perceived fine phonetic detail better than those of listeners with less experience interacting with children (less-experienced listeners). The second study (Julien & Munson, submitted) examined the propensity of adults to hyperarticulate productins to children whose speech they perceive to be inaccurate. More-experienced listeners were found to be more likely to hyperarticulate in response to hearing inaccurate production by a child than were less-experienced listeners. The third study (Christy, 2010, see also Munson, 2011) examined the perception of the accuracy of children''s speech when it was paired with pictures of African-American and European-American faces. For less-experienced listeners, there was a relationship between performance on a measure of implicit attitudes toward African-Americans and European-Americans and the extent to which the imputed race of the talker influenced ratings. For more-experienced listeners there was no such relationship. Taken together, these findings suggest that experience interacting with children is an important source of variation in speech perception.', 1322670600, 1322676900, 75, 60, 0, 'Department of Speech-Language-Hearing Sciences, University of Minnesota'),
(369, 433, 'Prof. Umberto Ansaldo', 'Within the field of contact linguistics the phenomenon of language creation, or formation of new grammatical systems, has attracted some serious attention over the past few decades. In trying to understand how and why speakers come up with new or restructured grammars a number of theoretical constructs have been generated with significant implications for our theories of grammar and language use. This talk reviews a number of assumptions about what is involved in the formation of new languages in the light of what we know about the most common contexts in which such phenomenon takes place. These include the nature of multilingual communitied, second kanguages acquisition in untutored settings and substrate transfer in typological diverse settings. This leads us to revisit some common assumptions about complexity, simplification and redundancy in new and old grammars.', 1321374600, 1321380900, 75, 60, 0, 'The University of Hong Kong'),
(370, 434, 'Prof. Tan Lee', 'In the seminar, I will start by giving a brief introduction to the basic principles and methods of computer processing of speech signals. Then I will talk about the capabilities and limitations of several key technologies of speech signal processing and discuss their potential applications in the research of linguistics, speech and hearing science. Several examples of our latest interdisciplinary studies will be given. They include tone-enhancement for cochlear implant users, design of next-generation electrolarynx, and automatic alignment of large amount of normal and disordered speech.', 1294763400, 1294769700, 75, 60, 0, 'Department of Electronic Engineering, CUHK'),
(371, 435, 'Prof. Andy Chin', 'In the past decade, there has been increasing interest in studying Sinitic languages from a typological perspective with an aim to explore the common and diversified properties that Sinitic languages share with other world''s languages. This type of study usually involes surveys of a huge pool of genetically unrelated languages. Such massive linguistic data can now be accesses via the World Atlas of Language Structures (WALS,http://www.wals.info)first published in 2005, then revised in 2008 and 2011. WALS provides us with a rich database in terms of the distribution of some major linguistic features across more than 1,000 languages, including Mandarin and Cantonese.', 1319560200, 1319566500, 75, 60, 0, 'Hong Kong Institute of Education'),
(372, 436, 'Prof. TENG Shou-hsin', 'The line of demarcation between theoretical linguistics and the applied linguistic discipline of modern language pedagogy has been gray and blurred for long. The dominance of the former over the latter cannot be felt more prominently than in the field of L2 Chinese. A case in point is the system of parts of speech. Over the past several decades, the systems of parts of speech in modern Chinese, as results of linguistic researches and debates, have been adopted verbatim in L2 Chinese, with less than satisfactory pedagogical consequences. What I hope to accomplish in this talk is to show that a set of pedagogical parameters should be built into the system of parts of speech in Chinese, enriching the theoretical system and endowing the words, the vocabulary items in pedagogy, with dynamic syntactic information. The end result should greatly assis the learners in acquisition of Chinese grammar. The set of pedagogical parameters include universality of certain parts of speech, positive and negative transfer, simplicity conditions, default values, reference to sub-categories and error-driven factors. Subsequesnt to the discussions of these parameters, an optimal system of parts of speech is illustrated not only for the pedagogical field but for theoretical considerations as well.', 1320942600, 1320948900, 75, 60, 0, 'Chulalongkorn University, Thailand'),
(373, 437, 'Patrick C. M. Wong', 'Empirical studies and anecdotal evidence point to the fact that a large individual variability exists in learning in adulthood. In particular, second language learning, especially foreign phoneme and grammar learning, is notoriously challenging, and adults differ to a large extent in how successful they learn. How this variability can be identified before training and how altering training may reduce variability have yet to be extensively investigated. In this presentation, I report two sets of experiments targeting these two questions, including experiments examining the learning of lexical tones and phonological opacity by native English-speaking adults. Both sets of experiments suggest that the large individual variability in language learning success can be attributed to genetic, neurobiological, perceptual, and/or cognitive factors. Furthermore, re-designing training based on these predictors can sometimes optimize learning. For example, training programs that take advantage of phonetic-phonology continuity and reducing the degree of phonetic-indexical variation can benefit the weaker (but not stronger) learners. Training that increasing trial-by-trial feedback can further improve the learning of learners with high (but not low) procedural memory ability. I will discuss how these experiments may provide an opportunity for understanding the nature of linguistic representations, the manner in which language processing and learning occurs in the brain, and the interactions between linguistic and cognitive systems. I will also discuss how such knowledge may have the potential to improve language pedagogy and treatment of language disorders.', 1316017800, 1316024100, 75, 60, 0, 'Northwestern University'),
(374, 438, 'San Duanmu', 'There have been alarming reports recently that Shanghai Chinese, once a highly prestigious regional tongue, is no longer the dominant language in the city. In addition, an increasing number of children of Shanghai-speaking parents do not speak it at home. What caused such rapid decline? What languages are taking over its place? Are people concerned about the loss of their mother tongue? Will a similar linguistic price be paid in other cities of fast socio-economic changes? To begin to address such questions, we examine the patterns of language use through a survey of 2000 residents in Shanghai. We found that the average home usage of Shanghai is under 40% and the average total usage is barely 30%. In addition, the trend shows a continued sharp decline of Shanghai and the quick rise of Putonghua and English.', 1312648200, 1312654500, 75, 60, 0, 'University of Michigan');
