(375, 439, 'Barry C.Y. Yang', 'Chinese is peculiar or sometime "cool" (Huang 1984) in terms of agreement and movement. A case in point is the licensing of null subjects/objects without the aid of overt agreement morphology. Another case is the scope-taking strategy of wh-construal without resorting to overt movement. A third case runs quite opposite to the wh-construal. That is, though Chinese does not overtly move its wh-items, it has at least two ways, i.e., object shift and focus fronting, to overtly move its object to the preverbak, IP-internal position. In this talk, I will re-investigate into the above seemingly unrelated constructions in Chinese, an "agreements" language, and show that they are not coincident. I will show that they can all be subsumed into the Top/Foc feature agreement system, a parametric version of phi-feature agreement per Miyagawa (2005,2009). The Top/Foc feature plays a crucial role with respect to EPP licensing in the "agreementless" languages such as Chinese, in contrast to the phi-features in the agreement languages whose "subject-of" function of the phi-features on T is reinterpreted as the "topic/focus-of" function of the Top/Foc feature in Chinese, a discourse configutational language (Kiss 1995). By so doing, we are able to bridge some gaps between the agreement languages and the agreementless languages in a uniform way.', 1306427400, 1306433700, 75, 60, NULL, 'National United University'),
(376, 440, 'GONG Tao', 'In this presentation, I will introduce a computer model to study the word order bias in languages. It simulates individual linguistic behavior in communications that exchange simple semantic expressions, traces a lexicon-syntax coevolution through iterated communications and general learning mechanisms and implements a "bottom-up" syntax development, i.e., by iteration of local orders among lexical items consistent global word orders in simple declare sentences are formed. Based on this model, I show that local constraints on language processing and semantic structures cognized by individuals can lead to bias towards certain forms of word orders (e.g., SVO/SOV). After comparing the simulation results with the language data. I evaluate the simulation approach in linguistics research and point out some connections to the research in the linguistics department in CUHK.', 1301416200, 1301422500, 75, 60, 0, 'University of Hong Kong'),
(377, 441, 'Masao Ochi', 'The probe-goal system of Chomsky (2000,2001), where uninterpretable/unvalued features play an important role, is based almost exclusively on the properties of A-dependencies, but we can find in the recent literature some empirical evidence for extending this system to the domain of A-bar dependencies (e.g., Rizzi 2006 and Boskovic 2008). The main goal of this talk is to present additional empirical evidence for such an extension. I will do so by highlighting Chomsky''s (1973) proposal to the effect that multiple wh-questions have some sort of uniformity requirement. In particular, this requirement is not met if one of the wh-phrases is base-generated in the spec of the interrogative C). By examining multiple wh-questions involving varieties of ''why'', I will first show that this uniformity requirement is a valid cross-linguistic generalization. I will then argue that it follows rather naturally from the probe-goal system as currently conceived in the minimalist syntax.', 1303230600, 1303236900, 75, 60, NULL, 'Osaka University'),
(378, 442, 'Kelvin YUEN', 'In every thousand of newborns around the world, four to six of them born with permanent hearing loss in both ears. Up to 14% of children at school age were found to have mild hearing loss or above in at least one ear. Without early intervention on tailored fitting of hearing prothesis including hearing aids, frequency modulation (FM) systems, and cochlear implants, and intensive speech and language re/habilitation, children with hearing loss will experience significant difficulties related to speech and language, auditory processing, and academic and social-emotional development. The effectiveness o hearing prosthesis and speech and language re/habilitation gas to be evaluated continuously using age and performance-level appropriate instruments to guide re/habilitation planning. This seminar will outline testing procedures and instruments that are used to behaviorally assess sound perception and speech recognition abilities of hearing-impaired infant to school-aged children. Factors affecting, and procedures on determining the reliability of these assessment measures will be discussed.', 1303835400, 1303841700, 75, 60, 0, 'The Hong Kong Institute of Education'),
(379, 443, 'Bin LI', 'Our knowledge in the native language (L1) influences how we learn another language (L2). In L2 speech learning, phonological status and phonetic properties of sounds in both L1 and L2 play an important role. The current study investigates effects of these factors on perceiving Mandarin tones. Speakers from various L1 backgrounds including Chinese, Thai, English and French, participate in the identification and discrimination of a continuum of pitches. Effects of two phoneti cues i.e., pitch height an pitch slope, are examined, Siginificant differences are found in the degrees of sensitivity to the cues across L1 groups, while "language-universal" dependence on certain factor is also discovered.', 1299342600, 1299348900, 75, 60, NULL, 'City University of Hong Kong'),
(380, 444, 'Dr Hiroko Tanaka', 'As is well known, responses to turns containing initiating actions such as assessments, opinions, offers, invitations, and requests broadly fall into alternative types: affiliative responses, namely those which display support and endorsement of the affective or evaluative stance embodied in the prior action (e.g. agreements and acceptances), or disaffiliative responses, which do not include such displays (e.g. disagreements and rejections). Relatively little is known about the concrete structures of affiliative responses apart from the fact that they tend to be performed explicitly and without delay, and have a simple turn structure. This paper employs conversation analysis to explore further the lexico-syntactic resources regularly employed in constructing affiliative responses in Anglo-American English conversation in comparison with published findings for Japanese. Notwithstanding the vast differences between the syntactic structures of the two languages, the available data in English initially reveal a surprising similarity in the kinds of verbal resources used as regular, albeit atypical, features of the designs of unequivocal affiliative responses. At the same time, however, major restrictions come to light in the pervasive application of the resources freely used in Japanese, no doubt reflecting the limitations and possibilities afforded by English syntax. It can be seen that the verbal resources in the respective linguistic domains have evolved flexibly and ingeniously in ways that are concordant with the overarching syntactic structures of the host languages while simultaneously addressing the potentially universal interactional contingency of constructing affiliative responses.', 1384428600, 1384434000, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Essex'),
(381, 445, 'Dr Rik De Busser', 'In this talk, I use a discussion of the problem of bias in linguistic evidence gathering as a starting point for a model conceptualizing linguistic structure as a complex network.Bias has been a major theoretical concern in many fields of science, but in many linguistic subdisciplines it has curiously been overlooked. I will discuss evidence from the morphosyntactic analysis of two languages, Bunun and Dutch, to illustrate that the knowledge we acquire through descriptive analysis and other forms of inductive linguistic inquiry is a selective and often inaccurate representation of complex linguistic systems as they occur in the real world.In the second part of the talk, we will see how these observations, together with recent developments in construction grammar, allow us to rethink the old metaphor of language as a living organism. I will formulate a hypothetical model of linguistic structure in which grammar is not a set of rules, but a type of hierarchical complex system in an n-dimensional fitness landscape. I will discuss how such a model relates to current ideas of linguistic structure in functional grammar and construction grammar and what the implications of such an approach are for our ideas of how grammar works.', 1376231400, 1376235000, 76, 61, 0, 'Graduate Institute of Linguistics, National Chengchi University'),
(382, 446, 'Professor Dr. Martin Haspelmath', 'Referential effects on argument coding have been widely discussed for monotransitive constructions, especially in the guise of “differential object marking” (but also as “split ergativity” and “inverse voice”). By referential effects I mean situations where argument coding is conditioned by referential properties of the verbal arguments: animacy, person, definiteness, topicality, and the like. In ditransitive constructions, such referential effects are even more common than in monotransitive constructions, and they are prominent even in English (cf. I gave my brother the money / *I gave my brother it.) In this talk, I will discuss a broad range of referential effects in languages from around the world, and I will address two questions: First, how should such effects be described in a cross-linguistic perspective? What is the relationship between diverse chracaterizations such as “differential marking”, “split ditransitivity”, “hierarchical alignment”, “inverse voice”, and “person-case constraint”? Second, how should such effects be explained? Can we reconcile diverse explanation such as “ambiguity avoidance”, “competition for slots”, “harmonic alignment” and “coding economy”?', 1373461200, 1373464800, 76, 61, 0, 'Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology, Germany'),
(383, 447, 'Dr Ohkuma Tomoko', 'Fuji Xerox Communication Technology Laboratory (CTL) aims to develop technologies to extract valuable information from large scale text data. NLP team in CTL works with three kinds of text data. The first is sales daily reports input by sales persons on an SFA system. The second is micro blog texts and the last is clinical texts. This talk introduces NLP technologies and applications for these texts.', 1362925800, 1362886200, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Bern, Switzerland'),
(384, 448, 'Dr Yap Foong Ha', 'In this talk I will illustrate how hearsay evidential constructions sometimes extend from converbal and attributive uses into finite, stand-alone structures. Diachronic evidence and usage frequency data will be used to show how these insubordination processes were realized in two verb-final languages, namely, Korean and Japanese. Data for our analysis for Korean come from the UNICONC corpus and the Sejong corpus, and for Japanese from the Taikei Honbun database. We will also briefly discuss how non-verb final languages such as Cantonese (verb-medial) and Austronesian languages (often verb-initial) develop finite, stand-alone hearsay evidential constructions.', 1380018600, 1380022200, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of English, Hong Kong Polytechnic University'),
(385, 449, 'Dr Satoshi Sekine', 'I''m going to introduce the activities at Rakuten Institute of Technology, New York (RIT-NY). It is a research laboratory of Rakuten, a global e-commerce company. Many NLP, text mining and ontology related technologies are applied in order to make business impacts with the real data with real business needs. The research topics includes misclassified product detection, product attribute extraction, product-product matching, a new style product recommendation using NLP and statistics.', 1379066400, 1379070000, 76, 61, 0, 'New York University'),
(386, 450, 'Professor George van Driem', 'An historical account of scholarly thinking regarding linguistic phylogeny in eastern Eurasia will introduce the Trans-Himalayan linguistic phylum. Scholarly thinking regarding language relationships in eastern Eurasia has undergone a long process of transformation since the introduction of Tibeto-Burman theory in 1823. In the heyday of racism in scholarship, Social Darwinism coloured both language typology and the phylogenetic models of language relationship in eastern Eurasia. Its influential role in the perpetuation of the Indo-Chinese model is generally left untold. The legacy of this tumultuous period in Western scholarship still shapes the way that we view the ethnolinguistic composition of Asia today. Language typologists of yore sought to blur the distinction between biological ancestry and linguistic affinity, although prominent historical linguists time and again stressed the independence of language and race. The Trans-Himalayan model is presented along with the challenges which it presents to future research. Finally, with all the necessary caveats in place, a conjectural reconstruction of the ethnolinguistic prehistory of eastern Eurasia is briefly presented based on possible correlations between genes and languages.', 1383964200, 1383967800, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Bern, Switzerland'),
(387, 451, 'Professor Victor Friedman', 'Although contact with Turkish is commonly assumed to be the source of evidentiality in the Indo-European languages of the Balkans, and indeed, there are good arguments to support this claim, the overall picture in the Balkan languages is much more complicated than this simple statement. Macedonian has influenced Albanian, Albanian has influenced Balkan Romance, and Balkan Slavic has influenced Romani. In particular, the reinterpretation of optatives, conditionals, and interrogatives as evidentials have complex histories.My talk will discuss interplay between typological and areal explanations in these Balkan phenomena.', 1378733400, 1378737000, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Chicago'),
(388, 452, 'Henriëtte Daudey', 'Evidentiality and egophoricity are two sides of the same coin in Wadu Pumi. On the one hand, speakers report on things that they are involved in themselves (egophoric); on the other hand they report on the actions of others (evidential). There are three sets of evidential and egophoric markers in Wadu Pumi that occur in the same (post-verbal) slot and cannot be used together. Similar markers in related dialects have been analysed in various ways. Lu (1983:42) treats them as a single paradigm of past, present and future tense markers. Fu (1998:104) analyses them rather as perfective, progressive and prospective aspect markers. Ding (1998) does not treat them as one paradigm, but analyses the three different sets of markers as aspectual, evidential and modality markers respectively.This paper will discuss how the temporal, aspectual and modal notions interact with the egophoric evidential parameter in Wadu Pumi, and whether these three sets of markers can be analyzed as a single paradigm in or not.', 1374762600, 1374769800, 76, 61, 0, 'La Trobe University, Melbourne'),
(389, 453, 'Dr Uli Sauerland', 'It is presently debated whether clausal complementation is universally available across languages. In particular, historical linguists have proposed that instead of subordination/hypotaxis several ancient languages used coordination/parataxis to express propositional attitudes (Deutscher 2000 on Akkadian). We first show that synchronic evidence from Teiwa (Alor-Pantar) is essentially the same as Deutscher''s Old-Babylonian evidence with respect to propositional attitude expression, and that a paratactic analysis seems initially plausible for Teiwa. We then argue that, however, more specific tests show that Teiwa propositional attitudes are expressed by hypotaxis after all. Our result suggests that also for the ancient languages as paratactic hypotaxis must have been available though plausibly no direct evidence for it has been preserved. (based on joint work with Frantisek Kratochvil and Bart Hollebrandse)', 1373902200, 1373905800, 76, 61, 0, 'Centre for General Linguistics (ZAS), Berlin, Germany'),
(390, 454, 'Dr Uli Sauerland', 'The expression of the grammatical category Person exhibits a very skewed distribution. While some syncretism patterns occur frequently, many others occur not at all. What explains this distribution? I first argue that grammar-free accounts of language do not explain the skewed distribution of Person paradigms. Specifically the correlation between semantic and morphological similarity is too weak to explain the distribution fully. I then consider a class of grammatical models based on a universal set of person features and Paninian rule ordering. I show that such models are very restrictive, indeed so restrictive that none of them would allow the actual distribution. This failure is unsurprising since syncretism can also be due to accidental homophony. However, accidental homophony then makes it difficult to evaluate any morphological account of syncretism. To overcoming this problem, I argue that accidental homophony should exhibit a random distribution in the statistical sense. I show how we can then compute for different grammatical models the likelihood they assign to the actual distribution of Person patterns. Furthermore, I show that maximum likelihood modeling supports one specific model of the universal grammar of Person: a Paninian model with a specific set of universal person features that turn out to semantically motivated.', 1383838200, 1383841800, 76, 61, 0, 'Centre for General Linguistics (ZAS), Berlin, Germany'),
(391, 455, 'Lim Ni Eng', 'To me, sociolinguistics is the study of how language serves and is shaped by the social nature of human beings, and interactional sociolinguistics focuses on the details of how language users utilize linguistic resources in talk-in-interaction to communicate social actions. Stancetaking in conversation is one such social action, as it engages in (in)direct forms of social categorization and evaluation, attributes intentionality, affect, epistemic knowledge, agency to self and others, and lay claims to social and/or moral identities.However, traditional linguistics approaches have unfortunately tended to focus on the subjective dimensions of stancetaking, treating it from the monologic perspective of individual language users. In this seminar, I’ll focus on a common epistemic marker Wo Juede (i.e. “I think”) in Mandarin Chinese. Through detail analysis of audio/video data using conversation analytic methodology, I will demonstrate how speakers’ positioning of this ostensibly subjective stance in actual interaction is in fact inherently dialogic and intersubjective in nature. Furthermore, it is shown how the deployment of a stance can be interactionally consequential. My investigations into other common lexical bundles in conversation and TCU-continuations, have also shown speakers to be similarly oriented to the subjectivity of their interlocutors when performing acts of stancetaking.Using conversation analytic and ethnomethodological approach, it is argued that an adequate understanding of stancetaking cannot be based on a Saussurean model, where the semiotics of language is primarily viewed as an outward representation of an individual’s inner cognitive state. Stancetaking, in its natural environment, are oftentimes not the unilateral product of the individual’s psyche, but are collaboratively built to achieve interactional goals.', 1380880800, 1380884400, 76, 61, 0, 'PhD Candidate (ABD) in Applied Linguistics, UCLA'),
(392, 456, 'Dr Mark Seilhamer', 'In his seminal work Distinction: A Social Critique of the Judgment of Taste, Pierre Bourdieu demonstrates how the cultivation of taste serves to reproduce class differences. In this talk, I argue that class divisions are similarly being reproduced today based on proficiency in languages of wider communication – particularly English. After discussing the mechanisms by which identities of distinction (or any identities, for that matter) are produced in interaction, I will present interview data from a longitudinal multi-case study illustrating how this process of practices and performance indexing dominant ideologies plays out in Taiwanese society. The study’s multilingual Taiwanese participants repeatedly point out instances in which they have distinguished themselves from those around them through their use of and (relative) proficiency in English (and to a lesser degree, French). For these participants, images of themselves as more worldly and sophisticated than their peers started to be nurtured quite early in life through tuition classes and private tutoring, and from that point on, they continuously struggled to maintain these identities of distinction, often resorting to performativity to foreground their linguistic practices. These participants, however, viewed their differentiated status as somewhat precarious, for accompanying their repeated reports of attempting to stand out through English use was a frequently expressed anxiety about the fact that their English abilities alone might not continue to adequately differentiate them from others, particularly in the employment arena, as more and more Taiwanese gain English proficiency.', 1378288800, 1378292400, 76, 61, 0, 'Post-doctoral Fellow, Nanyang Technological University'),
(393, 457, 'Dr Ivan Panovic', 'In this talk, I will discuss some of the main threads of my long-term ethnographic research conducted in Cairo. The Egyptian sociolinguistic setting is usually defined in terms of a diglossic continuum, the main poles of which are Modern Standard Arabic (MSA) and Egyptian Colloquial Arabic (ECA). It is, however, being significantly reconfigured by the increasing socio-economic importance of English, a linguistic variety with a strong stratifying force due to its high value on the contemporary Egyptian neo-liberal (linguistic) market.While the hegemonic ideological projection postulates writing as the domain of MSA, the actual literacy practices are anything but uniform. Non-literary, vernacular, texts, in particular, more often than not tend to result from a range of motivated, locally meaningful – metrolingual and translingual – acts of writing in which people draw on a variety of available resources. The inventory of these resources contains re-combinations of three linguistic varieties (MSA, ECA and English) and two scripts (Arabic and Roman), thus potentially becoming sixfold - which moves us beyond the simplistic dualism implied in the notion of diglossia.The analysis of linguistic details is conducted with reference to a broader socio cultural context and local language ideologies surrounding this dynamic, changing and diversified character of writing practices in present day Egypt. I provide illustrative examples from a number of different texts and domains of writing, including books, Wikipedia Masry (Wikipedia written in Egyptian Arabic), Twitter, Facebook, advertisements, online campaigns for political and social causes, graffiti, revolutionary signs, placards and banners. I discuss these contemporary literacy practices in terms of heteroglossic indexing of contesting identity positions, which is understood as an activity informed by different patterns of sociolinguistic consumption and enacted in what I term “spaces of sociolinguistic freedom”.', 1365082200, 1365085800, 76, 61, 0, 'Andrew W Mellon Postdoctoral Fellow in Arabic Sociolinguistics'),
(394, 458, 'Dr Gerald Stell', 'The theme of acculturation has risen to prominence in public discourses – where it tends to be broadly referred to as ‘integration’. In a privileged position to impact on policy-making in multiethnic societies, acculturation research has suffered from methodological limitations, often pointed out at as an excessive reliance on second-hand quantitative data collected by means of questionnaires. Such data have been criticized for providing a simplified picture of acculturation trends without accounting for unquantifiable manifestations of emergent cultural identities promoted by interethnic contact. On the basis of quantitative and qualitative studies of language variation across the Black/White divide in the United States, I take the view that interactional sociolinguistic data form adequate first-hand data for quantitatively and qualitatively reconstructing collective acculturation trends, namely ‘assimilation’ (whereby the original cultural identity is relinquished in favour of the dominant cultural identity), ‘integration’ (whereby the original cultural identity and the dominant cultural identity are jointly held), and ‘separation’ (whereby the original cultural identity is retained to the exclusion of any other cultural identity). On the basis of a semi-experimentally set up interaction involving Namibian Whites and Namibian Coloureds, I will present the potential and limits of concepts developed in interactional sociolinguistics, namely ‘convergence’, ‘divergence’ and ‘maintenance’, for reconstructing social dynamics governing interethnic contact and their correlation with acculturation trends. This practical demonstration precedes an outline of research projects on interethnic interaction which I wish to undertake in ethnically mixed school environments in two distinct urban contexts, namely Cape Town and Singapore. I will finally launch a discussion with the audience about whether the linguistic predictions which can be made with regard to interethnic acculturation trends in Cape Town’s school environment can also be made for Singapore.', 1359972000, 1359975600, 76, 61, 0, 'Research Fellow, National Research Foundation, Flanders/Vrije Universiteit Brussel'),
(395, 459, 'Dr Wing Li WU', 'In this talk, experimental findings on two aspects of Cantonese prosody, namely the tonal characteristics of sentence-final particles (SFPs) as a special case of the interaction between tone and intonation, and the acoustic correlates of prosodic focus will be presented.SFPs have functions similar to intonation, and they are usually described as having lexical tones similar to other syllables in the language. But whether their surface fundamental frequency (F0) contours are purely from lexical tones or a combination of tone and intonation has not been fully shown experimentally. Detailed analyses of ten Cantonese SFPs in the present study show that most of these SFPs are very similar to the lexical tones in terms of F0 contours, but differences can be seen in sentences with question SFPs, suggesting that the Cantonese SFPs have underlying tonal targets just like those of lexical tones, but they also carry intonational meanings by modification of the lexical tonal contours.Recent research shows that Beijing Mandarin marks focus not only by on-focus prosodic expansion but also by post-focus compression of pitch range and intensity (PFC), but PFC is absent in Taiwanese and Taiwan Mandarin. This finding highlights the non-universality of PFC and raises questions about its origin. The present study investigates the acoustic correlates of prosodic focus in Cantonese by Hong Kong speakers, and those in English and Cantonese by bilingual speakers born and raised in Southern England. PFC, which occurs in English, is not found in the Cantonese of both groups of speakers, but out of the fifteen bilinguals tested, only one-third show PFC in all their English test sentences, suggesting that PFC is hard to transmit across languages through bilingualism.', 1364481000, 1364484600, 76, 61, 0, 'Teaching Fellow, Department of Chinese and Bilingual Studies, The Hong Kong Polytechnic University'),
(396, 460, 'Dr Rebecca Dridan', 'Statistical parsers based on probabilistic context free grammars (PCFGs) have dominated much computational parsing research over the last few decades, with these parsers now able to automatically recreate the phrase structure trees of the Penn Treebank with quite acceptable accuracy. However, parsers that aim to produce a more complex linguistic analysis have lagged behind in terms of speed and robustness to unseen text because the mathematical tricks used for handling PCFGs can''t always be applied when we model more interdependencies between parts of an utterance. In this talk, I will describe some of my research aimed at improving the efficiency and robustness of a parser that uses Head-Driven Phrase Structure Grammars (HPSG), with a focus on supertags, detailed lexical descriptions that provide a means to introduce complex linguistic information in a form amenable to statistical processing.Supertags were first used in the context of Lexical Tree Adjoining Grammar (LTAG) as a means of “almost parsing”. In HPSG, the form of these supertags is not as obvious as in the original work, and my research has focussed on what linguistic information they should represent, both from the point of view of what can be predicted, but also what distinctions will lead to better analysis by the parser.', 1363357800, 1363361400, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of Informatics, University of Oslo'),
(397, 461, 'Professor Paul Drew', 'Conversation analysis (CA) has contributed to a transformation in linguistics in recent years, focusing enquiry on language use instead of abstracted linguistic structures; and on action, instead of meaning. And as a form of social linguistics, CA has contributed also to bringing linguistic analysis to bear on interaction in social settings. I’ll give an overview, a sketch, of what we’re trying to achieve in CA, focusing especially on the use of language in social action. And I will illustrate the recent applications of CA to understanding medical interactions, in research that suggests how very much talk matters in clinical settings.', 1361289600, 1361295000, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Loughborough, UK'),
(398, 462, 'Dr. Francis Wong', 'Speech perception can be thought of as a process that converts sounds into meanings. It is a process that involves various parts of the brain. On the input side, speech sounds are concrete as their acoustic properties can be described in physical terms (e.g. in terms of power or frequency analyses etc.). Whereas on the output side, the meanings of spoken utterances are abstract in a way that the semantic properties of words have little association with how the words are pronounced (e.g. “leg” and “lake” sound alike but have no commonality in meanings, whereas “leg” and “foot” are semantic associates even though they sound very differently).In this talk, I will present a series of studies to look at such hierarchical organisation, from concrete to abstract, of the hearing brain. I will first present neuroanatomical findings from an experiment in which we identified white matter pathways that mediate performance in a sound-to-word learning programme. This has led us to develop a brain model regarding how speech is processed. I will then talk about two experiments in which we aim to reveal mental representations of sounds from fMRI data, findings from which will shed lights on how different parts of the brain work together to support speech perception.', 1372759200, 1372762800, 76, 61, 0, 'Post-doctoral Fellow, Nanyang Technological University'),
(399, 463, 'Dr. Luca Onnis', 'One of the central goals in linguistics is to understand how humans learn and use language. To this purpose, three factors are to be identified: (a) the nature of the input experienced by the learner (both linguistic and extra-linguistic), (b) the types of computations learners make in analyzing the input, and (c) the biases and constraints that operate on these computational processes. The interaction of these three factors is considered fundamental to understanding how language knowledge rapidly emerges in children, as well as how language processes differ in childhood and adulthood. In this talk I will present a particular case of interaction between input and computations that generates constraints on later learning.In empirical studies carried out with infants and adults I document how experiencing a language with a given word order structure (head-initial versus head-final) can modify the computations that are carried out on novel language-like structures. I show that infants quickly become attuned to the most informative sequential regularities of their native language in the first years of life. This in turn may support the fast discovery of word order and phrase structure – a fundamental milestone in language acquisition. Such parsing biases reflect general language-specific statistical regularities latent in large corpora. These biases can be shown to persist in adult learners, potentially explaining some of the difficulties involved in learning a novel language with different word order structure.Adult brains however retain a large plasticity potential. Contrary to strong assumptions of critical periods in development, research in cognitive neuroscience now supports the idea of a permanently plastic brain. An exciting open question is thus whether training interventions can be designed that modify the learners’ entrenched experience by retuning learning mechanisms to the regularities of a novel language. Evidence of cognitive modifiability and plasticity in adults could promote new approaches to learning and teaching languages. Together, my behavioral and computational results shed light on experience-driven constraints on learning and plasticity in language acquisition.', 1364896800, 1364900400, 76, 61, 0, 'Center for Second Language Studies, University of Hawaii'),
(400, 464, 'Dr. Manami Sato', 'An increasing body of empirical work has revealed that language comprehenders mentally simulate visual features of scenes they hear or read about (Barsalou, 1999; Glenberg & Kaschak, 2002; Zwaan et al., 2002). Moreover, recent research shows that these simulations adopt a particular perspective (Borghi, Glenberg, & Kaschak, 2004; Brunyé, Ditman, Mahoney, Augustyn, & Taylor, 2009). While much has been clarified regarding what kinds of things and from what perspective people mentally simulate in response to language, there has been little exploration of mental simulation’s processing mechanisms, of its functional role, or of what factors are crucial in influencing it. In my talk, I will discuss these unexplored but interesting questions, including how early in a sentence simulation begins, how it changes as a sentence unfolds, whether simulation is necessary for understanding meaning correctly, what determines which perspective people simulate a scene from, and how culture influences the way people simulate meaning.', 1359367200, 1359370800, 76, 61, 0, 'Project Center for Brain Science of Language and Cognition, Department of Graduate School of Education, Hiroshima University, Japan.'),
(401, 465, 'Professor Suzanne Romaine', 'My talk examines the politics of policies promoting multilingualism in the European Union (EU), specifically in light of the recently released European Union Civil Society Platform on Multilingualism. As the most far-reaching and ambitious policy document issued by the European Commission, the Platform warrants close scrutiny at a significant moment when multilingualism seemed poised to become a policy field in its own right. This is an extremely important move given the fact that language policy has been politically untouchable at inter-governmental level and there is to date no coherent legally binding language policy either at the level of EU institutions or in member-states. I raise the question of whether the situation is likely to change in response to the Platform at a time when public support for European integration has been waning and the economic crisis surrounding the euro poses a new threat to the EU. The current austerity climate makes multilingual policy an easy target for budget cuts as evidenced in the European Parliament’s recent removal of the requirement to translate its plenary sessions into all 23 official languages.', 1358506800, 1358512200, 76, 61, 0, 'Merton Professor of English Language, University of OxfordToh Puan Mahani Idris Daim (TPMID) Chair Professor, NTU'),
(402, 466, 'Professor Chunshen Zhu', 'In Tai Chi, one of the most philosophic and intellectual forms of Chinese martial arts, pushing hands as a sparring technique is practiced between two people with hands remaining in a dynamic, budiu buding (‘neither separating nor confronting’) contact. Following the thought-provoking cross-semiotic analogy of translation as kung fu (John Minford, 1997), I shall here characterize translation, which inevitably brings two languages into intimate contact if not violent combat, more specifically as ‘pushing hands’ between the source and the target language driven by each other’s ‘articulate energy’ (Donald Davie, 1955). The process is initiated by an advancing flow of energy from the source language which is instantiated, realized, and confined in a finite ‘source text’. In response to this ‘foreign’ energy, the target language, through the agency of a translator, mobilizes its articulate potential to ensure a budiu buding state of contact, so as to follow the flow of the oncoming energy and to accommodate, absorb, and contain it in the formulation of a new text. We will then argue that the flexibility and agility of the articulate energy a language demonstrates in this game of pushing hands comes from its textual function of information structuring, which is sustained by its lexicogrammatical system as ‘a theory of human experience’ (M.A.K. Halliday, 1999). As such, on a micro level, following the movement of information focus as the ‘contact point’ may help maintain a budiu buding mode of translation to capture, accommodate, and contain the oncoming energy as the source text unfolds, and redirect it into an emerging target text.', 1353074400, 1353078000, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of Chinese, Translation and Linguistics, City University of Hong Kong'),
(403, 467, 'Professor Chunshen Zhu', 'In our talk, we will present an on-line platform (the Platform) specifically designed for an accountability-driven teaching and (self-)learning mode of translation and bilingual writing, which has the potential of forming an inter-institutional and international network of collaboration to optimize teaching resources. In particular, we will address the following issues in the construction of the Platform: 1) corpora-construction; 2) a system of glossed ‘tag-words’ to identify and describe textual and cultural phenomena for data-annotation; 3) the rigour of data annotation, exercises design and topical boards composition; and 4) an electronic programme design to interconnect text annotations, exercises and topical boards via the tag-word system for ease of cross-modular navigation in actual teaching and (self-) learning.The rationale of the design of the Platform and the accountability-driven mode of bilingual and translation education it embodies is that translation is not merely an operation of linguistic transfer between two languages but one of re-presentation of the linguistically formulated information presented in the source text as it unfolds in the real life context. Hence, to ensure the pedagogical quality of bilingual and translation education and to increase its efficiency, the relationship between linguistic form, communicative function and textual effect has to be accounted for in teaching with a research-informed rigour rather than in an impressionistic manner.The presentation will therefore demonstrate the operation of a tag-word led modus operandi used in our data annotation, which is theoretically informed by text-linguistics, systemic-functional linguistics, stylistics, and discourse studies, among others.', 1353063600, 1353067200, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of Chinese, Translation and Linguistics, City University of Hong Kong'),
(404, 468, 'Dr Yuanyuan Mu', 'In our talk, we will present an on-line platform (the Platform) specifically designed for an accountability-driven teaching and (self-)learning mode of translation and bilingual writing, which has the potential of forming an inter-institutional and international network of collaboration to optimize teaching resources. In particular, we will address the following issues in the construction of the Platform: 1) corpora-construction; 2) a system of glossed ‘tag-words’ to identify and describe textual and cultural phenomena for data-annotation; 3) the rigour of data annotation, exercises design and topical boards composition; and 4) an electronic programme design to interconnect text annotations, exercises and topical boards via the tag-word system for ease of cross-modular navigation in actual teaching and (self-) learning.The rationale of the design of the Platform and the accountability-driven mode of bilingual and translation education it embodies is that translation is not merely an operation of linguistic transfer between two languages but one of re-presentation of the linguistically formulated information presented in the source text as it unfolds in the real life context. Hence, to ensure the pedagogical quality of bilingual and translation education and to increase its efficiency, the relationship between linguistic form, communicative function and textual effect has to be accounted for in teaching with a research-informed rigour rather than in an impressionistic manner.The presentation will therefore demonstrate the operation of a tag-word led modus operandi used in our data annotation, which is theoretically informed by text-linguistics, systemic-functional linguistics, stylistics, and discourse studies, among others.', 1353063600, 1353067200, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of Chinese, Translation and Linguistics, City University of Hong Kong'),
(405, 469, 'Dr. Dipika Mukherjee', 'In Malaysia, language policies have changed over time due to political and economic developments in the country and also due to globalisation. Malaysia is a multi-ethnic, multilingual country and the population of Malaysia comprises three major ethnic groups (Bumiputera, Chinese and Indians) and currently, Malaysia is trying hard to maintain a unified nation through a national language despite the primacy of the English language in a globalising world. In Malaysia, however, religious affiliation and the subsequent benefits of that affiliation, appear to be a strong determinator of the language a community is likely to shift to. This phenomenon is unique in sociolinguistic studies. Drawing on data from Language Shifts Among Malaysian Minorities as Effects Of National Language Planning: Speaking in Many Tongues, this talk will investigate some trends in the language variation within the Klang Valley.Socioeconomic considerations, nation-building, modernization and globalisation, are all central parameters for language planning goals in many Asian nations, including China. As a comparison to the Malaysian case, the curious robustness of the Shanghai dialect in Shanghai, in the face of a strong national language policy, is an interesting phenomenon (especially in the media). By understanding the nature of the complementary relationship between Putonghua and the Shanghai dialect, a clear picture of language ability and language use in China’s fast-expanding economic capital can be ascertained.The duality of language expansion and language survival in these two Asian cities, both with strong language policies in place, is an interesting sociolinguistic contrast.', 1355221800, 1355225400, 76, 61, 0, 'Affiliated Fellow, International Institute of Asian Studies, Leiden, The Netherlands'),
(406, 470, 'Professor Bao Zhiming', 'Language can be understood as a complex adaptive system that responds to its environment. How it does this is a matter of intense research in linguistics. In this talk, I outline my view of this process. The basic idea I would like to sketch is this. The grammar of a contact language is the grammar of the substrate language filtered through the grammar of the lexifier language. I will illustrate this idea with salient grammatical features of Singapore English. Specifically, I discuss the way English, Chinese and Singapore English talk about time and action, and show that the Singapore English time talk is the Chinese talk carried out through English words.', 1328965200, 1328968800, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of English Language and Literature, National University of Singapore'),
(407, 471, 'Professor Dr. H. C. Juliane House', 'In this lecture I will look at the controversy about the current status of English in the world. I will consider the question of whether the dominant role of English as a global lingua franca must needs be seen as a menace to other languages and multilingualism and the profession of translation and interpreting, or whether there may be some justification for considering the omnipresent availability of English as a default means of communication as an opportunity for better understanding and intercultural communication. I will argue for a compromise position: neither bedevilling global English nor welcoming it uncritically and naively. I will support this stance from a number of different perspectives drawing on my own work on English as a lingua franca and translation.', 1351701000, 1351704600, 76, 61, 0, 'Hamburg University and Hellenic American University'),
(408, 472, 'Professor Dr. Gerhard Leitner', 'Conceptualizations (or “models”) of English is a prominent theme in studies of English in the world today. The core/periphery model (Quirk), the Three Circles (Kachru) and the Dynamic model (Schneider) have all been widely discussed and have shown their usefulness in descriptive studies of varieties of English and in applied linguistics. Less well-known is the Habitat model (Leitner 2004a/b). Though often discussed as if they covered the same ground, these conceptualizations have emerged at different periods of time and describe different features of English. The Habitat model is perhaps the most demanding as it embeds English in the wider spectrum of languages and societies and takes the reciprocity of language contact (more) seriously. It integrates the duality of changes – those towards greater homogeneity at the international level and those towards diversity at the national level. Centripetal and centrifugal forces co-exist and are most visible in the registers or discourses at the lower and higher end of communication. Noteworthy is also the shift in exo-normative orientation from British towards American English.Such conceptualizations have their uses beyond the description of English around the world. The State curricula of English in Germany, to take one example of many, reflect this reality and call for a diversity of teaching materials that enables students to acquire a competency in pluricentric English. That shift naturally highlights the acquisition of intercultural competencies that transfer between different foreign languages. This talk will survey the field and take a look at its translation into the education domain.', 1349884800, 1349888400, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of English, Free University Berlin, Germany'),
(409, 473, 'Dr Mary Dalrymple', 'Yag Dii (Niger-Congo/Adamawa-Ubangi) has a complicated pronominal system, with four series of pronouns whose distribution is determined by the type of clause in which they appear (Bohnhoff 1986, 2010). One series exhibits an extreme degree of long-distance binding: it must appear as the subject of a subordinate clause which is itself embedded within a separate syntactically-defined subordinate domain, with the result that it must be at least two clauses removed from its antecedent. The distribution of Yag Dii pronouns is difficult to capture by reference to standard noncoreference domains and the standard primitives of binding theory. Furthermore, the very long-distance anaphor seems to violate the Locality Condition (Dalrymple 1991), which states that "constraints on anaphoric binding are local; binding constraints never refer exclusively to nonlocal elements". Taking into account binding constraints on the full range of Yag Dii pronouns, binding patterns can be defined in a relatively straightforward way in terms of local specifications associated with particular domains and with subjects of particular types of clauses.', 1348232400, 1348236000, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Oxford');
