(410, 474, 'Dr Petter Haugereid', 'In this talk I will present the research I have conducted as a postdoc at LMS. The talk consists of two parts. The first part is about the effort to expand the Japanese English Machine Translation system Jaen. Jaen is a rule-based MT system, using semantic transfer rules. In my postdoc I have developed a method for automatic extraction of semantic transfer rules from parallel corpora. This has helped to increase the coverage the system as well as the quality of the translations.The second part of the talk is about a grammar design accommodating incremental processing. It is generally accepted in the psycholinguistic literature that utterances are processed word by word. Incremental processing has been accommodated by syntactic theories like GB/Minimalism and Combinatory Categorial Grammar by adapting the constituent structures to a right- or left-branching parse tree. I will show how incremental processing can be accounted for in a framework like HPSG by "detaching" the constituent structure from the (left-branching) parse tree and retaining a conventional constituent structure.', 1346418000, 1346421600, 76, 61, 0, 'Linguistics and Multilingual Studies, Nanyang Technological University'),
(411, 475, 'Professor Peter K Austin', 'The history of the indigenous languages of eastern Australia since first colonial contact in 1788 has been one of loss and disappearance, with radical reductions in speaker numbers to the point of extinguishment for many of the languages spoken in Victoria, New South Wales and eastern South Australia. For example, the Gamilaraay language of northern New South Wales went from the first language of a large community of speakers in the 1850’s (as documented by the missionary William Ridley) to the private language of old people in the 1930’s (documented by anthropologist Norman Tindale) to the last fluent speaker, recorded in the 1950’s by Stephen Wurm. Similar stories can be told in other areas, eg. the Diyari language from north-east South Australia had around 1,000 speakers in 1914 (when Lutheran missionaries were using it in schools and the church) to just 12 speakers when I started working on it in 1975. However, the last 10 years have seen a remarkable turn around in eastern Australia with moves to revitalise a number of languages and reintroduce them through various means, including school programmes. I will explore several case studies that I have been involved in first-hand to look critically at the motivations, methods and outcomes of these language revitalization efforts.', 1344960000, 1344963600, 76, 61, 0, 'School of Oriental and African Studies'),
(412, 476, 'Dr Don Bysouth', 'During therapy sessions clients and therapists collaboratively negotiate and produce in talk the issues that will be the focus of therapeutic attention. In many cases the talk concerns problems clients have experienced with third parties, involving accounts of various acts of deception and lying.Given that these may figure as matters of some potential therapeutic concern for the clients, and that therapists routinely cannot check the veracity of such accounts beyond the talk in session, how do therapists accept or reject various accounts pertaining to lying and deception provided by clients while maintaining therapeutic rapport? In this paper we examine data drawn from audio recordings of therapy sessions in which clients engaged in psychotherapy produce accounts pertaining to lying and deception. We examine how therapist challenges to such accounts can be constructed to preserve the therapeutic alliance.We provide a detailed sequential analysis (e.g., Schegloff, 2007) of sequences in which various acts of lying and deception are produced in client accounts, and how these may (or may not) be formulated by a therapist as morally problematic, potentially inaccurate, or indeed symptomatic of underlying psychiatric pathology. In addition we also employ a taxonomic analytic approach (e.g., Bilmes, 2009) to examine how something that counts as a “lie” (for example) can be rendered by interactants in therapy as something less morally problematic which might serve to attenuate possible therapist-client conflicts.', 1342454400, 1342458000, 76, 61, 0, 'Osaka University and Kansai University'),
(413, 477, 'Dr Keiko Ikeda', 'During therapy sessions clients and therapists collaboratively negotiate and produce in talk the issues that will be the focus of therapeutic attention. In many cases the talk concerns problems clients have experienced with third parties, involving accounts of various acts of deception and lying.Given that these may figure as matters of some potential therapeutic concern for the clients, and that therapists routinely cannot check the veracity of such accounts beyond the talk in session, how do therapists accept or reject various accounts pertaining to lying and deception provided by clients while maintaining therapeutic rapport? In this paper we examine data drawn from audio recordings of therapy sessions in which clients engaged in psychotherapy produce accounts pertaining to lying and deception. We examine how therapist challenges to such accounts can be constructed to preserve the therapeutic alliance.We provide a detailed sequential analysis (e.g., Schegloff, 2007) of sequences in which various acts of lying and deception are produced in client accounts, and how these may (or may not) be formulated by a therapist as morally problematic, potentially inaccurate, or indeed symptomatic of underlying psychiatric pathology. In addition we also employ a taxonomic analytic approach (e.g., Bilmes, 2009) to examine how something that counts as a “lie” (for example) can be rendered by interactants in therapy as something less morally problematic which might serve to attenuate possible therapist-client conflicts.', 1342454400, 1342458000, 76, 61, 0, 'Osaka University and Kansai University'),
(414, 478, 'Dr Amandine Michelas', 'Spoken utterances are parsed into prosodic units (phrasing), which have been shown to play an important role in both speech production and perception. The number of these units and the type of phonetic/phonological markers that cue their boundaries are language dependant. Theories about French intonation generally agree on the existence of two levels of phrasing: the accentual phrase and the intonation phrase. In this talk, I will provide evidence for the existence of an additional level of phrasing ranked between these two units in French. In the first part of the talk, I will characterize the phonetic and phonological properties of the intermediate phrase (ip) and explain why this additional level of phrasing is necessary to fully account for French prosody. I will show that the right boundary of the ip is recruited for demarcative functions at the level of both syntactic and pragmatic constituency. Secondly, I will present analyses conducted in perception, showing that the intermediate phrase right boundary is used early in the syntactic processing of spoken utterances. French listeners are able to use phonetic and phonological markers at intermediate phrase boundaries to build expectations about the syntactic structure of upcoming phrases. A separate analysis of different types of acoustic cues allows us to demonstrate that both tonal and durational markers seem to be necessary to exploit ip-boundaries in syntactic processing. I will discuss these findings in light of existing proposals describing French prosodic structure and current models of speech processing.', 1339776000, 1339779600, 76, 61, 0, 'Erasmus Mundus Multi'),
(415, 479, 'Dr Geoffrey Benjamin', 'It is relatively easy to transcribe Temiar (a Mon-Khmer language of Peninsular Malaysia) in a phonemically responsible manner for practical purposes, including publication. However, the author has found it surprisingly difficult to develop a satisfactory transcription for the special requirements of linguistic analysis. If ‘phonemic’ is taken to mean ‘not wholly determined’, any transcription that accordingly omits all the wholly determined vowels will seriously misrepresent the syllabic structure and rhythm of the language, as well being difficult to read.If, on the other hand, all of the wholly determined vowels are represented in the orthography, at least three further problems arise: (i) the initial consonantal clusters of sesquisyllables are misrepresented; (ii) it becomes difficult to indicate the difference between a wholly determined vowel and the same vowel occurring non-determinedly (phonemically) in the same position; (iii) the phonological differences between lexical words and prosodic words (generated by the frequent presence of proclitics) need special orthographic treatment. The seminar will present the provisional orthography worked out by the author, in the hope that it may stimulate advice on how to proceed further.', 1337961600, 1337965200, 76, 61, 0, 'Institute of Southeast Asian Studies (ISEAS)'),
(416, 480, 'Professor William Wang Shi-Yuan', '', 1334332800, 1334338200, 76, 61, 0, 'The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(417, 481, 'Amos Teo', 'In this talk, I will be looking at the semantic and pragmatic functions of two enclitics ye and no in Sumi, a Tibeto-Burman language of Nagaland. The enclitic no typically marks actors in transitive clauses that display a high degree of agentivity, i.e. volitionality and purpose, while the enclitic ye typically marks actors in transitive clauses that display a low degree of agentivity. In addition to these functions, no can mark contrastive focus on an argument, while ye can mark the topic of a non-transitive clause, placing contrastive focus on the predicate. However, it will be shown that it is not always easy to tease apart the semantic and pragmatic functions of these two markers. An analysis of no and ye is complicated by the fact that both markers (or arguably, homophonous markers with the same pragmatic functions) can occur with non-core arguments.', 1349193600, 1349197200, 76, 61, 0, 'Visiting Research Fellow, Australian National University'),
(418, 482, 'Professor Randy LaPolla', 'In this presentation, Prof. LaPolla will critically discuss and contrast some of the different conceptualisations of transitivity that have been presented in the literature, and argue that transitivity as a morphosyntactic phenomenon and effectiveness of an event as a semantic concept should be separated in discussions of transitivity. He will also argue that, like many other aspects of grammar, transitivity should be seen as a constructional phenomenon, and so each construction in a language needs to be examined separately, in natural contexts in terms of transitivity and so-called argument subcategorisation.', 1343903400, 1343908800, 76, 61, 0, 'La Trobe University'),
(419, 483, 'Dr Cheryl Frenck-Mestre', 'Theories abound as concerns the acquisition of a “second” language, i.e. a language that is acquired in either a natural or scholastic setting some time after early childhood. For some, grammatical processing is qualitatively different in a second and native language (Shallow processing hypothesis: Clahsen & Felser 2006); whereas for others, the fundamental mechanisms of L1 and L2 grammatical processing are the same (Dekdtspotter, Schwartz & Sprouse 2006; Herschensohn 2000; Hopp 2007; Schwartz & Sprouse 1996), with processing differences being attributable to factors such as reduced automaticity (slowness) of L2 processing (Frenck-Mestre 2002; 2005), the influence of L1 properties (Prévost & White 2000; Foucart & Frenck-Mestre 2011, 2012; Frenck-Mestre et al. 1997; Hopp, 2007) and limited computational resources (McDonald 2006). In the present talk we will show that the adult learner indeed goes through developmental stages in the acquisition of the target grammar, which can be tracked via the neural response to grammatical and ungrammatical structures. We will show that during early stages of L2 acquisition, the automatic neural response elicited during online syntactic processing is qualitatively different than that found for either more advanced learners or native speakers. At more advanced stages of learning coupled with immersion however, the differences in the neural response observed between native and non-native speakers during syntactic processing are quantitative rather than qualitative in nature. We will argue from these data that, indeed, full acquisition of grammatical competence is possible even for languages learned “late” in life, while not undermining the various factors that impinge upon processing capacity.', 1327075200, 1327078800, 76, 61, 0, 'Centre National de Recherche, Scientifique Universités d’Aix-Marseille'),
(420, 484, 'Professor Paul Kay', 'We examined the influence of verbal color categories on color appearance through two sets of experiments. In one, we measured the effects of color differences on perceptual grouping for hues that spanned the blue‐green boundary, to test whether chromatic differences across the boundary were perceptually exaggerated. The tendency to group showed little categorical bias. In a second case, we analyzed results from two prior studies of hue scaling of chromatic stimuli to test whether color appearance changed more rapidly around the blue‐green boundary. In this task observers tended to show much stronger categorical effects. The differences between these tasks could arise either because different signals mediate color grouping and color appearance, or because linguistic categories might differentially intrude on the response to color and/or on the perception of color. Our results suggest that the interaction between language and color processing may be highly dependent on the specific task and cognitive demands and strategies of the observer. They also highlight pronounced individual differences in the tendency to exhibit categorical responses.', 1324303200, 1324306800, 76, 61, 0, 'Emeritus Professor of LinguisticsUniversity of California, Berkeley and Standford University'),
(421, 485, 'Associate Professor Umarani Pappuswamy', 'Though India is one of the world''s most diverse countries in linguistic terms, focused discussion on issues of language endangerment has only recently come into focus. In this talk, I will focus on the following issues relating to the endangered languages in India: (a) the definition of endangered languages; (b) their status; (c) the linguistic, social and political factors contributing to their retention or attrition; and (d) the role of government, universities and other organizations in promoting and preserving these languages. I conclude by summarizing some of the main challenges that face efforts to document endangered languages in India.', 1315760400, 1315764000, 76, 61, 0, 'North-Eastern Hill University, Shillong, India'),
(422, 486, 'Prof Anthony Liddicoat', 'Technology has widened the possibilities for interaction between native speakers and non-native speakers by removing the need for geographic proximity. Online dyadic text chat in particular provides non-native speakers with opportunities for spontaneous free conversation with expert speakers other than the language teacher in an online one-to-one out-of-class setting. In these online textual conversations, non-native speakers of Italian generally have equal status with native speakers as interaction managers, including the regular initiation of repair sequences on unknown lexicon in native speakers’ talk (Tudini, 2007). However, there is evidence that both they and their online native speaker partners assume that one of native speakers’ fundamental roles is to initiate and complete repair of non-target utterances in language learners’ online talk, even where these do not cause problems of understanding. This paper will examine instances in which learners of Italian interact with native speakers using web-based chat. In these interactions, even though their purpose is social interaction, there are two salient identities for non-native speakers: language user and language learner (c.f. Kern & Liddicoat, 2008) and these identities are both potentially co-present at all moments of the interaction. The presence of these identities invokes complementary/contrasting identities for the native speaker, in this case language user and language teacher. At various points in these interactions, participants move between these identities and native speakers take on a didactic role through acts of correction, explanation and evaluation of the non-native speakers’ performance. In the performance of such acts, the identity of the native speaker becomes a resource for the exercise of power in the interaction making manifest Davies’ (1991, p. 167) observation that the distinction between native speakers and non-native speakers is “at bottom one of confidence and identity”. This paper will examine how these issues of confidence and identity play out in the corpus of chat interactions. The didactic voice of the native speaker, and the non-native speakers’ orientations to it, can be understood as interactional expressions at the micro-level of the power of the native speaker.', 1319212800, 1319218200, 76, 61, 0, 'University of South Australia'),
(423, 487, 'Dr Enza Tudini', 'Technology has widened the possibilities for interaction between native speakers and non-native speakers by removing the need for geographic proximity. Online dyadic text chat in particular provides non-native speakers with opportunities for spontaneous free conversation with expert speakers other than the language teacher in an online one-to-one out-of-class setting. In these online textual conversations, non-native speakers of Italian generally have equal status with native speakers as interaction managers, including the regular initiation of repair sequences on unknown lexicon in native speakers’ talk (Tudini, 2007). However, there is evidence that both they and their online native speaker partners assume that one of native speakers’ fundamental roles is to initiate and complete repair of non-target utterances in language learners’ online talk, even where these do not cause problems of understanding. This paper will examine instances in which learners of Italian interact with native speakers using web-based chat. In these interactions, even though their purpose is social interaction, there are two salient identities for non-native speakers: language user and language learner (c.f. Kern & Liddicoat, 2008) and these identities are both potentially co-present at all moments of the interaction. The presence of these identities invokes complementary/contrasting identities for the native speaker, in this case language user and language teacher. At various points in these interactions, participants move between these identities and native speakers take on a didactic role through acts of correction, explanation and evaluation of the non-native speakers’ performance. In the performance of such acts, the identity of the native speaker becomes a resource for the exercise of power in the interaction making manifest Davies’ (1991, p. 167) observation that the distinction between native speakers and non-native speakers is “at bottom one of confidence and identity”. This paper will examine how these issues of confidence and identity play out in the corpus of chat interactions. The didactic voice of the native speaker, and the non-native speakers’ orientations to it, can be understood as interactional expressions at the micro-level of the power of the native speaker.', 1319212800, 1319218200, 76, 61, 0, 'University of South Australia'),
(424, 488, 'Dr Bharath Chandrasekaran', 'Auditory learning is an engagement property of a distributed network consisting of subcortical and cortical structures working in cohesion. The operational specifics of auditory learning cannot be understood by exclusively cortical structures. Despite tremendous progress in functional neuroimaging over the last decade, our understanding of human auditory learning is limited due to a corticulocentric bias in the field. Functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) studies on auditory learning have almost exclusively focused on the cortical structures. Yet animal models have highligted the critical role of subcortical structures, especially the inferior colliculus (IC), a midbrain structure, in auditory learning. In humans, a significant challenge to learning a foreign language is to perceive non-native phonemes. Individual differences in phonetic learning ability have been thus far attributed to cortical circuitry. In this seminar, I will discuss a series of studies using multimodal neuroimaging methods (brainstem electrophysiology, fMRI) that demonstrate that sensory encoding in the inferior colliculus (IC) contributes significantly to individual differences in language learning success.', 1313402400, 1313406000, 76, 61, 0, 'The University of Texas Austin'),
(425, 489, 'Dr. Francis Wong', 'Recent neuroanatomical models have postulated the importance of white matters in the frontal-temporal brain network for speech processing. Within this brain network, two important streams have been proposed, the dorsal stream and the ventral stream. The precise location of this ventral pathway has not been well established, with competing study findings claiming the role of the arcuate fasciculus and the extreme capsule. Furthermore, while there is emerging evidence confirming the ventral stream’s role in language comprehension, how language functions are coordinated by this pathway has yet to be explored.Using diffusion tensor imaging, a brain-imaging tool to investigate white matter connectivity in humans, we found that fractional anisotropy, an estimate of white matter integrity, in the left parietal-temporal region positively correlated with the performance in sound-to-word learning. In addition, fibre tracking revealed a ventral pathway, composed of the extreme capsule and the inferior longitudinal fasciculus, that mediated auditory comprehension. Our findings provide converging evidence supporting the importance of the ventral steam, an extreme capsule system, in the frontal-temporal language network. Implications for models of speech processing will also be discussed.', 1302278400, 1302282000, 76, 61, 0, 'Northwestern University/Nanyang Technological University'),
(426, 490, 'Dr. Anthony Jukes', 'Toratán is a virtually moribund language of North Sulawesi in Indonesia, spoken by a few hundred people in four villages, with the youngest fluent speakers in their 60s. This elderly generation of speakers often express regret at the decline of their language, and discuss the prospects of ''someone'' doing something about it. However there has been general resistance to the suggestion that they should begin by simply speaking Toratán to their grandchildren. The paper will discuss the impulse to relegate responsibility for language maintenance and revival to external authorities, taking as a starting point a comment from a community member and coworker: ‘we always say it’s someone else’s job’. I argue that this externalization of responsibility and action is one of the biggest factors working against prospects of Toratán language revival. I will also discuss a way of reframing the issues to return authority to the community.', 1306425600, 1306431000, 76, 61, 0, 'La Trobe University'),
(427, 491, 'Professor Angel Lin', 'Halliday’s linguistic theory of ‘grammatical metaphor’ and his discussion of the pivotal role that grammatical metaphor plays in the abstraction and technicalization of the language of science have been key theoretical resources informing the linguistic analysis of English academic language. In this presentation, I discuss the strategic role that a formal variety of Cantonese (based on Modern Standard Chinese) can play in scaffolding students’ development of formal academic literacy in educational contexts by examining the kinds of grammatical metaphors used in formal Cantonese and Modern Standard Chinese and how these grammatical metaphors can be connected to grammatical metaphors in formal academic language in English in educational settings. I explore the possibility of doing explicit modeling and mentoring in bridging courses to raise students’ awareness of grammatical metaphor as a central feature of English academic writing.', 1303999200, 1304004600, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Hong Kong'),
(428, 492, 'Professor Randy La Polla', 'Too often the assumption of global categories when analysing languages does an injustice to the language in terms of obscuring the picture of what is going on in the language, so, for example, the assumption of global categories of “noun” and “verb” and “subject” etc. lead to protracted arguments about why the language doesn’t seem to fit the ideal and why some words in the language seem more to fit the ideal of say “noun” than others. Witness the two volumes of papers on the definition of form classes in Chinese recently published in Yuyanxue Luncong (《语言学论从》).Ifonetakesaconstructionalperspective,similartothatarguedforinCroft2001,butwithanevenmoreradicallyinductiveapproachtostructure(LaPolla2003),theproblemsimplygoesaway,andonecanseethesystemspresentinthelanguagesmuchmoreclearlyandalsoseetheirfunctionalmotivations.DataandargumentswillbepresentedfromSino-TibetanandAustronesianlanguages.    Croft,W.2001.RadicalConstructionGrammar:SyntacticTheoryinTypologicalPerspective.Oxford:OxfordUniversityPress.    LaPolla,RandyJ.2003.Whylanguagesdiffer:Variationintheconventionalizationofconstraintsoninference.InD.Bradley,R.J.LaPolla,B.Michailovsky&G.Thurgood(eds.),Languagevariation:PapersonvariationandchangeintheSinosphereandintheIndosphereinhonourofJamesA.Matisoff,113-144.Canberra:PacificLinguistics.', 1312468200, 1312473600, 76, 61, 0, 'La Trobe University'),
(429, 493, 'Professor Anne Pauwels', 'The place of foreign language learning in education has a rich and diverse history since the introduction of compulsory schooling with some countries including the learning of a foreign language as a compulsory part of the curriculum whilst in others foreign language learning is seen as an optional subject suited for more academically minded students. In more recent times the place and role of foreign or second language learning have come under increasing scrutiny, partly in response to world-wide developments in communication technologies, increased and expanded transnational mobility, global security concerns and the emergence of a global lingua franca, English. In this presentation I will briefly outline how different countries and societies have reacted to these new circumstances before discussing in some detail the challenges for university level language learning. I will focus my attention on three key elements of foreign and second language learning: the learner, the teacher and the curriculum.', 1320328800, 1320334200, 76, 61, 0, 'School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London'),
(430, 494, 'Dr Mutsumi Imai', 'Whether and to what extent our conceptual structure is universal is of great importance for our understanding of the nature of human concepts. Two major factors that might affect our concepts are language and culture. In this research, we investigated whether these two factors affect our concepts of everyday objects in any significant ways. Concerning the linguistic factor, we tested whether a grammatical categorization system by classifiers, which classify objects in the world very differently from the way nouns do, influence the conceptual structure of speakers of classifier languages.Concerning the culture factor, we tested a specific proposal by Nisbett and colleagues (e.g., Nisbett, Peng, Choi, & Norenzayan, 2001), which predicts that Westerners organize object concepts around taxonomic relations while Easterners organize them around thematic relations. For this purpose, we tested children and adults speaking a classifier language, Chinese and Japanese, and those speaking German, a non-classifier language, on a range of tasks including categorization, similarity judgment, novel label extension, property induction, and object individuation. The overall results indicate that the global structure of our concepts of everyday objects is very similar across the three different culture/language groups, while there was much variability in the participants’ performance across different tasks. We discuss how language-specific linguistic properties might affect our concepts, categories, and cognitive processes, and how they interact with task-specific constraints as well as our universal cognitive dispositions.', 1298892600, 1298898000, 76, 61, 0, 'Professor of Psychology at the Faculty of Environment and Information Studies, Keio University'),
(431, 495, 'Professor Peter Auer', 'In this talk, I will be reporting the findings of a series of studies on the spontaneous acquisition of Turkish by speakers of non-Turkish family background in Hamburg. These include:    The acquisition of Turkish by adolescents of non-Turkish family background in Germany questions the hegemonic status of German.    The acquisition process rarely leads to a monolingual Turkish speaking style, but to codemixing and codeswitching which become part of social styles.    These styles are structured like those of Turkish adolescents.    They imply a convergence towards their speech, and do not constitute a case of “crossing”.    Using these styles often, but not always positions the speaker close to the Turkish group.    In addition, it may position the speaker, i.e. as a member of a certain youth culture or a subcultural milieu.    The acquisition process includes learning through routine formulae and prefabricated speech, but also self-administered and other-administered informal (lay) instructions.    It supports the prestige of this language in peripheral language markets.', 1298390400, 1298395800, 76, 61, 0, 'Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies, Germany'),
(432, 496, 'Dr Cao Fan', 'Typical reading acquisition and reading development is associated with specialization to one specific writing system at the neurological level. In the talk, I will address this issue by comparing reading development in two very contrastive writing systems: Chinese and English. Chinese reading development is characterized by increased involvement of visuo-orthographic areas in both hemispheres and decreased involvement of phonological region in left superior temporal gyrus. English reading development is characterized by increased involvement of orthographic and phonological areas in the left hemisphere and decreased involvement of non-linguistic visual processing in the right hemisphere. When there is a reading disability, reduced activation has been found in orthographic and phonological regions in English and Chinese. Reading disability is associated with a failure of specialization to one specific writing system. In the last part of the talk, I will talk about how appropriate learning methods help specialization in second language reading. Specifically, I will talk about how writing helps reading in English speakers learning Chinese and its implications in the intervention of reading disability in Chinese. Possible training methods for Chinese speakers learning English will also be discussed.', 1320244200, 1320247800, 76, 61, 0, 'Learning Research and Development Center, University of Pittsburg'),
(433, 497, 'Professor Patrick Wong', 'Empirical studies and anecdotal evidence point to the fact that a large individual variability exists in learning in adulthood. In particular, second language learning, especially foreign phoneme and grammar (including phonological grammar) learning, is notoriously difficult to learn, and adults differ to a large extent in how well they learn. How this variability can be identified before training and how altering training may reduce variability has yet to be extensively investigated. We report two sets of experiments targeting these two aspects of second language learning. Both sets of experiments point to the fact that the large individual variability in language learning success in adults can be attributed to neurophysiological, neuroanatomical, cognitive, genetic, and/or perceptual factors. Furthermore, re-designing training based on these predictors can sometimes optimize learning.', 1312300800, 1312304400, 76, 61, 0, 'Northwestern University'),
(434, 498, 'Professor Hilary Chappell', 'It is widely held that classifier systems develop along two main parameters with respect to the most representative type of this category known as the „individuating classifier‟1 (see Peyraube & Wiebusch 1993):1. general classifiers > specific classifiers (diversification)2. quantifying function > classifying function (development of semantic function of categorization)In the case of atrophy, however, the opposite tendencies to those found in the birth of a classifier system are found, namely (i) specific CLF > general CLF and (ii) classifying function > quantifying function. Where historical documents exist, a cycle of change can thus be detected. An analysis and comparison of fully-fledged classifier systems in two separate Sinitic languages will be covered – those of the unclassified language, Waxiang (Xiangxi, Hunan), and certain dialects of the Southern Min group in order to assess (i) whether any change involving the gradual replacement of specific classifiers by general classifiers can be observed (i.e. loss of diversity) and (ii) if so, whether there is any subsequent diminution in their function as classifiers to assume only the quantifying function (i.e. loss of the categorization function).Based on a diachronic comparison of the developments in Southern Min classifier systems between 16th and 20th centuries (Chappell & Peyraube 2010), one of the few dialect groups for which extensive historical material is available, an analysis of the state of the art for classifiers in Waxiang is presented. This is based on fieldwork data from 2008 and 2010 on the Guzhang dialect spoken in the Xiangsi Tujia and Miao autonomous district of Hunan province. In particular, the use of several high frequency classifiers in both language groups, namely chiah4隻, tiau5條andki1枝inSouthernMinandpa41□,lau13 □and條tiau25條inWaxiang(theoriginofthefirsttwoclassifiersisasyetunclear)havebeenconsidered.ItisshownthatthediversityoftheseclassifiersystemsandthefunctionofcategorizationarestillhighlyinevidenceforthesetwoSiniticlanguages,asdistinctfromcertaindialectsofMandarin.', 1295964000, 1295967600, 76, 61, 0, 'Ecole Des HautesEtudes en Sciences Sociales, Paris'),
(435, 499, 'Prof K P Mohanan', 'This “talk” is intended as a conversation on a question that has haunted Tara Mohanan and me for the last two decades: given that most students who graduate with an undergraduate degree in linguistics would not need their knowledge of linguistics in their professional or personal lives after graduation, what is our justification for teaching linguistics? Of what value is linguistics education for our students, ten years after graduation?At the end of December 2010, I will be leaving NUS to join the Indian Institute of Science Education and Research (IISER) in Pune, India, where students specialize in mathematics, physics, chemistry and biology. The question in that context becomes more poignant: of what value is a course in linguistics for science students, during their degree program as well as ten years after graduation?The answer that Tara and I have come up with in our twenty years of linguistics education is this: for students who are not going to specialize in linguistics what is important is not the knowledge content of linguistics but the modes of inquiry and thinking that are prototypical of linguistics. We are theoretical linguists by training: what we teach can be of value to our students if we can help them develop the capacity to function like theoretical linguists in domains outside of linguistics per se: in every day lives, in professional lives, and in scientific research in areas like biology, sociology, ethics, and religion. In the “talk”, I will first outline briefly what we do to accomplish this educational goal, and proceed to have a conversation with the audience on linguistics education.', 1268388000, 1268393400, 76, 61, 0, 'Department of English Language and Literature, National University of Singapo'),
(436, 500, 'Dr Geoffrey Benjamin', 'The infix -a- in Temiar (Central Aslian, Peninsular Malaysia) covers a wide range of functions, both productive and non-productive. In Temiar morphology generally it serves iconically to indicate an embedded object. As a productive infix, it forms the middle voice of verbs and the singular of human nouns (Benjamin, in press a). The main non-productive function of -a- is as a frozen infix in (1) a set of non-inflecting ‘deponent’ verbs and (2) a set of disyllabic (‘middle-voice’) nouns. The same semantic dimension underlies both, namely that the verbs and nouns in question indicate that the subject or entity is thought of as being simultaneously its own agent and patient. Culturally, the special attention paid to ‘middle-voice’ processes relates to a central Temiar interest in the specifically dialectical character of Self–Other relations.', 1290767400, 1290771000, 76, 61, 0, 'School of Humanities & Social Sciences, Nanyang Technological University'),
(437, 501, 'Professor Nicholas Evans', 'Our ability to interact with others by building a shared and complex mental world is what distinguishes humans from other animals. This capacity for social cognition – sometimes also known as social intelligence – enables us to construct functioning societies sharing knowledge, values and goals, to empathise and communicate with others, and to undertake collaborative action.At the same time, psychosocial concepts like ‘uncle’, ‘clan’, ‘owner’, ‘benefit’, or ‘mutual’, being largely constructed by culture and language, are less evidently preexisting categories of the natural world than, say, colours, spatial relations or causality. On the assumption that the more evolutionarily recent a category of the world is, the more cross-cultural and cross-linguistic variety there is in how people construct and delineate it, we would expect psychosocial categories to be the most open to cross-linguistic variation, and therefore among the most fertile areas for studying the interaction of language, culture and thought. Yet most investigations on these neo-Whorfian questions have focussed on categories of the natural world rather than social cognition.In this talk I will discuss the potential contribution that the cognitive variety afforded by the world’s 6,000 languages can make to our understanding of human social cognition, when studied through a typological approach: the grammar of one language may be a sensitive index of accidental vs. deliberate action, another may index the monitoring of joint vs. individual attention, another may index differences between the subjectively- and the objectively- knowable, and another may index complex kinship categories.', 1290162600, 1290168000, 76, 61, 0, 'ANU College of Asia-Pacific, ANU'),
(438, 502, 'David Nathan', 'Language documentations and the archives that hold them are valuable sources of linguistic research data. In the future, these archives will also become crucial vectors of transmission for many endangered and extinct languages. Thus the theory and practice of documentation and the capabilities of archives will play key roles in the futures of many human languages. Today, documentary linguistics needs an evaluative and critical discourse about its practices and outcomes. Researchers have been struggling to go beyond conceiving of documentations as collections of data files. One route forward is through consideration of documentation''s audiences and usages, to reach better understandings of the forms of documentation and what it means to publish them.Just as documentary linguistics has found an ethical and community-oriented footing (Austin 2010), archives must also function as ethical publishers of this component of human heritage. The ELAR archive at SOAS has taken a social networking approach in order to address two major characteristics of endangered languages documentation: the sensitivity of many such materials (Thieberger & Musgrave 2007), requiring effective but nuanced access control; and the fluidity of the materials and their access conditions over time, requiring multiple ongoing relationships between depositors, users, and the archive (Nathan, in press). Tomorrow’s digital language archiving is not about technology but about relationships. Management of non-preservation functions is largely handed over to depositors and users, and the archive becomes redefined as a forum for building and conducting relationships and exchanges among them.In this talk, I will outline and demonstrate ELAR''s approach to these issues.', 1284220800, 1284226200, 76, 61, 0, 'Director, Endangered Languages Archive (ELAR), School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London.'),
(439, 503, 'Dr Petter Haugereid', 'One of the attractive features of constructionalist grammars, is that they have so-called `syntactic bootstrapping,'' which means that the argument structure of a lexical item is imposed on it by the syntax. This accounts nicely for valence alternations and innovations, where the argument structure and category of a given lexical item cannot be predicted without the syntactic context, as illustrated in (1)-(5) (from Clark and Clark, 1979).(1) The factory horns sirened throughout the raid.(2) The factory horns sirened midday and everyone broke for lunch.(3) The police car sirened the Porsche to a stop.(4) The police car sirened up to the accident site.(5) The police car sirened the daylight out of me.However, constructionalist approaches have been avoided in high-precision grammar development, mainly because of the relatively flat syntactic structures associated with syntactic constructions, and the correspondingly high number of rules. In this talk I will show how one can avoid the flat structures in a constructionalist approach by decomposing constructions into 4-5 subconstructions. These subconstructions, which will be realized as either syntactic rules, function words, or inflections, link one argument at a time, and make it possible to maintain binary structures.The talk will be illustrated with concrete examples from an implemented grammar of Norwegian.', 1288362600, 1288366200, 76, 61, 0, 'School of Humanities and Social Sciences, NTU'),
(440, 504, 'Professor Luke Kang-Kwong', 'For almost eighty years, Chinese linguists have been fascinated by sentences like ‘Pijiu ba, he dianr!’ (‘Beer, I’ll have some!’), which look superficially like a jumbled-up version of ‘normal-order sentences’. Numerous accounts have been proposed to explain their structure and meaning, but no consensus has been reached to this day as to how their true essence should be captured, making it one of the most intriguing and least well understood phenomena in Chinese grammar. This paper adopts a ‘dynamic’ perspective and analyses these sentences from the point of view of their planning and delivery in real time. It is argued that the key to a full understanding of these sentences is to think of them as ‘incremental sentences’, i.e., bipartite structure consisting of a ‘host’ followed by an ‘increment’. An examination of a corpus of naturally occurring data shows that as a grammatical form the incremental sentence can be used in different sequential contexts to perform a variety of actions. These span a spectrum of possibilities including intensification, emphasis, backgrounding, qualification, clarification and disambiguation.', 1287153000, 1287158400, 76, 61, 0, 'School of Humanities and Social Sciences, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore'),
(441, 505, 'Dr Nicole Kruspe', 'The Aslian languages of Peninsular Malaysia and Isthmian Thailand are a geographically isolated subgroup of the Mon-Khmer branch of Austroasiatic. Austroasiatic is the oldest known language stock spoken in mainland Southeast Asia and India. The 18 or so languages of the Aslian subgroup are spoken by minority groups, who reside predominantly in the interior of the Malay Peninsula.The languages remain gravely understudied, however a picture is emerging of typologically rich and diverse languages displaying intricate processes of morphological derivation and fine-grained lexical semantics. This talk will provide an introduction to the languages and their speakers, and discuss furture prospects for the study of these highly endangered languages.', 1281448800, 1281454200, 76, 61, 0, 'University of Melbourne, Australia'),
(442, 506, 'Birgit Hellwig', 'When we document under-described languages, we constantly engage with semantics: every fieldworker needs to establish semantic facts - even if "only" to find appropriate translations for words and morphemes. The collection and analysis of this data poses a number of methodological challenges, which revolve around the fact that any semantic investigation needs to be based on native-speaker intuitions. But often we are not native speakers of the languages we study, and we thus need to find other ways of accessing these intuitions. Usually, we resort to elicited and observational data. Semantic text books, however, argue that we cannot fully rely on these established methods when it comes to the investigation of semantics.This talk explores some possibilities for conducting semantic fieldwork. It gives an illustrative example (from Goemai, a West Chadic language of Nigeria), discussing the advantages and disadvantages of different methods.', 1284993000, 1284998400, 76, 61, 0, 'Research Centre for Linguistic Typology, La Trobe University'),
(443, 507, 'Professor Hongyin Tao', 'In this talk, Professor Tao will present an analysis of the so-called topic constructions using video recorded Mandarin conversations. He will show that there is a need to categorize topics into three groups based on the role of the speaker who produces them; self-initiated topics, self repetition, and other-initiated topics. These three topic types differ with regard to form (prosody and grammar), conversation function, as well as gesture pattern. Professor Tao hope to show that attention to actual language use and a video-based analysis can provide a useful methodology and yield new insights into some of the controversial issues in Chinese Linguistics.', 1283596200, 1283603400, 76, 61, 0, 'University of California, Los Angeles'),
(444, 508, 'Dr Randy J. LaPolla', 'In this talk Dr. Randy will argue that communication is not a coding-decoding process, but is instead one application of a human instinct to try to understand the world through inference. Communication relies crucially on this inferential ability, but language is not necessary for communication. Language can aid in communication, though, by helping to constrain the inferential process of the addressee. The inferential process can be more or less constrained, and language structure (both words and grammar) arises as speakers use the same forms to constrain the addressee''s interpretation in the same way, until they become habits on the individual level and conventions at the societal level. Language and its use is then culture (societal conventions for carrying out particular activities), much like other aspects of what we normally think of as culture and human behaviour, and is governed by the same principles. What we think of as the meaning of language structures is our experience of the use of those forms in constraining the interpretation in a particular way. Languages differ in terms of which semantic fields they obligatorily constrain the interpretation of, to what extent they constrain them, and what lexical or grammatical means they use to constrain them. Each language then is unique, as it reflects the patterns of use of its unique speaker community which are determined by the cognitive categories and culture of the speakers.', 1288798200, 1288801800, 76, 61, 0, 'Research Centre for Linguistics Typology, La Trobe University, Australia');
