(488, 552, 'Professor Marios Fourakis', 'The primary reason that persons with post-lingual severe-to-profound hearing loss receive cochlear implants is their desire to be able to perceive speech again. However, speech perception among implanted persons varies widely, from star to very limited performance. The research reported here aims at optimizing speech perception for people not in the star category. According to Loizou et al (1998, JASA 103, p. 1141ff), part of the problem is an impaired ability to track frequency changes in the speech signal as these changes constitute important information for perceiving differences between speech sounds. A cochlear implant is, at maximum, a 22-channel information transmitter, where a channel is composed of a band-pass filter and its corresponding electrode. A frequency allocation table is used to assign the band-pass limits to each band-pass filter. These tables are provided by the manufacturer and are, so to speak, the default tables. In this study, we changed these tables so that more channels would be assigned to the frequency range of 1000-3000 Hz, where many changes occur in the frequency content of the speech signal (experimental tables). Newly implanted patients were tested using the default and experimental tables on various speech perception tasks, most importantly the CNC word perception task, an open set and difficult task. Overall, there were no differences in performance. However, five of the nine subjects preferred the new tables for everyday listening, one was indifferent, and three preferred the default tables. In addition, closer inspection of the confusion matrices for each condition showed significant improvement using the experimental tables in the perception of stop consonants, especially for velar stops, which are not lip-readable.', 1361959200, 1361966400, 77, 62, 0, 'Department of Communication Sciences and Disorders, University of Wisconsin.'),
(489, 553, 'Professor Maria Teresa Guasti', 'In this study, we investigate a range of language abilities: phonology/short term memory (through non-word repetition), lexicon, syntax and pragmatics in a group of children with cochlear implants (mean age o 5 years). These children have all received their implant in the same hospital and have followed the same rehabilitation program. The vast majority received the implant before 2 years. We compare the performance of children with a cochlear implant with that of chronologically age-matched (CA) children. As expected, children with cochlear implants are weaker than CA-matched children. However, when age of implant is taken into account, their performance is age appropriate in some areas. The area of morphosyntax as measured by clitic (phonologically weak pronoun) production is particularly vulnerable and shows age of implantation effects. We also report on a follow up study carried out at the mean age of 7 years with a subset of the children who took part in the first study, in which we investigate language performance and reading abilities. We show that there is an improvement in the language outcomes. We also show that children with cochlear implants are slower than CA matched children in reading. We discuss these results in a cross-linguistic dimension, which calls attention to the specific challenging areas in a specific language. In addition, we compare the performance in reading of children with cochlear implants with those of early L2 learners of Italian and demonstrate some similarities. In the light of these, we discuss the impact of a delay on language exposure on reading.', 1361894400, 1361899800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, University of Milan-Bicocca.'),
(490, 554, 'Dr Stefan Bode', 'How does the human brain accomplish decision-making? Decisions, whether perceptual, internally driven, or economic, often have categorical outcomes. I will illustrate how multivariate pattern classification approaches (MVPA) for functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and electroencephalography (EEG) data can be used to predict choice outcomes directly from patterns of brain activity. First, I will show how this method can be used to predict perceptual decisions under high and low discriminability, even when stimuli do not provide discriminative information. Then, I will then provide examples for how MVPA can be used to investigate internally motivated choices, linking perceptual guessing decisions and so-called free decisions, by investigating the similarity of their underlying activation patterns. I will further show how the same analysis techniques applied to event-related potentials (ERPs) can be used to link perceptual decisions under low discriminability to pre-stimulus brain activity. This approach allows understanding early predictive brain activity as the starting point setting in an evidence accumulation model framework. Finally, I will extend the EEG-based MVPA approach to the analysis of post-decision neural processes and show that it can also be used to predict decision errors from brain signals prior to response execution. In conclusion, multivariate pattern classification provides a powerful tool for decoding the content of mental processes from brain activity and can be used for the analysis of both fMRI and EEG data. This provides a basis for an advanced investigation and a better understanding of the neural processes underlying human decision-making.', 1361457000, 1361462400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Melbourne School of Psychological Sciences, University of Melbourne.'),
(491, 555, 'Professor Jan Edwards', 'In the first few years of life, most children learn to talk. Children acquire language whether they are learning to speak English, or Korean, or both at once. They learn to pronounce words in the same way that the adults around them do, regardless of whether they live in a middle class American English home where mothers engage in intense interaction with the children using a special emphatic speech style that stresses nouns and labeling, or in a Korean home, where the analogous infant-directed speech style instead emphasizes verbs and the actions that verbs name. Perhaps because most children learn to talk so easily, the traditional view of phonological development has focused on children''s acquisition of abstract phonological categories such as phonemes, distinctive features, or markedness and faithfulness constraints, depending on the linguistic theory that is in vogue. Such a view of phonological development makes many assumptions: for example, it assumes that children''s phonological learning is best described in terms of alphabetic transcription and that patterns of phonological development are similar across different languages. In this talk, I will present analyses of data from the paidologos project (http://ling.osu.edu/~edwards) in support of a more nuanced view of phonological development. The paidologos project is a cross-linguistic examination of first-language phonological development across a number of languages, including American English, Cantonese, Greek, Japanese, and Mandarin. In this talk, I will argue that phonological knowledge is a complex system that involves many different levels of representation. The child''s task, as a language learner, is to learn these different levels and the mappings among them. Clinical implications of this view of phonological development will also be considered. [Supported by NIDCD grant #02932 and NSF grant #BCS-0729140 to Jan Edwards]', 1360749600, 1360756800, 77, 62, 0, 'Department of Communication Sciences and Disorders, University of Wisconsin.'),
(492, 556, 'Professor Peter Gaerdenfors', 'The talk presents a semantic theory based on conceptual spaces. In particular the theory provides a cognitive grounding of word classes. Meanings of words are analyzed as convex regions in different domains. I develop cognitive models of actions and events. These models are then used to present semantic analysis of verbs. I also show how the meaning of prepositions can be analyzed in geometric terms. Please feel free to attend also another talk presented by Professor Peter Gaerdenfors on Thursday 14 February 2013 at UTS, Sydney.', 1386000000, 1386005400, 77, 62, 0, 'Cognitive Science, Lund University'),
(493, 557, 'Dr Yuki Kunioka', 'Dr Yuki Kunioka Introduction of the mission and program of Hokuriku Innovation Cluster for Health Science (HICHS) HICHS, has been promoting 12 scientific projects and 4 expansion program in the Hokuriku area in Japan supported by the MEXT (Japanese Ministry of Education Culture, Sports, Science and Technology). The MEG standardization program by Prof. Isao Hashimoto in KIT and the research project on activated magnetometry utilizing SQUID efficacy by Prof. Gen Uehara in KIT are also belong to HICHS. The overview of the projects will be given. Dr Hirotoshi Hiraishi and Dr. Naoki Furutani Early diagnosis system of prevasive developmental disorders in young children We developed an integrated MEG and NIRS device optimized for the early diagnosis of pervasive developmental disorders (PDD) in young children. With this device, we recorded neurophysiological data from young children with PDD and typically developing young children (200 children in total). By obtaining non-invasive measurements with the child custom-sized MEG and NIRS, we demonstrated a rightward-lateralized neurophysiological network, and aberrant brain hemodynamic connectivity between the right and the left anterior frontal cortex under the concious conditions in young children with PDD. We found that these physiological features are available for the early diagnosis of PDD. Dr Hirotoshi Hiraishi Brain activity and related network during moral judgment in autism -MEG study- Morality is important for keeping human society stable. Typical developed people (TD) get morality through their development but autistic people (ASD) are difficult to get it. I measured ASD adolescents'' brain activities by using fMRI and also measured TD adults'' PFC activities and networks by using NIRS. There is a possibility that these blood changes are not directly reflect neural activity. Therefore, from the view points of developmental changes and networks, I want to compare neural activities related to moral judgment between ASD and TD. These data will be expected to establish an index of moral development. Dr. Naoki Furutani GPCRs play important roles in social behavior Neuropeptide B/W receptor 1 (NPBWR1) is a G-protein coupled receptor and whose ligands were identified by my group in 2002. NPBWR1 is Gi-coupling and exists on GABAergic neurons in the central amygdaloid nucleus. Npbwr1⁻/⁻ mice showed abnormality in some behavioral experiments and these data suggest important roles of NPBWR1 in regulating amygdala function during physical and social stress. The human NPBWR1 gene has a single nucleotide polymorphism at nucleotide 404 (404A>T). This polymorphism results in an amino acid change Y135F and this change alters receptor function. In psychological experiment, a significant genotype difference was observed, suggesting that the polymorphism of NPBWR1 affects human behavior in a social context. We are investigating the relation between the polymorphism and autism spectrum disorder now.', 1359025200, 1359032400, 77, 62, NULL, 'HICHS, Kanazawa University'),
