(517, 581, 'Assistant Professor Celeste Rodríguez Louro', 'The English quotative system (featuring forms such as say, think, zero, go, all and be like used in direct speech reproduction and thought) has been the subject of vigorous, in-depth sociolinguistic investigation, particularly in the past two decades. However, with the notable exception of Winter’s (2002) study of quotative be like in the speech of Melbourne adolescents, the Australian English quotative system remains virtually uncharted. I address this gap in the literature by offering a quantitative sociolinguistic analysis of the quotative system of Perth English, investigating to what extent linguistic (grammatical person, content of quote and tense) and social (age and sex) variables are implicated in the use of be like. My results stem from 32.5 hours (325,096 words) of spontaneous narratives of personal experience recorded with 47 speakers in Perth in 2011 and evince an overwhelming increase in the use of be like particularly amongst the youngest speakers—as compared to Winter’s (2002) findings for Melbourne in the late 1990s. Multivariate analysis using Goldvarb X (Sankoff, Tagliamonte & Smith 2005) indicates that—although some constraints like the favouring effect of first person subjects behave similarly across the generations and are in line with other Englishes—Australian be like is subject to different constraints across generations of young speakers. Pre-adolescent and adolescent girls are active agents of language change by upping be like’s frequency and its use with the historical present in narratives. Young adults are steady users of be like in historical present contexts but the significant effect of sex has reversed: it is young male adults—rather than women—who favour be like in this cohort. The findings are in line with trends noted in the literature on English quotation elsewhere and point once again to the irrevocable link between system-internal forces and social factors as speakers move through life', 1346238000, 1346241600, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Linguistics, University of Western Australia.'),
(518, 582, 'Dr Akira O''Connor', 'Neuroimaging studies of human recognition have found that a large network of brain regions is recruited by the identification of previously studied ''old'' items. This has led to regions such as the medial prefrontal cortex and lateral parietal lobes being understood as retrieval success regions, despite little converging evidence from neuropsychology. I will show that retrieval success activation may actually be driven by the hidden expectations we hold about our memories, rather than the act of remembering itself. In three fMRI experiments, inducing memory expectations about upcoming stimuli resulted in elevated activation in these regions, but only when these expectations were wrong. These findings demonstrate that process-pure measurements are hard to attain in studies of human cognition.', 1345564800, 1345570200, 77, 62, 0, 'School of Psychology, University of St Andrews, UK.'),
(519, 583, 'Professor Mari Ostendorf', 'Parsing is a core natural language processing technology, but most parsing work has been developed on written text. Spoken language poses challenges for systems trained on text due to the presence of disfluencies, recognizer errors, and differences in word choice and grammatical style. Parsing language models have been shown to be useful for improving speech transcription in terms of reducing word error rate, but we argue that parsing has benefits that go beyond word error rate. With increasing interest in language processing applied to spoken documents, there are now several applications that show a benefit from explicitly parsing speech and using parsing as an objective.This talk illustrates the impact that parsing can have on speech transcription and surveys examples of applications that directly benefit from parsing speech. We also discuss ways in which parsers can be modified to be more effective with spoken language.', 1345546800, 1345550400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Electrical Engineering, University of Washington, USA.'),
(520, 584, 'Dr Elise Baker', 'Children with a speech-sound disorder (SSD) constitute almost half of most paediatric speech pathologists caseloads (McLeod & Baker, 2004). For the majority of these children their difficulty is phonological (in the mind) rather than motoric (in the mouth). My talk will focus on the effect of phonological intervention on children’s acquisition of consonant clusters in monomorphemic and bimorphemic contexts. I will address two issues. Firstly, I will consider whether sonority is a useful theoretical construct for understanding children’s patterns of consonant cluster generalization in monomorphemic contexts (e.g., skip, play, tree). Secondly, I will consider whether intervention targeting initial consonant clusters with small sonority differences facilitates children’s acquisition of final consonant clusters in bimorphemic contexts (e.g., cats, drinks, jumped', 1344947400, 1344951000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Kids Talk Lab, University of Sydney.'),
(521, 585, 'Dr Natalie Munro', 'For over three decades now, researchers have utilised fast mapping experiments to investigate how children learn words (e.g., Carey and Bartlett, 1978). This now classic paradigm has led some to conclude that word learning is easy. However, slow mapping studies show that word learning is more complex and prone to obliviscence. For instance, despite being able to recognise a newly learnt name for a given referent, children can struggle to name the same referent. Children with specific language impairment (SLI) find word learning particularly challenging. In this talk, I will present the results of a slow mapping study involving children with and without SLI. I will explore two aspects of their performance. Firstly, I will examine the children’s abilities to recognize and name trained non-words, initially in a fast mapping context, then overtime. Secondly, I will present their immediate list recall performance of the same trained words relative to known real words. I will posit that the word learning deficits seen in children with SLI extend beyond phonological loop working memory accounts', 1344951000, 1344954600, 77, 62, NULL, 'Kids Talk Lab, University of Sydney.'),
(522, 586, 'Associate Professor Michael White', 'In this talk, after reviewing our approach to surface realization with Combinatory Categorial Grammar, I''ll survey our recent efforts to incorporate linguistically motivated features into our discriminative realization ranking model, focusing on experiments investigating dependency length minimization. Comprehension and corpus studies have found that the tendency to minimize dependency length has a strong influence on constituent ordering choices. We find that adding a total dependency length feature to a comprehensive realization ranking model yields statistically significant improvements in BLEU scores and significantly reduces the number of heavy/light ordering errors, many of which are egregious. Through distributional analyses, we also show that with simpler ranking models, dependency length minimization can go overboard, too often sacrificing canonical word order to shorten dependencies, while richer models manage to better counterbalance the dependency length minimization preference against (sometimes) competing canonical word order preferences. To conclude, I''ll return to the larger picture, suggesting that our work provides evidence that one should indeed aim to *capture* linguistic generalizations in NLP, not just "cover"'' them, despite what you may have heard to the contrary.', 1344855600, 1344859200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Linguistics, Ohio State University, USA.'),
(523, 587, 'Professor Martin Bruene', '“Social cognition” has been accepted as an umbrella term for a range of cognitive abilities involved in understanding other people, including social perception, emotion recognition, mentalising, and attributional style, and, as is argued here, social decision-making. The majority of neuroimaging studies have focused on a neural network connecting parts of the prefrontal, the temporal and the parietal cortex that is activated during performance of social cognitive tasks. With the exception of emotion recognition tasks, relatively little attention has been paid to the question as to what extent non-neocortical structures are involved in social cognition. Here, it shall be shown that some of the evolutionarily most “advanced” human emotions such as empathy for pain and the recognition of trust and reciprocity are anatomically represented in parts of the limbic lobe, a phylogenetically older part of the brain. These neural substrates are also activated during economic decision-making involving, for example, the reciprocation of trust, rejection of unfairness and “costly” punishment. Understanding the interplay of limbic structures with neocortical regions can inform us not only about the neuronal architecture of social decision-making in general, but also about the ways, people with psychological illnesses recognize and respond to challenges from their social environment.', 1341763200, 1341768600, 77, 62, NULL, 'LWL University Hospital, Ruhr-University Bochum, Germany.'),
(524, 588, 'Professor Roy Kessels', 'Fifty years of memory research has resulted in theories on working memory and episodic memory, which are generally regarded as dissociable and separate systems, each with their own neural underpinnings. However, recent evidence suggests that working memory and episodic memory may in fact rely on the same cognitive operations and brain processes. In this talk I will present evidence from fMRI studies showing that the medial temporal lobe (including the hippocampus) is implicated in working-memory maintenance of bound information, especially when information processed in different brain regions needs to be integrated. This activation may reflect episodic buffer processing in accordance with Baddeley’s working-memory model. It is, however, still an open question whether this hippocampal involvement actually reflects working-memory processing or whether it is long-term encoding that determines the hippocampal activation during working-memory tasks. Recent findings on the interaction between working memory processing and episodic memory formation in normal ageing indicate that long-term encoding occurs during working-memory tasks. In addition, neuropsychological findings in patients with MTL-diencephalic amnesia indicate that long-term encoding processes indeed – at least in part – play a role in working-memory tasks that require the binding of information. I will present recent data from ongoing neuroimaging, ageing and patient studies on the role of the MTL and long-term encoding in visual working memory maintenance and subsequent memory effects.', 1343750400, 1343755800, 77, 62, 0, 'Donders Institute for Brain, Cognition and Behaviour, Radboud University Nijmegen, The Netherlands.'),
(525, 589, 'Professor Marc Brysbaert', 'In recent years it has become possible to assess speech dominance in a noninvasive and valid way with the use of fMRI. In this talk I will discuss how we found of sample of 20+ lefthanders with right hemisphere speech lateralization, who we compared to control participants (both left- and righthanded) with left hemisphere dominance. Questions addressed are: (1) does language dominance have implications for foveal word recognition (split-fovea vs. bilateral fovea), (2) does language dominance have implications for eye movements in reading, (3) does atypical speech dominance have implications for the lateralization of other language and non-language functions?', 1342540800, 1342546200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Experimental Psychology, Ghent University, Belgium.'),
(526, 590, 'Dr Emmanuel Keuleers', 'In a recent experiment, Grainger et al. (2012) showed that baboons learn to distinguish four-letter words from nonwords with an accuracy of about 75%. Whereas the authors defined orthographic processing as "the computation of letter identities and their relative positions", the representations and positional information required for this task remain unclear. We investigate the required level of orthographic processing in a lexical decision task using a nearest neighbor decision model (Keuleers & Brysbaert, 2011) extended with a Jaccard distance metric which can be made (in)sensitive to letter order and letter clusters. Simulations on the baboon data show that a non-positional single letter metric shows performance similar to that of baboons and that using bigrams and trigrams decreases performance, casting doubt on claims of advanced orthographic processing in baboons. Grainger, J., Dufau, S., Montant, M., Ziegler, J. C., & Fagot, J. (2012). Orthographic Processing in Baboons (Papio papio). Science, 336(6078), 245-248. Keuleers, E., & Brysbaert, M. (2011). Detecting inherent bias in lexical decision experiments with the LD1NN algorithm. The Mental Lexicon, 6(1), 34-52.', 1349625600, 1349631000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Experimental Psychology, Ghent University, Belgium.'),
(527, 591, 'Distinguished Professor Mabel Rice', 'Children with SLI, and younger typically developing children, are likely to omit auxiliary DO. This is part of a profile of omitted finiteness markers posited to be part of an Extended Optional Infinitive (EOI) period for children with SLI. Other accounts posit general learning deficiencies or breakdowns in input processing. DO has multiple grammatical functions. Under an EOI account, aux DO should be selectively weak relative to lexical DO and overt syntactic errors should be unlikely. This presentation reports on a study of the use of DO in multiple grammatical contexts in the spontaneous utterances of 37 children with SLI, 37 age equivalent children, and 15 language equivalent children. The outcomes conform to the predictions of the EOI model, and support the Grammatical Conservatism model of Synder (2007).', 1333794600, 1333800000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Speech-Language & Hearing, University of Kansas, USA.'),
(528, 592, 'Associate Professor Alex Holcombe', 'In confronting our problematic publishing system, the open access movement has recently celebrated several victories. Although Australian funding agencies have lagged their peers in the UK, the US, and Europe, increasing numbers of researchers will be affected by the shifting expectations of research funders worldwide. The repercussions will extend beyond unfettered access to journal articles and create space for new ways of doing and publishing science. This should include some opportunities to address the file-drawer problem. Replications and failures to replicate are published very rarely in psychology. Yet replication is part of the foundation of science. We need a way to publish replications, and the system should be encouraging rather than discouraging replication studies. After discussing broader issues of the open access movement, I will describe two projects I am involved in to increase the number of replications performed and published. One is the website www.psychfiledrawer.org, another is a plan to start a new journal (together with Dan Simons) for replication studies about which I hope you''ll give me some comments.', 1331136000, 1331141400, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, University of Sydney.'),
(529, 593, 'Dr Megan Willis', 'Over the past four decades an abundance of research has been dedicated towards delineating the cognitive and neural mechanisms that underpin explicit facial expression recognition. We have a considerably poorer understanding of the manner in which we use the information depicted in facial expressions to guide our subsequent behaviour. Developing our understanding of the processes that underlie the way in which facial expressions influence behaviour is particularly important, given that individuals in many clinical conditions show the co-?existence of abnormal social behaviour and facial expression recognition impairments. This talk will discuss recent research that has explored how we use facial expressions to guide decisions relevant to our social behaviour, in this case, judging how approachable another person is – and the impact that context and social anxiety have on these judgements. Finally, this talk will also discuss new research examining how facial expressions influence an individual’s confidence and task performance, which has important implications for understanding behaviour in employment and educational settings.', 1340884800, 1340888400, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, Australian Catholic University.'),
(530, 594, 'Dr Emma Barkus', 'Schizotypy is a personality trait which holds intrigue for both individual difference researchers and clinicians alike. It is link to a number of normal personality variables such as creativity, however along a clinical spectrum it is associated with increased risk for psychotic symptoms and psychosis. Schizotypy is characterised by emotional and social withdrawal, along with attenuated psychotic symptoms including unusual perceptual experiences, unusual beliefs and though patterns and, perhaps, an increased risk of depression and anxiety. Individuals from the general population who score highly on schizotypy are a useful surrogate group or model for investigating the psychological, neurological and biological mechanisms underpinning clinical psychotic symptoms. In this talk I will present data from a number of studies which we have conducted at the University of Wollongong. We have investigated factors associated with elevated schizotypy scores, how schizotypes interact with and perceive their environment.', 1340726400, 1340731800, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, University of Wollongong.'),
(531, 595, 'Dr Simone Favelle', '', 1340280000, 1340283600, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, University of Wollongong.'),
(532, 596, 'Professor Ken Forster', 'Is it possible that we can process more than one word at the same time? Research on eye movements during normal reading suggests that we can pick up information about the word to the right of the currently fixated word (the parafoveal preview effect), but it is not known whether the two words are processed sequentially or in parallel. This research deals with the processing of two spatially distributed words. A different perspective arises in masked priming, which deals with temporally distributed words. In these experiments, priming effects are obtained with a 50 ms prime-target SOA, and the existence of phenomena such as cross-language translation priming, and congruence effects in semantic categorization tasks indicates that the prime must have been interpreted semantically. However, it is estimated that at least 150 ms is needed to retrieve the meaning of a word. This suggests that the prime continues to be processed after the target has been presented, which is support for parallel processing. Current models of visual word recognition have difficulty explaining how this is possible, since the activation produced by the target would suppress activation produced by the prime. New experiments will be described which examine the effect of inserting a brief intervening stimulus between the prime and the target. If priming is unaffected, this would mean that three words could be processed simultaneously.', 1340121600, 1340127000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, University of Arizona, USA.'),
(533, 597, 'Distinguished Professor James Townsend', 'As a fundamental part of our daily lives, visual word processing has received much attention in the psychological literature. Despite the well-established perceptual advantages of word and pseudoword context using accuracy, a comparable effect using response times has been elusive. Some researchers continue to question whether the advantage due to word context is perceptual. We use the workload capacity coefficient, a well established, response time based functional measure of efficiency to provide evidence of word processing as a particularly efficient perceptual process to complement those results from the accuracy domain. Bio: James Townsend is a Distinguished Professor and a Rudy Professor at the School of Psychological and Brain Sciences, Indiana University. His research focuses on the development of general mathematical approaches to human information processing in cognitive and clinical psychology including: identification of cognitive systems, configural perception, inter-modality interactions, visual and memory scanning, decision theory, attentional capacity, applications to schizophrenia and autism. Prof. Townsend earned a BA from Fresno State University and a PhD from Stanford University. He then went on to assume faculty positions in U. of Hawaii, Purdue, and, since 1989, in Indiana University. Among his many services, Prof. Townsend had served twice as the president of the Society for Mathematical Psychology, and as the Editor in Chief of the Journal of Mathematical Psychology. He had won numerous national and international awards, many competitive grants, and publishes prolifically. Some of his papers, on Decision Field Theory (1993) and on General Recognition Theory (1986) are among the most highly cited in Mathematical Psychology, ever, and his book Stochastic Modeling of Elementary Psychological Process (with Greg Ashby) is a ''must read'' in the field. Professor Townsend''s current theoretical interest centers on unifying his theories and methodologies using response times and those employing patterns of accuracy. His content focus is on configural and face perception.', 1354809600, 1354815000, 77, 62, 0, 'School of Psychological and Brain Sciences, Indiana University, USA.'),
(534, 598, 'Dr Susan Shuai', 'In this presentation, I report three ERP studies investigating the hemispheric specialization of tone perception and one ERP study exploring the contour feature of tones. This line of research begins with the debate between the task-dependent (based on linguistic mechanisms) and cue-dependent (based on acoustically driven mechanisms) hypotheses, which predict opposite lateralization patterns. Since lexical tone is defined as the use of pitch variations to distinguish lexical meanings, it is natural to examine both the linguistic function and acoustic property of lexical tone, and the current work shows that both aspects affect the lateralization in tone perception, in both early (~200 ms) and late (~400 ms) time windows. This work contributes to a more complete picture of tone lateralization, and supports a parallel processing of both linguistic and acoustic factors. Further explorations of the lateralization of level and contour tones reveal different degrees of lateralization of these two types of tones, and partially support the existence of tone contour feature. The results are discussed in a broader sense associating with brain structure and theories of language evolution.', 1344268800, 1344274200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Chinese, Translation and Linguistics, City University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong.'),
(535, 599, 'Professor Reinhold Kliegl', 'Microsaccade research has enjoyed a revival during the last ten years. The presentation briefly reviews this development. I will describe how the relation between microsaccade orientation and covert shifts of attention can be examined in a multinomial processing tree model (Laubrock et al., 2011, AP&P). Finally, I will also describe Engbert''s (in press, J Neurosci) computational dynamical modeling of changes in orientation effects of microsaccades across the cue-target interval and in response to exogenous and endogenous cue conditions.', 1336320000, 1336325400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, Potsdam University, Germany.'),
(536, 600, 'Dr Thomas Whitford', 'Self-generated sensations typically feel less salient than externally-generated sensations, with tickling as a well-known example. An abnormality in this process of sensory self-suppression has been argued to underlie some of the most bizarre yet characteristic symptoms of schizophrenia, in which patients misattribute self-generated actions to external agents. The talk will start with a review of the evidence for sensory self-suppression from the animal and human literature. I will go on to present electrophysiological and Diffusion-Tensor Imaging data suggesting that schizophrenia patients may show conduction delays in the neural signals (“corollary discharges”) that are normally involved in suppressing self-generated sensations and distinguishing between self-generated and externally-generated actions', 1338307200, 1338312600, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, University of New South Wales.'),
(537, 601, 'Dr Evan Kidd', 'We know very little about the (neuro)-cognitive mechanisms that support language acquisition. For instance, although much research has identified Working Memory as a possible candidate, several recent empirical results are inconsistent with this claim. In my talk I will argue that language acquisition is better conceptualized as a process of linguistic adaptation as supported by an implicit learning mechanism. First I will discuss various frequency effects in the acquisition of different syntactic structures, which I will argue are symptomatic of an implicit learning mechanism that attends to distributional frequency information. I will then present a study that shows a direct association between implicit visual sequence learning and acquisition as indexed by structural priming. I will conclude by discussing how these findings fit with current theories of language acquisition.', 1338213600, 1338217200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, Australian National University.'),
(538, 602, 'Professor David Chiang', 'In the last 50 years, computational linguistics research has touched barely 1% of the world''s languages. In 100 years, 90% of them will be extinct or nearly so. What can computational linguistics offer to support the urgent task of documenting and analyzing the world''s endangered languages? Based on the observation that bilingual parallel text is both the primary artifact collected in documentary linguistics as well as the primary object of statistical translation models, we are initiating a project that explores the use of machine translation to accelerate the global language documentation effort. En route to our first field trip to Eastern Highlands province in Papua New Guinea, I will give a brief overview of what we expect to accomplish there, and afterwards with the data and experience we bring back.', 1337337000, 1337340600, 77, 62, NULL, 'Information Sciences Institute, University of Southern California, USA.'),
(539, 603, 'Ashish Vaswani', 'Statistical techniques are the mainstay for solving most Natural Language Processing (NLP) problems. Many of these approaches are supervised, requiring large labeled corpora to train the models. However, for many important problems like part of speech (POS) tagging or word alignment, annotated corpora are unavailable for many languages. Without labeled data, unsupervised learning is the primary solution. The workhorse for learning most unsupervised NLP models is the Expectation Maximization (EM) algorithm (Dempster et al. 1977), which finds the maximum likelihood estimates of the parameters. However, the maximum likelihood estimator suffers from overfitting and does not give small model sizes which results in poor performance. We address both of these problems in a single approach. We carry out parameter learning and model minimization simultaneously by optimizing a single objective function that encourages parameter sparsity. Inspired by the MDL principle, we use an objective function for generative models that captures the description of the data by the model (via log-likelihood) and the description of the model (via the L0-norm of the model parameters). We also develop an efficient general search algorithm based on the MAP-EM framework to optimize this function. Our approach is both simple and scalable. It significantly improves performance over vanilla EM on multiple tasks and scales well to large datasets.', 1337340600, 1337344200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Information Sciences Institute, University of Southern California, USA.'),
(540, 604, 'Professor Stephen J Wright', 'Optimization is proving to be a vital tool in machine learning, as a means to formulate and solve problems. Recently, the complex challenges posed by large data sets and the demands for a greater variety of analysis and learning tasks have brought a wider range of optimization tools into play. Among these tools are stochastic gradient methods, sparse optimization methods, enhanced first-order methods, coordinate descent, and approximate second-order methods. In this talk, we survey a variety of problem formulations and outline the optimization techniques that are relevant in each case.', 1337090400, 1337094000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Computer Sciences Department, University of Wisconsin-Madison, USA.'),
(541, 605, 'Dr Tiberio Caetano', 'Maximum A Posteriori inference in graphical models is often solved via message-passing algorithms, such as the junction-tree algorithm, loopy belief-propagation, or factor-graph inference. All such algorithms rely on two components: a procedure to pass a single message and a protocol that determines the order in which different messages should be passed. This presentation describes a novel algorithm for solving the first problem: passing a single message. The algorithm is exact, just as the standard algorithm used for this task, however it is substantially faster in practice when the state space of the random variables is large. Although it has the same worst-case complexity, it has a much better expected-case complexity since it exploits the structure of the clique potentials in the graphical model. Since the algorithm only affects the message-passing step, it can be used with any protocol. The assumptions it requires are also very often met in practice. We illustrate the practical advantages of the improved algorithm in a number of tasks, such as text and image denoising, optical flow inference, stereo disparity estimation, and graph matching.', 1346842800, 1346846400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Statistical Machine Learning Group, NICTA.'),
(542, 606, 'Professor Cheryl Grady', 'Professor Cheryl Grady, a Canada Research Chair in Neurocognitive Aging, is a senior scientist at the Rotman Research Institute in Toronto, Canada. Her work focuses on the use of brain imaging to explore the functional changes that occur in aging and how these relate to changes in behaviour. She will discuss the findings from her recent projects on age-related (i) deficits in inhibition of external distractions, (ii) differences in BOLD signal variability, and (iii) differences in neural network connectivity.', 1344182400, 1344187800, 77, 62, 0, 'Department of Psychology and Psychiatry, University of Toronto, Canada, Rotman Research Institute, Canada.'),
(543, 607, 'Dr Matthew Howard', 'Despite our in depth knowledge of the basic mechanisms underlying pain, we still struggle to develop effective new analgesics. Until relatively recently, the development of novel therapies and a clearer understanding of how we process pain have been almost wholly reliant on individual ‘self-report’ measures that are inherently subjective. Evoked-response paradigms often employed in BOLD fMRI experiments have provided key insights into supraspinal mechanisms of acute pain, but are ill-suited to examining spontaneous or background ongoing pain common to persistent pain conditions or to examining long-term treatment effects. In this talk, we demonstrate the utility of continuous arterial spin labeling (cASL), a perfusion-sensitive magnetic resonance imaging technique, to the challenge of visualizing ongoing, clinically relevant pain and its treatment (Howard et al., PlosOne, 2011). Multivariate ‘machine learning’ image analysis techniques, in particular, Gaussian Process Classification (Marquand et al., Neuroimage, 2010), are applied to cASL data to provide probabilistic, individualized predictions of ongoing pain states and treatment responses.', 1333629000, 1333589400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Neuroimaging, Institute of Psychiatry, King’s College London, UK.'),
(544, 608, 'Professor Morris Moscovitch', '', 1328445000, 1328405400, 77, 62, 0, 'Department of Psychology, University of Toronto, Canada, Rotman Research Institute, Canada.'),
(545, 609, 'Dr Chiara Fiorentini', '', 1335441600, 1335445200, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, Australian National University.'),
(546, 610, 'Professor William Bechtel', 'Most accounts of brain processes in neuroscience and proposals for cognitive architectures in cognitive science construe the mind/brain as reactive: processing is initiated in response to a stimulus. But there is growing evidence that brains are endogenously active: oscillations in electrochemical activity at multiple frequencies are ongoing in the brain even in the absence of stimuli and stimuli serve to modulate these oscillations rather than initiate activity. Moreover, this endogenous activity is used in various information processing activities. I appeal to evidence from EEG, LFPs, and resting state fMRI to support the claim of ongoing oscillatory behavior in the brain and identify several ways it contributes to cognition. Modeling neural activity requires a cognitive architecture that both reflects the organization of the brain and the dynamic activity exhibit by the brain.', 1335283200, 1335288600, 77, 62, 0, 'Department of Philosophy, Center for Chronobiology, and Interdisciplinary Program in Cognitive Science, University of California, San Diego, USA.'),
(547, 611, 'Dr Carolyn Wilshire', '', 1334836800, 1334799000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, University of Wellington, New Zealand.'),
(548, 612, 'Professor Kim Cornish', '', 1334678400, 1334683800, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology and Psychiatry, Monash University.'),
(549, 613, 'Ben Crittenden', 'In goal-directed behaviour it is often necessary to break down a more complicated task into simpler tasks. For example, when on a shopping trip, you will want to buy all of your items without revisiting the same shop while also covering less ground around the shopping centre, so you plan what order you get your things to save you time. It has been shown that patients with lateral Prefrontal Cortex lesions often struggle when they need to do such structured tasks as this. However, how structured tasks are functionally organised across the lateral PFC is not well understood. In our lab we are trying to address this question using functional MRI. I will present a study which provides evidence against two prevailing models of PFC organisation, one based on how abstract a task is and one that is grounded in information theory. In addition, I’ll discuss another study which suggests that larger changes in the neural representation of a task take place as subjects approach the overall goal. Finally I will introduce our labs current thoughts on how the lateral PFC is organised.', 1330876800, 1330882200, 77, 62, NULL, 'MRC Cognition and Brain Sciences Unit, University of Cambridge, UK.'),
(550, 614, 'Professor Ina Bornkessel-Schlesewsky', 'What makes two languages similar to or different from one another? This question was traditionally approached via language families or, from the perspective of "language typology", through the structural properties of the languages in question. However, recent neuroscientific findings have revealed that neither of these two dimensions may be crucially relevant to whether or not two languages are processed in the same way by the human brain. Rather, the neural signatures of language processing can differ qualitatively between related and intuitively similar languages (e.g. German and Dutch). At the same time, genetically unrelated languages with no such readily apparent similarities engender qualitatively similar brain responses (e.g. German, Chinese and Turkish). In this presentation, we will argue that the "neurotypology" of languages that can be gleaned from data of this type can help to shed light on the cognitive bases underlying the human language faculty.', 1333117800, 1333121400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences, Germany, Johannes Gutenberg-University, Germany.'),
(551, 615, 'Professor Matthias Schlesewsky', 'What makes two languages similar to or different from one another? This question was traditionally approached via language families or, from the perspective of "language typology", through the structural properties of the languages in question. However, recent neuroscientific findings have revealed that neither of these two dimensions may be crucially relevant to whether or not two languages are processed in the same way by the human brain. Rather, the neural signatures of language processing can differ qualitatively between related and intuitively similar languages (e.g. German and Dutch). At the same time, genetically unrelated languages with no such readily apparent similarities engender qualitatively similar brain responses (e.g. German, Chinese and Turkish). In this presentation, we will argue that the "neurotypology" of languages that can be gleaned from data of this type can help to shed light on the cognitive bases underlying the human language faculty.', 1333117800, 1333121400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences, Germany, Johannes Gutenberg-University, Germany.'),
(552, 616, 'Professor Ina Bornkessel-Schlesewsky', 'Whether it is spoken, written or signed, a linguistic utterance unfolds in time. Accordingly, the information which it conveys changes from moment to moment, depending on which parts of the utterance have already been encountered and which are yet to come. As a result of this intimate relation between language and time, the order in which the words in a sentence are encountered is of crucial importance to the way in which that sentence can be understood: order or sequence information is a cue that a hearer "gets for free" in any language. Interestingly, however, and in spite of the fact that sequencing information is always available, not all languages adhere to a rigid word order. How, then, does the human brain deal with linguistic sequences? In this presentation, we will review a range of results from different languages which provide evidence for a neuroanatomical gradient of sequence processing in frontal cortex. These findings suggest that, while temporal structure may be particularly important in language, linguistic sequencing builds upon basic aspects of human information processing which also apply in a range of other domains.', 1332946800, 1332952200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences, Germany, Johannes Gutenberg-University, Germany.'),
(553, 617, 'Professor Matthias Schlesewsky', 'Whether it is spoken, written or signed, a linguistic utterance unfolds in time. Accordingly, the information which it conveys changes from moment to moment, depending on which parts of the utterance have already been encountered and which are yet to come. As a result of this intimate relation between language and time, the order in which the words in a sentence are encountered is of crucial importance to the way in which that sentence can be understood: order or sequence information is a cue that a hearer "gets for free" in any language. Interestingly, however, and in spite of the fact that sequencing information is always available, not all languages adhere to a rigid word order. How, then, does the human brain deal with linguistic sequences? In this presentation, we will review a range of results from different languages which provide evidence for a neuroanatomical gradient of sequence processing in frontal cortex. These findings suggest that, while temporal structure may be particularly important in language, linguistic sequencing builds upon basic aspects of human information processing which also apply in a range of other domains.', 1332946800, 1332952200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Max Planck Institute for Human Cognitive and Brain Sciences, Germany, Johannes Gutenberg-University, Germany.'),
(554, 618, 'Dr Juanita Todd', 'Prediction-error is a term given to events that do not conform to our expectations. Prediction-errors possess motivational salience in that they are capable of capturing attention, directing our behaviour and therefore prompting new learning. The mismatch negativity (MMN) is a prediction-error signal that occurs when a sound fails to match expectations based on an established regularity in the environment. Exposure to repetition leads to the formation of memory-based perceptual inferences about the most probable characteristics of future stimuli. MMN is elicited automatically (even when asleep) if an event does not conform to the inferred characteristics and is studied by measuring auditory evoked potentials. The MMN represents an alert signalling the occurrence of potentially relevant changes or salient events in the environment. It also reflects an updating process that incorporates this recent change into a model of probable features to enable more accurate future predictions. This system therefore ensures an automatic, dynamic and contextually relevant filter of the acoustic environment – a filter that diminishes the influence of events that confirm expectation, and promotes orientation to events that provide new information. MMN is reduced in size in schizophrenia. This reduced size is assumed to have functional consequences as MMN size is generally considered proportional to the degree to which the sounds violates expectations and therefore its potential relevance. The reduction in MMN size is present from first-episode with recent studies indicating that it may also be evident in those at ultra high risk who go on to develop the illness. In this presentation I will discuss research designed to determine why MMN is smaller in schizophrenia and to identify which aspects of prediction-error coding are dysfunctional. I will review research that elevates MMN from a very simple change detection signal into an intelligent inferential process that engages a context-sensitive network to determine relevance. Our most recent work reveals the presence of learning biases that influence automatic attributions of sound relevance. I will use these data to explain how smaller MMN amplitude in schizophrenia could reflect impaired prefrontal monitoring of the adequacy of perceptual inference.', 1332864000, 1332869400, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, University of Newcastle.'),
(555, 619, 'Professor Michael Webster', 'The perceived characteristics of a face can be strongly biased by adaptation to faces seen previously. These aftereffects have been found for many of the attributes characterizing natural variations in the face including identity, gender, and expression. We are exploring the impact of adaptation on judgments of facial age. Previously we showed that adaptation to a young or old face shifts the category boundary for classifying an individual as old vs. young. These aftereffects occur for both the textural and shape changes associated with aging, but are more strongly driven by the facial texture. In current work we are exploiting the fact that observers are relatively good at inferring a specific age from a face, so that it is possible to assess how adaptation affects faces drawn from different points throughout the lifespan. This provides a unique metric for examining the actual form of the response changes underlying adaptation to an important dimension of face perception, and I will consider how it can be used to test a number of unresolved questions about face adaptation, such as the role and nature of norms in the adaptation.', 1332158400, 1332162000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, University of Nevada, Reno, USA.'),
(556, 620, 'Professor Cathi Best', 'Recent studies show that by 11 months, language experience constrains infants'' detection of audio-visual correspondences in non-native speech (Pons et al., 2009; Best et al., 2010, 2011). But what is it that they have learned about native AV relations, and how does it bias their responses to non-native speech? An array of theoretical views offer differing hypotheses. The Learned Association view posits that AV associations require experience to develop, i.e., should emerge in older infants only for audio and visual speech patterns that co-occur in native speech (e.g., Kuhl& Meltzoff, 1982; Massaro, 1998). The Intersensory Narrowing account assumes young infants are innately sensitive to intersensory relations in speech, but experience narrows intersensory perception such that older infants remain sensitive only to native AV correspondences (Pons et al., 2009). The Amodal Articulatory Perception account premise is that infants perceive information about the actions of the speech articulators. They can distinguish speech segments by different articulators (between-organ) even in non-native speech, but to distinguish contrasts made by a single articulator (within-organ) they must experience them in native speech (Best & McRoberts, 2003; Goldstein & Fowler, 2003; Tyler et al., 2008). The Perceptual Assimilation Model (PAM: Best, 1995) posits instead developmental changes in infant perception of non-native contrasts depends on whether they perceive them as speech as nonspeech sounds. We therefore tested English-learning infants'' perception of cross-modal articulator congruency in one native and two nonnative between-organ contrasts, one of which English adults hear as speech (ejective stops), the other as nonspeech (clicks). By the Learned Association view, older infants should detect congruency more reliably than younger infants for native speech contrasts, and neither age should do so for nonnative contrasts. But if Intersensory Narrowing is correct, younger infants should detect congruency in native and nonnative contrasts, while older infants should do so only for the native contrast. The Amodal Articulatory account predicts sensitivity to articulator congruency in all between-organ contrasts at both ages, whereas the PAM account predicts different developmental trajectories for non-native contrasts perceived as speech versus contrasts perceived as nonspeech. Results for the nonnative ejective and native contrast support the Amodal Articulatory account, whereas results for the clicks and for the nonnative within-organ contrast used in the prior report (Pons et al., 2009), support the Intersensory Narrowing account. The difference in findings for the two non-native contrasts is compatible with PAM. The possibility of an integrated account combining those three views will be discussed.', 1332160200, 1332163800, 77, 62, NULL, 'MARCS Auditory Laboratories, University of Western Sydney.'),
(557, 621, 'Associate Professor Genevieve McArthur', 'The primary aim of this randomised control trial was to determine how to improve the treatment of dyslexia. To this end, we divided 94 children with dyslexia, aged between 7 and 12 years into three treatment groups. The first group was given 8 weeks of phonics training and then 8 weeks of sight?word training (phonics+sight-word group). The second group was given the same training but in reverse order (sight-word+phonics group). The third group was given phonics and sight?word training on alternate days (mixed group). The outcomes revealed that 16 weeks of phonics and sight?word training had a statistically significant and large effect on word reading accuracy, fluency and comprehension, regardless of order of phonics and sight-word training. Further, 8 weeks of sight-word training had a larger effect on irregular­ word reading than phonics training, while 8 weeks of phonics training had a larger effect on regular word reading than sight-word training. These findings indicate that many children with dyslexia require both sight-word training as well as phonics training.', 1331812800, 1331816400, 77, 62, NULL, 'ARC Centre of Excellence in Cognition and its Disorders, Department of Cognitive Science, Macquarie University.');
