(558, 622, 'Colleen Holt', 'Cochlear implant (CI) users often struggle to perceive pitch accurately, due to limitations of the device in combination with individual factors. In Australian English, rising pitch accents form part of the intonation system and can be characterised phonetically by differences in the coordination of fundamental frequency (F0) peaks and valleys with the segmental string. To date, little research has examined the perception of pitch accents in cochlear implant users. This seminar will focus on the results of three discrimination experiments conducted with an adolescent CI user group. All three experiments used speech stimuli with manipulated F0 contours. Experiment 1 examined the discrimination of level versus rising F0. The CI group easily discriminated between the level F0 contour and rises of 14, 18 and 23 semitones. Experiment 2 examined the discrimination of F0 peaks which differed in alignment with the segmental string. A control group with normal hearing could discriminate between F0 peaks which differed by 40 milliseconds or more. The CI group results were varied, with only a handful of individuals displaying a pattern of results similar to the control group. Experiment 3 saw bilaterally-implanted CI users repeat Experiment 2 in both unilateral and bilateral conditions. No bilateral advantage was evidenced for this task. As differences in F0 peak alignment may influence our categorisation of pitch accents, any difficulty in perceiving alignment differences may affect processing of pragmatic information.', 1331823600, 1331827200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Otolaryngology and Department of Audiology and Speech Pathology, University of Melbourne.'),
(559, 623, 'Distinguished Professor Mabel Rice', 'Static snapshots of language ability at a given level of development form the basis for a diagnosis of Specific Language Impairment (SLI) in children. Recent studies document interesting similarities and differences in the growth of language in children with and without SLI. Other studies provide evidence of likely genetic contributions to SLI. In this talk, Dr Rice suggests that growth patterns and genetic influences could be brought together in an epigenetics perspective for causal mechanisms.', 1328272200, 1328275800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Speech-Language & Hearing, University of Kansas, USA.'),
(560, 624, 'Dr Markus Neumann', 'Distracter faces are difficult to ignore. Faces that are entirely irrelevant to an ongoing task are being processed even in ''high load'' conditions that promote distracter inhibition for non-­face stimulus categories. Distracter face processing can, however, be reduced by adding a second face to a display. In my talk, I will report ERP- and behavioral evidence for such capacity limitations in face processing. Additionally, I will present new data from a series of experiments on ''set averaging'' for famous faces. It has recently been suggested that information from multiple faces, presented simultaneously for a brief time (''set''), may efficiently proceed in form of a statistical value such as the ''mean/average'' from the set (e.g., mean emotion, Haberman & Whitney, 2009). Our data suggests that such abstractive coding can occur for facial identity information, even when famous faces were shown in the set. In contrast to earlier set averaging studies, where memory for the set instances was extremely poor, participants in our experiments were highly accurate for famous set faces. This seems to suggest that participants can extract abstractive and instance-­based representations simultaneously.', 1325592000, 1325595600, 77, 62, NULL, 'General Psychology and Cognitive Neuroscience, Friedrich Schiller University of Jena, Germany.'),
(561, 625, 'Dr Karin Verspoor', 'The biomedical literature is a tremendously rich source of biomedical knowledge. It is, however, becoming increasingly challenging for biomedical researchers to keep up with this literature due to the exponential growth in publication and the simultaneous breakdown of disciplinary boundaries. While tools to find relevant literature are improving, and natural language processing can play an important role in concept-based indexing of the literature, there is also tremendous value in supporting biomedical knowledge discovery from the literature more directly; i.e. to utilize text mining techniques to support analysis of biological data sets. I will specifically discuss our efforts to support protein function prediction with evidence from the literature, as well as the use of information extracted from the literature in the context of analysis and interpretation of results derived from genome-scale experiments.', 1330081200, 1330084800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Biomedical Informatics Team, NICTA.'),
(562, 626, 'Associate Professor Nicolas Fay', 'Human communicaCon systems evolve and socio-­cultural processes play an important role in this process. The cultural mechanisms that guide this evoluCon are not well understood. Using a laboratory study that is extended by computer simulaCons, we test three mechanisms through which human communicaCon systems may evolve: neutral driI, local coordinaCon and selecCon. Our results indicate strong support for a selecCon based account.', 1329998400, 1330002000, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, University of Western Australia.'),
(563, 627, 'Professor Kevin D Haggerty', 'Surveillance is a key aspect of contemporary industrialised Western societies. The now extensive literature on the current dynamics of surveillance has, however, curiously overlooked how a host of non-human phenomena have been incorporated into quite different surveillance-related agendas. This talk provides a general overview of some of the ways in which such surveillance operates, pointing to some of the broader social and political consequences that flow from recognising the broad dynamics of surveillance and/of nature.', 1330011000, 1330018200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Criminology and Sociology, University of Alberta, Canada.'),
(564, 628, 'Professor Marit Westergaard', 'Children acquiring languages such as English, German or Dutch typically go through a phase where they produce non-finite root clauses, often referred to as the Optional Infinitive (OI) stage. But there is a difference between English on the one hand and the other Germanic languages on the other with respect to the occurrence of non-finite wh-questions: while there is a high number of OIs in English in this context, non-finite wh-questions are virtually non-existent in child data of e.g. German or Swedish. This is often argued to be due to the early setting of the V2 parameter: Verb movement only applies to finite verbs and children will therefore produce exclusively finite wh-questions. This paper provides acquisition data showing that this finding also holds for Norwegian. However, considering the variation that exists across languages wrt V2, this paper argues that there is no V2 parameter and that children instead are sensitive to fine syntactic distinctions in the input (micro-cues). On this view, both English and Norwegian have restricted V2 in wh-questions, and the difference between the two languages cannot be due to a parameter setting. The paper also shows that there is no causal correlation between finiteness and word order in this context. Comparing a considerable amount of Norwegian and English child data, it is argued that children’s non-finite root clauses are generally caused by a problem realizing auxiliaries, in both languages, and the difference between English and Norwegian is due to the type of verb typically required in wh-questions (auxiliaries vs. lexical verbs).', 1329913800, 1329917400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Faculty of Humanities, Social Sciences and Education, University of Tromsø, Norway.'),
(565, 629, 'Professor Marit Westergaard', 'This talk presents the results of three studies, all involving determiners and definiteness in some way: The first is a corpus study of the acquisition of grammatical gender in Norwegian in two bilingual English-Norwegian children, comparing them to two monolingual children. Our results show that, while the acquisition of suffixed forms is unproblematic (i.e. definite singular and plural forms), the children experience problems with gender agreement on indefinite articles, possessives and so-called double definite forms. The second study focuses on the acquisition of word order and definiteness in possessive constructions in Norwegian, where two word orders are possible (Poss-N or N-Poss, the latter also requiring definiteness marked on the noun itself). The bilingual children are shown to have an early preference for Poss-N, even though N-Poss is by far the most frequent word order in the input. The third study considers these possessive constructions in attrited speakers, where word order is found to be intact, while definiteness is vulnerable. Our results are discussed in terms of issues such as gender vs. declension classes and frequency vs. complexity.', 1329919200, 1329922800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Faculty of Humanities, Social Sciences and Education, University of Tromsø, Norway.'),
(566, 630, 'Professor Marit Westergaard', 'This paper discusses different approaches to language acqui­sition in relation to children’s acquisition of word order in wh-questions in English and Norwegian. While traditional generative models assert that children set major word order parameters and thus acquire a rule of subject-auxiliary inversion or generalized verb second (V2) at an early stage, some constructivist work argues that English-speaking children are simply reproducing frequent wh-word + auxiliary combi­na­tions in the input. The paper questions both approaches, re-evaluates some pre­vious work, and provides some further data, concluding that the acqui­sition of wh-questions must be the result of a rule-based process. Based on variation in adult grammars, a cue-based model to language acqui­sition is presented, according to which children are sen­si­tive to minor cues in the input, called micro-cues. V2 is not considered to be one major parameter, but several smaller-scale cues, which are responsible for children’s lack of syntactic (over-)generalization in the acquisition process (often referred to as conservative learning).', 1329741000, 1329744600, 77, 62, NULL, 'Faculty of Humanities, Social Sciences and Education, University of Tromsø, Norway.'),
(567, 631, 'Pierre Jacob', 'This informal talk considers the generic problem of performing Bayesian inference in a state-space model with observation process y, state process x and fixed parameter theta. Bayesian inference is the problem of estimating the law of the parameter theta given the observations. In state-space models the likelihood is intractable in most cases, but it may be unbiasedly estimated by a particle filter, for any fixed theta. This motivates a few recent algorithms, which are heavily based on standard algorithms like the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm, the Gibbs sampler or the Iterated Batch Importance Sampling algorithm. These algorithms remain "ideal" here because of the intractability of the likelihood. However one can try to "replace" the likelihood values (whenever they are needed during these algorithms) by unbiased estimates obtained by particle filters. These lead to the Particle MCMC methods (Andrieu et al., 2010) and SMC "square" (Chopin et al., 2012). These new algorithms have the very remarkable property of being "exact", ie they target the correct posterior distribution at each iteration t, despite the intractability of the likelihood increments. I''ll try to underline the usefulness and the potential of these methods.', 1329746400, 1329750000, 77, 62, NULL, 'CEREMADE, Université Paris-Dauphine, France.'),
(568, 632, 'Dr James Curran', 'This talk will consist of two halves (or possibly three since I tend to get over excited). Firstly, I will give a ''state of the union'' style summary of what''s going on in Schwa Lab: CCG parsing, named entities, the Computable News project, and what we submitted to EACL, NAACL and ACL. Secondly, I am going to talk about my ARC fellowship project: "Parsing the web: exploiting redundancy to understand language". The central idea of this proposal is to exploit the redundancy of simple facts in web-scale quantities of text to identify constraints on the syntactic analysis of more complex sentences, and then to use these sentences as partially annotated training data. I''ll discuss the current engineering and scientific progress on the project.', 1329476400, 1329480000, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Information Technologies, University of Sydney.'),
(569, 633, 'Professor Ludo Verhoeven', 'Much of the research on the development of children’s word decoding to date has involved the English language, which has a highly irregular orthography with many inconsistencies and complexities. For English-speaking children, the foremost task in learning to read is thus to crack the code for unfamiliar words and, in most studies, the focus has therefore been on accurate word identification as opposed to decoding speed. However, there is clear evidence that the ease of word decoding may vary across languages depending on their so-called orthographic depth. Alphabetic orthographies differ in the degree to which they deviate in a principled manner from their underlying phonetic representations and thus in the extent to which deeper lexical/linguistic information is preserved. The primary focus of this talk is on the acquisition of reading in Dutch. The Dutch language presents an interesting case because Dutch orthography is largely phonemic and much more consistent than English. To begin with, the development of Dutch word decoding across the elementary grades will be highlighted. Therefore, we will explore the development of speed and accuracy, as well as the relationship between decoding abilities for different word patterns. Moreover, the role of morphology in learning to read will be discussed. Finally, a perspective on the role of lexical quality in reading comprehension will be presented.', 1341244800, 1341250200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Behavioural Science Institute, Radboud University Nijmegen, The Netherlands.'),
(570, 634, 'Dr Karen Croot', 'Two important issues for the clinical management of primary progressive aphasia are the differential diagnosis between the logopenic and nonfluent subtypes of progressive aphasia, and the need for evidence about the effectiveness of language and communication interventions for this client group. In this talk, I will present results from studies related to these two issues. Study 1 suggests that attention to the apraxic versus phonological errors in speech production can assist with differential diagnosis between the logopenic and nonfluent subtypes. Study 2 is an impairment-directed word retrieval treatment for people with logopenic and nonfluent progressive aphasia. Results for the first two participants show a treatment effect as predicted on the retrieval of words in a picture naming task, but no generalisation to use of these words in a sample of connected speech.', 1338640200, 1338643800, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, University of Sydney.'),
(571, 635, 'Johannes Höhne', 'Brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) based on event related potentials (ERPs) strive for offering communication pathways which are independent of muscle activity. Various paradigms that utilize auditory or visual stimuli were recently presented. All those paradigms rely on the difference in the evoked potentials for attended (target) and unattended (non-target) stimuli. Thus, the choice of stimuli for any kind of ERPs-based paradigm is crucial. This problem will be introduced and outcome of several studies will be discussed that show how to improve classification accuracy and BCI performance by using optimized stimuli.', 1326816000, 1326821400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Machine Learning Laboratory, Berlin Institute of Technology, Germany.'),
(572, 636, 'Dr Marina Nespor', 'SISSA – ERC PASCAL Project In past work, we have proposed that a revised version of the Iambic-Trochaic Law (ITL) at the phrasal level accounts for the relative order of heads and complements, both cross-linguistically and within one language (Nespor, Shukla et al. 2008). Given the sensitivity of infants to prosody, we also suggested that the ITL could lead infants to the acquisition of the basic word order of their language of exposure. In this talk I will present experiments that show that adult participants group sequences of syllables that vary either in duration or in pitch as predicted by ITL. Results showing that 7-month-old infants are sensitive to pitch but not duration distinctions will also be presented and discussed (Bion, Benavides & Nespor 2011). The ITL has first been proposed to account for grouping in music (Bolton 1894; Woodrow, 1951): it is thus not exclusively a linguistic grouping mechanism, but more generally it accounts for grouping of auditory stimuli. The question I will address in the final part of my talk is whether the ITL can account for grouping also in the visual domain (Peña, Bion & Nespor 2011).', 1326715200, 1326675600, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, University of Milano-Bicocca, Italy.'),
(573, 637, 'Dr Melissa Slavin', 'Background: Early diagnosis of dementia is crucial, and research is focussed on the best indicators of cognitive decline. The opinion of the individual and/or their informant is taken into account by clinicians assessing for dementia, and is part of the diagnostic criteria for the intermediate stage of Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI). These so-called “subjective cognitive complaints” (SCCs) have not been well validated or operationalised however. Further, while some studies have found SCCs predict progression to dementia, to date there has been no evaluation of which type (participant/informant, memory/non-memory) or severity of complaints are most sensitive to progression to dementia, or indeed progression from normal to MCI. In the current studies we aimed to examine the relationship between SCCs and objective cognitive impairment, the influence of mood and personality variables, and to assess whether SCCs at baseline could predict cognitive decline or diagnostic classification at two year follow-up. Methods: Participants were drawn from the Sydney Memory and Ageing Study, a longitudinal study of 1037 community-dwelling older adults initially aged 70-90 years. A subsample of 637 participants who completed a comprehensive assessment including 15 memory and 9 non-memory complaint questions, personality and mood questionnaires, and neuropsychological testing at baseline were included. An informant answered 15 memory and 4 non-memory complaint questions, and rated their functional independence. Each participant was classified into normal, MCI, or dementia groups. Repeat testing was conducted two years later. Results: Overall, 95.5% of participants or their informants endorsed at least one SCC at baseline. Informants were most accurate in endorsing a complaint when objective cognitive impairment was present. Regression analysis showed that psychological factors explained the number of complaints more than cognitive performance. Participant memory complaints predicted MCI, and sum of informant memory complaints predicted dementia two years later. Informant memory complaints also predicted decline in memory scores and global cognitive scores over two years. Conclusion: We question the usefulness of SCCs as a criterion for MCI at a single time point due to their high prevalence and their relationship to psychological factors. They seem more useful longitudinally however. Participant memory complaints were related to an MCI classification after two years, perhaps indicating greater sensitivity of self-observation; and informant memory complaints were better at predicting dementia, as well as decline in memory and global cognition scores after two years, perhaps reflecting greater specificity of decline observed by others.', 1321977600, 1321983000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Dementia Collaborative Research Centre - Assessment and Better Care, School of Psychiatry, University of New South Wales.'),
(574, 638, 'Dr Yaffa Yeshurun', 'Our visual experience is affected by both the spatial and the temporal aspects of the scene we are viewing. Understanding how our system processes both aspects is crucial for a comprehensive view of visual perception, yet we know considerably more about the spatial than the temporal domain. This is especially true of our knowledge of spatial attention. In this talk I will first present a mechanism of transient attention that takes into account the tradeoffs between segregation and integration processes and between the spatial and temporal domains. Specifically, I will suggest that attention facilitates spatial segregation and temporal integration but impairs their counterparts –spatial integration and temporal segregation. Support for this mechanism is derived from various studies that explored the effects of transient attention on various temporal and spatial processes such as enhancement of spatial resolution, degradation of temporal resolution, prolongation of perceived duration, prolongation of temporal integration, and degradation of spatial integration. I will further suggest a possible physiological instantiation of this mechanism: an attentional preference for parvocellular over magnocellular neuronal activity. Finally I will present evidence in support of this physiological instantiation. This will include evidence from different stimuli and paradigms including attentional effects on selective adaptation, isoluminant stimuli, reversed apparent motion, and the steadypedestal and pulsed-pedestal paradigms.', 1321372800, 1321380000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Institute of Information Processing and Decision Making, University of Haifa .'),
(575, 639, 'Dr Hélène Deacon', 'As children learn to read, they learn about the ways in which letters do and do not combine, or orthographic processing. For example, that the letters –ts often occur at the ends of words and –tzrarely does so (e.g., as in the unusual spelling of Ritz). There has been debate as to whether children learn about these patterns through their reading (e.g., Ehri, 2005) or whether children’s knowledge of these patterns helps them to learn to read. I will present our new research that provides the first empirical demonstration that children learn about these patterns through their reading. I will then review our recent evidence of how children learning to read in two languages build up an understanding of letter-patterns. We have shown that orthographic processing skill is built up in a manner that is transferable to reading across languages, specifically when these languages share the same writing systems (such as English-French) and not when the languages do not share a writing system (such as English-Chinese). I will consider the developmental and cross-linguistic implications of these findings.', 1313078400, 1313085600, 77, 62, 0, 'Department of Psychology, Dalhousie University.'),
(576, 640, 'Dr Glenn Carruthers', 'The rubber hand illusion (RHI) is the experience of an artificial body part being a real body part and the experience of touch coming from that model. An explanation of this illusion takes significant steps towards explaining the experience of embodiment in one’s own body. I present a new qualitative cognitive model to explain the RHI. I argue that the sense of embodiment arises when an on-line representation of the candidate body part is represented as matching an off-line prototype representation of what one’s body is usually like. The distinguishing feature of this model is the off-line body representation and the process of matching an on-line model to an off-line model, both of which are to be understood in terms of a conceptual space. I close by suggesting that Tsakiris’ model cannot not account for non-visual forms of the illusion and considering future directions for completing the ‘conceptual space’ model.', 1319558400, 1319563800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Berlin School of Mind and Brain, Humbolt University.'),
(577, 641, 'Stephen Crain', '', 1318953600, 1318957200, 77, 62, NULL, 'ARC Centre of Excellence in Cognition & Its Disorders, Macquarie University.'),
(578, 642, 'Dr Holger Wiese', 'Presenting as part of the symposium: "Neural, perceptual and cognitive mechanisms involved in recognising other-race and other-age faces”. Humans are better at remembering faces of their own ethnic and age groups as compared to other-race and other-age faces. Theoretical accounts for these so-called own-race and own-age biases emphasize varying amounts of contact or expertise with faces of different groups as an underlying mechanism. In this talk, I will present both behavioral and ERP evidence in support of this account. First, long-term expertise with a limited number of other-race faces reduces both the own-race bias and its ERP correlate in the occipito-temporal P2. However, while ERP correlates of same- and other-race processing during learning depend on situational factors such as task demands, the behavioral own-race bias does not. Second, an own-age bias has been demonstrated repeatedly in young adult participants. Whether a corresponding bias for elderly participants emerges was found to depend on the amount of contact wit same-age people. Third, results from a combined own-race and own-age bias experiment demonstrated differences in the neural processes underlying the two effects. In sum, these findings suggest a lack of expertise with "out-group" faces as one mechanism mediating both the own-age and own-race bias, while the exact memory related neural processes for the two phenomena appear to differ.', 1316092800, 1316095200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Friedrice Schiller University of Jena.'),
(579, 643, 'Dr Kate Crookes', 'Presenting as part of the symposium: "Neural, perceptual and cognitive mechanisms involved in recognising other-race and other age faces". Recent evidence suggests that the strength of holistic and/or configural processing may underlie the own-race advantage in face memory. While Caucasian participants have consistently demonstrated larger effects for Caucasian over Asian faces, the pattern for Asian participants is less clear. I will present two experiments exploring holistic and configural processing in Chinese participants. The first compares holistic processing for own- and other-race faces using the part-whole effect. The second looks at sensitivity to horizontal vs vertical spacing changes in upright and inverted faces.', 1316088000, 1316090400, 77, 62, NULL, 'University of Hong Kong.'),
(580, 644, 'Prof William Hayward', 'Presenting at the symposium: "Neural, perceptual and cognitive mechanisms involved in recognising other-race and other-age faces" Many studies have shown that own-race faces are easier to remember the other-race faces, a phenomenon called the other-race effect(ORE). In recent years a number of papers have been published showing an apparent impairment in holistic processing of other-race faces, using paradigms such as the part-whole task or the composite task. Using data collected from Hong Kong Chinese and Australia Caucasian participants, I will argue that the case for a perceptual basis for the ORE appears to have been over-stated. Rather than being due to impaired perceptual representations of faces, it appears that the ORE is largely due to an impairment in matching the perceptual representation of a face with memory representations (in either short-term or long-term memory).', 1316090400, 1316092800, 77, 62, NULL, 'ARC Centre of Excellence in Cognition & Its Disorders, University of Hong Kong.'),
(581, 645, 'Dr Jon Brock', 'Currently, Jon Brock is investigating links between cognitive and neural-level mechanisms of language impairments in autism. He adapts varied methological approaches to investigate this, including behavioural testing, eye-tracking and brain imaging using magnetoencephalography (MEG) and structural MRI.', 1323428400, 1323432000, 77, 62, NULL, 'ARC Centre of Excellence in Cognition & Its Disorders, Macquarie University.'),
(582, 646, 'Joanne Taylor', 'How do readers of English learn to read words with both regular spelling-sound mappings (such as FEW, NEW, or STEW) and irregular mappings (such as SEW), and to generalize this knowledge in order to read pseudowords (such as TEW)? My talk will explore these questions, focusing on three pieces of research. First, I will present a meta-analysis of neuroimaging studies of single-word reading. This describes the patterns of brain activation observed during word vs. pseudoword and irregular vs. regular word reading, framed within the dual route and triangle models of reading. Second I will introduce an artificial orthography paradigm, developed during my PhD, in which adults learn to read novel words written in novel symbols. Using this method we explored how spelling-sound consistency and frequency influence learning to read. Finally, I will discuss data from an fMRI experiment in which we have adapted this paradigm to ask how the neural systems underpinning orthographic learning are similar to and different from those supporting object-label learning.', 1314115200, 1314120600, 77, 62, NULL, 'MRC Cognition and Brain Sciences Unit, Cambridge University.'),
(583, 647, 'Joel Pearson', 'Our ability to consciously experience the world around us has been dubbed one of the most amazing yet enigmatic processes under scientific investigation today. However, our ability to imagine the world around us in the absence of stimulation from that world is perhaps even more amazing. This talk will cover new methods for investigating mental imagery and its role in visual perception, associative learning and short-term visual working memory.', 1297180800, 1297186200, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, UNSW.'),
(584, 648, 'Professor Walter Sinnott-Armstrong', 'Psychopaths are less than 1% of the population but commit over 30% of the violent crime in most modern societies. Some experts claim that psychopaths make moral judgments but do not care about morality. Others argue that psychopaths do not really make moral judgments but only pretend to do so. I will present recent data as well as experimental plans to address this dispute. These results can be important for treatment, prediction, and punishment policies as well as philosophical debates about the nature and basis of moral judgment. Prof Sinnott-Armstrong is a Distinguished Visitor at the Macquarie Research Centre for Agency Values and Ethics and this is a joint CAVE/MACCS seminar.', 1311696000, 1311701400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Philosophy and the Kenan Institute for Ethics, Duke University.'),
(585, 649, 'Chris Chambers', 'The human cognitive control system supports a diverse repertoire of behaviours, including attention, motor planning, working memory and higher reasoning. In this talk I will focus on one central facet of cognitive control: the ability to update behaviour following changes in the environment. Psychological theories have argued that behavioural updating requires the activation of task goals that drive lower systems. For instance, when updating requires behavioural inhibition, the control system activates a â€˜stopâ€™ goal to countermand planned or ongoing motor activity. Other forms of updating can involve the programming and selection of alternative responses and the reorienting of selective attention. A convergence of evidence suggests that behavioural updating is supported by a distributed neural network, with a central hub in the prefrontal cortex. Yet precisely how this network supports updating is controversial and poorly understood. In this talk I will summarise some of our recent studies, which contrasted competing accounts of prefrontal updating using repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS). Our findings confirm that the right inferior frontal cortex is crucial for behavioural updating, but that contrary to previous suggestions it is not uniquely important for inhibiting behaviour. Instead, the IFJ appears to be important for updating the focus of visual attention while the more ventral IFG (pars opercularis) updates corresponding action plans â€“ regardless of whether such plans are inhibitory or excitatory. Overall, we believe our findings help reconcile an ongoing debate about neural systems of cognitive control in the human inferior frontal cortex.', 1309276800, 1309282200, 77, 62, NULL, 'School of Psychology, Cardiff University, UK.'),
(586, 650, 'Todd Horowitz', 'Visual behavior takes place in a world that is dynamic and extended in both time and space. Tracking moving objects is a key skill necessary to interact with this environment. In order to get a picture of the cognitive and neural architectures underlying tacking, we need to answer a few questions. Do we track objects in parallel or in series? In what frame of reference are tracked objects represented? What are the neural signatures of tracking, and what might be the brain networks involved? I will address these questions, and start to fill in the picture.', 1308067200, 1308072600, 77, 62, NULL, 'Visual Attention Laboratory, Brigham and Women''s Hospital, Ophthalmology, Harvard Medical School, Boston, USA.'),
(587, 651, 'Ken Forster', 'Lexical co-occurrence refers to the similarity of the co-occurrence vectors of words, such that if two words tend to have similar profiles of occurrence with other words, they are said to have a high co-occurrence relationship. The present study examines whether meaning selection for an ambiguous word can be biased by the prior presentation of a word that shares a strong co-occurrence relationship with the ambiguous word under one of its meanings, despite the absence of any plausibility support. A â€œmazeâ€ self-paced reading experiment examined highly implausible sentences with balanced ambiguous words. The ambiguous word was preceded by a word that shares a strong co-occurrence relationship with one of its senses. The effectiveness of the priming stimulus was assessed in terms of the magnitude of a garden-path effect at a subsequent disambiguating word.. Additional experiments demonstrated that this ambiguity resolution effect could not be explained in terms of spreading activation. In addition, an eye-tracking experiment revealed a pattern of results comparable to that of the maze task experiment, indicating that this effect is not an artifact of the maze procedure. These results are taken to support a heuristic for lexical ambiguity resolution that is driven by relatively low-level intralexical connections based on lexical co-occurrence.', 1308061800, 1308067200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, University of Arizona, Tucson.'),
(588, 652, 'Dr Nadine Kloth', 'We gain a lot of different information from faces, even when they are unfamiliar to us. For example, we can almost instantly determine the gender or emotional expression of a face, evaluate how attractive we find it, and decide whether or not that person is looking at us. Although most of these different facial aspects seem to be independent of each other, earlier research suggests that at least some of them interact. Following this line of research, the talk focuses on a potential interaction of attractiveness and gaze perception, examining the question of whether we are more likely to perceive attractive faces as looking at us.', 1306411200, 1306414800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Psychology, University of Western Australia.'),
(589, 653, 'Dr Linda Jeffery', 'Face recognition performance improves during childhood, not reaching adult levels until late adolescence. Likewise, face-sensitive brain regions to not appear fully mature until a similar age. Recognition of faces across changes in viewpoint appears particularly slow to develop, suggesting that children''s face representations are more view-specific than those of adults. We used face aftereffects to investigate whether children encode faces in a more view-specific way than adults. Using both the figural aftereffect (E1) and the identity aftereffect (E2) we showed that 8 year-old children''s aftereffects transferred across substantial changes in viewpoint. Indeed, there was a trend for greater transfer among children than adults. In adults, transfer of aftereffects across views has been argued to reflect the operation of neurons broadly tuned to a limited number of viewpoints and/or to the operation view-invariant neurons. Our results suggest that changes in viewpoint children''s neural coding of face viewpoint is similar to that of adults.', 1305806400, 1305810000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Psychology, University of Western Australia.'),
(590, 654, 'Dr Richard Morey', 'Since its introduction by Fisher in the early 20th century, null hypothesis significance testing has been controversial. However, the controversy has not stopped the null hypothesis significance test from becoming the dominant method of inference in psychology. Despite its flaws, there has been no serious contender for a replacement. In recent years, a number of developments in Bayesian statistics have finally made the Bayes factor, introduced by Jeffreys nearly 80 years ago, a viable replacement for inference by p values. I will describe a number of recent advances, including replacements for the t test, regression, ANOVA, and ongoing work in adapting these methods for time-series data.', 1305648000, 1305653400, 77, 62, 0, 'Psychometrics and Statistics, University of Groningen.'),
(591, 655, 'Louise Ewing', 'Face processing atypicalities observed in children with autism spectrum conditions (ASC) have been suggested to reflect atypical reward value of social stimuli, which leads to reduced interest and experience with faces. This claim was tested by assessing the relative reward values of attractive and unattractive faces, inverted faces and cars for cognitively able children with ASC (n=35)and matched typical developing children (n=35). Specifically, we measured the effort participants exerted to view these images in a key pressing task. Despite showing impaired performance on a basic face recognition task, children with ASC were highly sensitive to variations in the reward value (attractiveness) of faces. Critically, there were no significant group differences in the reward value of faces, inverted faces, or cars. Atypicalities in processing reward therefore cannot explain the face processing difficulties observed among these children with ASC, prompting consideration of alternative theoretical accounts.', 1323086400, 1323090000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Psychology, University of Western Australia.'),
(592, 656, 'Ami Eidels', 'People must often process multiple sources of information and respond appropriately. When driving a car, for instance, we must notice and respond to other cars cutting our lane, the lights turning red, or pedestrians crossing the road. People may process each of these information sources one at a time (i.e., serially) or at the same time (in parallel). Also, our responses may be based on either source of information alone (â€˜stop as soon as you see red light or a pedestrian crossingâ€™), or on both (â€˜go on only when the light is green and the cross-walk is clear). These processing aspects are referred to as architecture and stopping-rule, respectively. Another interesting question concerns workload capacity â€“ is it more demanding to process one signal (say, red light) than it is to process two (light and pedestrian)? Finally, the question of (in)dependence asks whether two sources of information are processed independently from one another. In this talk I introduce a non-parametric framework, known as Systems Factorial Technology (developed by James Townsend and his colleagues), which allows to asses the above properties based on response-time data. I shall demonstrate how it was used to study classic phenomena such as Stroop and visual search. If time permits, we can discuss potential ways of using this method in research conducted in MACCS.', 1317830400, 1317835800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Newcastle Cognition Lab, School of Psychology, University of Newcastle.'),
(593, 657, 'Dr Peter Nestor', '', 1317817800, 1317821400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Cambridge Neuroscience, Cambridge University & Addenbrooke''s Hospital.'),
(594, 658, 'Stefanie Abel', '', 1299340800, 1299346200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Sections Neuropsychology & Clinical Research of Cognition, University Hospital RWTH, Aachen, Germany.'),
(595, 659, 'Michael Hornberger', '', 1312452000, 1312459200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Neuroscience Research Australia, University of New South Wales.'),
(596, 660, 'Anna Mitchell', '', 1312452000, 1312459200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Psychology Department, Oxford University.'),
(597, 661, 'Distinguished Professor Stephen Crain', 'Suppose you overhear someone say "He said Barry ordered sushi". Even if you don''t have any idea who "he" is, you know one thing for certain - that "he" is not Barry. In other sentences, though, the pronoun "he" and the name "Barry" can refer to the same person, as in "Barry said he ordered sushi" or "While he was holding the pasta, Barry ordered sushi." Whenever a pronoun and a name must refer to different individuals in a linguistic structure, this is referred to as ''non-coreference.'' Interestingly, non-coreference crops up in discourse. Suppose you overhear two people talking. One says "I know where he is hiding" and the other replies "Me too. In Barry''s basement". Again, one thing you know for certain is that whoever "he" might be, "he" is not Barry. In this talk, I will argue that the same linguistic principles that enforce non-coreference in ''connected'' statements like "He said Barry ordered sushi" also apply in ''disconnected'' discourse sequences, such that the pronoun "he" in one speaker''s utterance becomes connected to the name "Barry" in another speaker''s utterance. Finally, I will present evidence that four-year-old English-speaking children and Mandarin-speaking children know how to connect pronouns and names in ordinary declarative sentences and in discourse. And they know much more than this, since the same linguistic principles that govern the connections between pronouns and names are also used in deriving the interpretation of many other linguistic expressions, including disjunction (English "or", Mandarin "huozhe"), and negative polarity items (English "any", Mandarin "renhe").', 1307203200, 1307208600, 77, 62, NULL, 'Macquarie University, ARC CoE in Cognition & its Disorders (CCD).'),
(598, 662, 'Professor Rebecca Treiman', 'Learning to write, and learning to interpret writing, is critical for success in modern societies. In this talk, I provide an overview of spelling development in toddlers through to teenagers and adults. I discuss research studies with learners of several different languages, including English, Portuguese, and Chinese. The findings show that statistical learning and knowledge about language play important roles in learning to spell. Implications for teaching are also discussed.', 1301414400, 1301419800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, Washington University in St. Louis.'),
(599, 663, 'Steve Most', 'Your mind doesn''t always see what your eyes see. Despite deeply held intuitions, conscious perception does not depend solely on where we turn our eyes. Rather, it is robustly influenced by expectations, motivations, and even emotions. Given that people navigate the world with different priorities in mind and with different "affective styles", understanding such mechanisms can provide insight into why different people can witness the same event while perceiving it differently. In this talk, I will describe work in my lab that investigates how motivation and emotion help shape perception.', 1301061600, 1301067000, 77, 62, NULL, 'University of Delaware, University of Delaware.'),
(600, 664, 'Professor A. Mark Williams', 'Many factors contribute to the development of expertise. The contribution of hereditary characteristics and the importance of practice, instruction, and the mentorship of significant others such as parents and coaches are often debated. A common or lay opinion is that elite performers are born rather than made, creating the perception that less â€˜giftedâ€™ individuals may continually strive to reach excellence without making the necessary gains needed to become experts in the domain. However, recent research in the sport and cognitive sciences has indicated that individuals achieve excellence through many hours of deliberate, purposeful practice with the specific intention of improving performance. Typically, for example, elite athletes have to devote in excess of 10,000 hours of practice to achieve excellence, regardless of sport. This commitment and continual engagement in practice is the most important determining factor on the path to excellence. Hereditary factors may also be important in helping individuals develop the necessary â€˜rage to masterâ€™ (i.e., the commitment and motivation to persist in practice over many years). The proposal is that expertise develops as a result of adaptations to the unique environmental constraints imposed during practice and performance. In this presentation, an attempt is made to highlight the practice history profiles of elite performers, with a particular focus on sport, and to illustrate through reference to recent empirical research the type of psychological adaptations that arise as a result of extended involvement in practice. A particular focus will be on the development of perceptual-cognitive skills such as anticipation and decision making in sports like soccer and tennis, as well as in other domains such as law enforcement and medical diagnosis. Practical implications for talent selection and development are highlighted, with attempts to illustrate the nature and type of practice activities most likely to help nurture future generations of experts.', 1300809600, 1300815000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Faculty of Health Sciences, University of Sydney.'),
(601, 665, 'Professor Leslie Zebrowitz', '', 1299168000, 1299173400, 77, 62, NULL, 'Psychology, Brandeis University.'),
(602, 666, 'Megumi Kobayashi', '', 1296748800, 1296754200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Chuo University, Chuo University.'),
(603, 667, 'Yumiko Otsuka', '', 1296748800, 1296754200, 77, 62, NULL, 'Chuo University, Chuo University.'),
(604, 668, 'Professor Ulrich Ansorge', 'As humans we are not aware of all our psychic processes. But what exactly are the capabilities and limits of unaware or unconscious processing? One way to study these questions is by human vision. Humans are able to process visual stimuli even if they do not see these stimuli. This has been demonstrated in masked-priming experiments with human participants. In these experiments, visual masking prevents the participantsâ€™ awareness of a priming stimulus. Nonetheless, the priming stimulus affects the participantsâ€™ behavior. In my talk, I will first explain the masked-priming procedure and then review some of the major conclusions that have been drawn from masked-priming research about the types and the limits of unaware processing. The presentation concludes with a discussion of the pros and cons of the method and the possible division of labor between conscious/aware and unconscious/unaware processing.', 1294070400, 1294075800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Institute for Basic Psychological Research, University of Vienna.'),
(605, 669, 'Elisabetta Ladavas', 'The purpose of the talk is to present new evidence showing the relevance of subcortical and cortical structures in the processing of visual information and to discuss their relevance for understanding perception. The topic will be addressed by referring to different effects called â€œAffective blindsightâ€ and â€œCrossmodal blindsightâ€. Affective blindsight refers to the uncanny ability of patients with cortical blindness to discriminate reliably the emotional valence of stimuli they cannot consciously perceive. I will present new behavioural and EEG findings showing the presence of implicit recognition of fearful faces in a sample of eight hemianopic patients, probably mediated by a colliculo-amygdalar pathway bypassing the striate cortex. â€œCrossmodal blindsightâ€ refers to the phenomenon by which an unseen visual stimulus presented in the blind field can influence the detection/localization of an auditory stimulus. I will examine on-line and off-line effects of audio-visual stimulation on the visual and spatial impairments following damage to the geniculo-striate pathway. I will demonstrate that an improvement in spatial orienting can be obtained not only when an on-line response is required, but also after either a brief or a long adaptation to audio-visual stimulation. These findings suggest that the mechanisms subserving audio-visual perceptual learning are still active after a damage to the geniculo-striate pathway; this perceptual learning is probably mediated by the collicular-extrastriate pathway. Then, we will explore the possibility that such a system might represent the neural correlate of sensory compensation when a sensory modality has been damaged by a cerebral lesion.', 1298390400, 1298395800, 77, 62, NULL, 'Centro Studi e Ricerche in Neuroscienze Cognitive, University of Bologna.');
INSERT INTO `seminar` (`id`, `conference`, `speaker`, `abstract`, `start_time`, `end_time`, `university`, `department`, `about_speaker`, `affiliation`) VALUES
(606, 670, 'Professor Simon Garrod', 'Recent advances in computer animation and cognitive neuroimaging have created powerful tools to study human social interaction. This talk will concentrate on what we are now learning about the specialized brain networks that underlie ''first impressions'' based on facial appearance, speech and bodily movement. It will show how such first impressions determine who gets elected to the US Senate or who is chosen to run the biggest corporations. The talk will also touch on other automatic outcomes of social interaction such the interactive alignment of actions and emotions and how we come to pull together when we interact. The research indicates that humans are intrinsically social animals in a way that few other creatures are.', 1298372400, 1298376000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Cognitive Psychology, University of Glasgow.'),
(607, 671, 'Alison Gopnik', '', 1297785600, 1297791000, 77, 62, NULL, 'Department of Psychology, University of California at Berkeley.'),
(608, 672, 'Dr. Nathan Holmes', 'The basolateral amygdala (BLA) and perirhinal cortex (PRh) mediate distinct aspects of learning and memory. Here, we used rats to investigate the involvement of the BLA and PRh in acquisition and extinction of associations between two different environmental stimuli (e.g., a tone and a light). The first study shows that when one stimulus is neutral and the other is a learned danger signal, infusion of the GABAA agonist, muscimol, or the N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor (NMDAr) antagonist, ifenprodil, into the BLA impairs associative formation. However, when both stimuli are neutral, acquisition and extinction of the association between them is unaffected by manipulations targeting the BLA. The second study reveals an opposite pattern of results following manipulations targeting the PRh: inactivation of the PRh or blockade of PRh NMDAr impairs formation and extinction of an association between two stimuli when they are both neutral, but not when one stimulus is a learned danger signal. The third and final study shows that fear shifts processing of an association between neutral stimuli from the PRh to the BLA: when training is conducted in a dangerous environment, formation and extinction of an association between two neutral stimuli is impaired by BLA inactivation or blockade of NMDAr, but unaffected by PRh inactivation. These double dissociations in the roles of the PRh and BLA in learning under different stimulus and environmental conditions imply that fear-induced activation of the amygdala changes how the brain processes sensory stimuli: Harmless stimuli are treated as potentially harmful, resulting in a shift from cortical to subcortical processing in the BLA.', 1357920000, 1357923600, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of New South Wales'),
(609, 673, 'Dr Daneial Costa', 'How would you rate your overall quality of life? People tend to have little difficulty answering this question. But how would you define quality of life? Is it possible to define quality of life? Is it desirable to define quality of life? Is it necessary? We hear about quality of life regularly. Its increasing popularity among policy-makers and economists is evident, and the term regularly finds its way into everyday conversations. Everybody knows what it means. In health research, the term has become the foundation of a budding empire, spawning an international society and several dedicated journals. Health policy decisions in many countries routinely incorporate quality of life information. So how is it defined? The brief answer is: in ways too numerous to keep track of. In this talk we’ll embark on a quest to discover how quality of life has been conceptualised, what attempts have been made to assess it (including some of our own data), and why it may not be good enough to simply accept that there is a proliferation of definitions.', 1382716800, 1382720400, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of Sydney'),
(610, 674, 'Dr Marc De Rosnay', '', 1382112000, 1382115600, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of Sydney'),
(611, 675, 'Assistant Professor Martin Guhn', 'This presentation will illustrate developmental outcomes at kindergarten, and will describe the context factors during middle childhood and early adolescence that are associated with children''s well-being. The presentation will include an overview of two projects that monitor children''s and youth'' well-being and developmental health in British Columbia: The Early Development Instrument (EDI) project and the Middle Years Development Instrument (MDI) project. The EDI project collects data on children''s developmental outcomes at kindergarten via teacher ratings, and the MDI collects data on children''s well-being and associated context factors via student self-report at age 10 and 13. This is the first time that data from the EDI and the MDI have been linked. This presentation will share empirical findings that illustrate relationships between outcomes from kindergarten to middle childhood and early adolescence, and share some knowledge translation tools that have been developed in collaboration with school districts and communities.', 1384099200, 1384102800, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of British Columbia'),
(612, 676, 'A/Prof Holly Fitch', 'Over the past decade, epidemiologic studies have identified a number of genes with significantly elevated rates of mutation among dyslexic populations. Among the most consistently replicated dyslexia risk genes are DYX1C1, DCDC2 and KIAA0319. These genes also have rodent homologs, allowing developmental functions of the protein products for these genes to be studied. Results show that all three genes play a critical role in early cortical development, and particularly so for neuronal migration. At the behavioral level, studies employing RNAi (or shRNA) gene knock-down, as well as gene deletions ("knock-outs"), show that all three genes are related to behavioral endophenotypes (also called "intermediate phenotypes") that can be mapped onto dyslexia. For example, in rat studies using embryonic transfection of neuron-progenitors with RNAi for Dyx1c1, we later found behavioral deficits in discriminating complex acoustic stimuli, working memory, and visual attention. Using identical procedures with RNAi of Kiaa0319, we found subsequent deficits in processing rapidly changing acoustic stimuli, but no deficits encoding complex (slow) stimuli nor in working memory. More recent work with a mouse KO for Dcdc2 again revealed deficits in processing short acoustic stimuli, and in working memory. The implications of these findings for our understanding of the role of gene mutations in effecting anomalies of neural circuitry -- and the relationship between genetic mutation, neural anomalies, and core or "intermediate" behavioral phenotypes underlying dyslexia -- will be discussed.', 1380297600, 1380301200, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of Connecticut'),
(613, 677, 'Dr. Tony Vladusich', 'A key unsolved problem in vision science is how the brain represents surface properties, such as lightness, transparency and gloss. I have recently introduced a novel computational approach to surface perception, known as gamut relativity, which provides a unified perspective on the processes underlying surface lightness, transparency and gloss perception. It does so by rejecting the assumption of ‘reification’—the assumption that the dimensional structure of the representation of the physical world corresponds to the dimensional structure of the physical world itself—that is widespread in psychology and neuroscience. The theory instead posits that the form of the representation underlying surface perception is more closely related to the computational division of the visual brain into parallel ON and OFF channels. This representation takes the form of a perceptual blackness-whiteness space in which a process of vector decomposition plays the key computational role. According to this view, surface lightness emerges in terms of the relationships between points falling on different black-to-white ‘gamut’ lines in blackness-whiteness space, each representing different illumination, transparency or gloss levels. In this talk, I show how gamut relativity explains some striking demonstrations of surface lightness and transparency perception recently investigated by Anderson and colleagues. I discuss, in particular, how the theory explains key elements of the “world''s largest lightness illusion” and related transparency effects. The theory provides quantitative predictions that agree with perceptual data from several experiments and suggests a number of important implications for the study of representation in vision science, psychology and neuroscience.', 1379692800, 1379696400, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of South Australia'),
(614, 678, 'Dr Joshua McGrane', 'The study of the philosophy of measurement has a rich history in the School of Psychology at the University of Sydney. It was here as both an undergraduate and postgraduate student under the teaching of Joel Michell that I was first exposed to the rigorous analysis of this fundamental scientific concept, and this education inspired an ongoing passion for this topic in my postdoctoral research. This presentation will overview my research on the evolution of scientific measurement throughout the 19th, 20th and 21st Centuries, and the divergences and convergences between the psychological and physical sciences throughout this time. I will argue that the understanding and application of measurement in psychology is predicated upon 20th century philosophies which do not form the foundation of measurement in the physical sciences. Consequently, psychologists have been blinded to important advances that have occurred in metrology into the 21st century. However, as metrology has sought to broaden its reach beyond its traditional physics base, it has embraced a definition of measurement that may be seen, to a certain extent, to vindicate psychology’s position. I will explore the extent of this vindication and argue that this broader definition of measurement is symptomatic of the creeping influence of operationism and so should not be viewed as a legitimisation of current psychological practices. Finally, I will argue that there is a scientific and moral imperative for psychology to embrace a realist conception of measurement, whether it is broadly or narrowly defined.', 1379088000, 1379091600, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of Western Australia'),
(615, 679, 'Prof Rick Richardson', 'Mental health problems are often assumed to have their roots in early-life experiences. For example, modern theories have emphasised the importance of early learning experiences in the development of adult anxiety disorders. However, memories acquired in infancy are rapidly forgotten in nearly all species (including humans). Further, recent pre-clinical research has shown that extinction of learned fear (which is the empirical basis for exposure-based therapies) leads to a loss of fear that is relatively relapse-resistant in infants. Neither of these findings fit well with the assumption that early experiences significantly contribute to later mental health problems. However, we have recently shown that early life stress (induced by maternal separation) alters the developmental trajectory for both the memory retention and the fear inhibition systems in the developing rat. That is, animals repeatedly separated from their mother early in life exhibit an earlier transition to the adult-like retention and extinction systems. In other words, these animals exhibit much longer-lasting memory than their standard-reared peers, and they also exhibit relapse-prone extinction. Further, we have also found that the infant offspring of males previously exposed to the maternal separation procedure exhibit the same developmental shifts observed in their fathers, even though they were not exposed to any early life stress. These results suggest that behavioural phenotypes putatively involved in vulnerability to later life anxiety are transmitted from father to offspring and can be detected very early in development, which is of clinical relevance for targeting and developing preventative treatments for mental health problems.', 1370793600, 1370797200, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of New South Wales'),
(616, 680, 'Dr Angela Nickerson', 'Elevated rates of psychological disorders have been documented in refugees. Little is known, however, about the mechanisms by which psychopathology develops following exposure to refugee-related trauma and torture. This presentation will outline a theoretical model that proposes pathways to adaptation following trauma and displacement. Findings from empirical studies testing components of this model will then be presented. These studies will examine the impact of both refugee experiences (trauma exposure and post-migration living difficulties) and internal processes (memory dysfunction, cognitive processes and emotion regulation) on refugee mental health. Implications of these research findings for psychological interventions will be discussed.', 1377878400, 1377882000, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of New South Wales'),
(617, 681, 'A/Prof Jennie Hudson', 'Anxiety disorders are increasingly recognized for their substantial costs to society as well as significant personal suffering. Such impacts have been found throughout the lifespan, with research increasingly focusing on child populations. Effective prevention and intervention strategies need to be informed by evidence regarding risk. Although knowledge of risk factors for anxiety disorders has not been as extensive as it has for some other problems, there is growing evidence for the importance of several factors (such as parenting, temperament) in the development of anxiety disorders. I will present recent data from our own centre examining early predictors of anxiety disorders from the preschool years through to middle childhood. I will also review recent research examining genetic, clinical and demographic predictors of outcome for children receiving cognitive behavioural treatment for anxiety disorders. The potential implications of this research for the treatment of children with anxiety disorders will be discussed.', 1377273600, 1377277200, 78, 63, NULL, 'Macquarie University'),
(618, 682, 'Dr David Sewell', 'Mathematical models allow researchers to articulate hypotheses with a degree of precision not usually found in the behavioral sciences. My research focuses on testing and developing models of the cognitive processes involved in attention, learning, memory, and decision-making. In this talk, I will discuss two projects that use models to leverage insight about different aspects of visual cognition. The first characterizes the storage capacity of visual short-term memory (VSTM) using classic signal detection models. The key analysis reveals how changes in the precision of VSTM representations under increasing memory load can be explained, in a parameter-free way, by a so-called “sample size” model. Theoretically, the result favors normalization models of VSTM that assume allocation of a finite pool of resources across stimuli. The second project investigates individual differences in the implicit learning processes thought to underpin the contextual cuing effect in visual search (i.e., the reduction in search time for arrays surreptitiously repeated over the course of an experiment, relative to novel arrays). Choice response time data were modeled using different versions of Ratcliff’s diffusion model. Model selection indices suggest that far from being a monolithic phenomenon, a variety of learning mechanisms contribute to the contextual cuing effect.', 1376668800, 1376672400, 78, 63, NULL, 'University of Melbourne'),
(619, 683, 'Dr Michael Proctor', 'New advances in magnetic resonance imaging now make it possible to acquire video sequences of human speech production, at rates up to 40 frames per second, with synchronized audio recordings (Narayanan et al. 2004; Bresch et al. 2004). This real-time MRI technology is providing new insights into the goals of speech production and phonological organization. In this talk, I will present rtMRI data on Mandarin fricatives, Arabic emphatics, French nasalization, and human beatboxing, and discuss implications for our understanding of articulatory control and phonological representation.', 1378656000, 1378659600, 78, 63, NULL, 'Macquarie University'),
(620, 684, 'Dr Dominic Dwyer', 'One product of simple exposure to similar visual stimuli is that they become easier to distinguish. This has been attributed to exposure allowing the comparison of the relevant stimuli, which in turn affords the extraction of the discriminating features. The early visual cortex and other brain areas (such as the prefrontal cortex) have been implicated in such perceptual learning effects; but the anatomical specificity within visual cortex and the relationship between sensory cortex and other brain areas has yet to be examined. Today, I begin by considering the fact that increasing the opportunity for comparison by manipulating the exposure schedule improves perceptual learning, while decreasing the opportunity for comparison using distracting stimuli attenuates perceptual learning. In addition, in an event-related fMRI study, participants were exposed to confusable pairs of faces, scenes and dot patterns, using either intermixed or blocked presentation schedules. Stimulus independent activation, correlated with the overall perceptual learning advantage was seen in frontal areas (e.g. frontal and supplementary eye fields and dorsolateral prefrontal cortex) and in early visual cortex (V1-4). In all cases, the difference in activation between exposed and novel stimuli decreased as a function of the amount of perceptual learning. Overall levels of activation differed across regions, consistent with the possibility that, as perceptual learning progresses, processing shifts from initial engagement of early visual regions to higher order visual areas. Similar relationships were observed when contrasting intermixed with blocked exposure, suggesting that the opportunity for comparison primarily influences the amount, rather than the nature, of perceptual learning.', 1360339200, 1360342800, 78, 63, NULL, 'Cardiff University'),
