(682, 746, 'Mehran Norafkan', '', 1370512800, 0, 80, 66, NULL, 'Simon Fraser University'),
(683, 747, 'Stella Tagnin', 'In my talk I will present a corpus Project we have been developing at the University of São Paulo since 1998. The CoMET Project consists of three distinct corpora which can be freely investigated online (www.fflch.usp.br/dlm/comet). The first is atechnical corpus–CorTec–with original texts in Portuguese and English in, to date, 20 different domains. The second is a bidirectional Portuguese and English translation corpus–CorTrad-with technical-scientific, literary and journalistic original texts and their respective translations. The third is a learner corpus which hosts the written production of students learning English, French, German, Italian and Spanish. All three corpora have customized search tools allowing for a variety of research possibilities. These will be illustrated and discussed throughout the talk.', 1369913400, 1369918800, 80, 66, NULL, 'Universidade de São Paulo'),
(684, 748, 'Reem Alsadoon', '', 1366797600, 0, 80, 66, NULL, 'Simon Fraser University'),
(685, 749, 'Allard Jongman', 'Invariance and variability are notions that have stimulated much research on theacoustics and perception of speech. While some phonemic distinctions do seem to berepresented by invariant acoustic properties, it is clear that many acoustic cues are contextdependent. Normalization or compensation processes for coping with specific sources of variability have been proposed as solutions to this context dependency. In this talk, I will argue that the lack of invariance is not a major obstacle. I will use the English fricatives as a test case to demonstrate that variability can be overcome by the use of multiple acoustic cues and a relatively simple compensation scheme by which cues are recoded relative to expectations derived from context. I will also provide results from clearly produced fricatives to show that speakers not only are aware of the contrasts in their phonetic inventory and make a general effort to maintain these contrasts but also attempt to preserve contrast at a more local level, adapting on line in response to perception errors. Together, these results support the notion that speakers constantly assess the listener’s needs for explicit signal information and modulate their speech cues, which must in turn be interpreted relative to a multitude a expectations.', 1365075000, 1365082200, 80, 66, 0, 'University of Kansas'),
(686, 750, 'Michael Walsh', 'For many years we have sensed that the retention and revitalization of Australianlanguages can lead to health benefits for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples,but it is only rather recently that more concrete demonstrations of these views havebegun to emerge. For instance, the Australian Human Rights Commission’s Social JusticeReport 2009 observes, ‘A ten year study of Indigenous Australians in Central Australiafound that “connectedness to culture, family and land, and opportunities for self determination” assist in significantly lower morbidity and mortality rates in Homelandresidents’ [http://www.hreoc.gov.ausocial_justice/sj_report/sjreport09/chap3.html]. Elsewhere we find instances of collaborations between language revitalisation efforts and those involved in health delivery. Such collaborations can be mutually beneficial aslanguage documentation provides a clearer vision of cultural considerations for healthworkers. This paper will survey the growing interest in the link between language retention and revitalization, and, Indigenous wellbeing not just in Australia but other parts of the world, including British Columbia.', 1372851000, 1372856400, 80, 66, NULL, 'AIATSIS Centre for Australian Languages'),
