(743, 807, 'Prof. Dai Xianchi', 'This presentation includes two parts. In the first part I will talk about a heuristic underlying the effect of value (desirability, monetary incentive, etc.) on judgment. I will show that people infer scarcity of an object from their personal desire, or valuation of it. In the second part, I will propose a two-process model of the effect of motivation (desire, needs, etc) on judgment. According to this model, motivation leads to two opposite effects. One is wishful thinking, in which people’s evaluation is assimilated toward their motivated expectation. The other is a contrast effect, in which people use their motivated expectation as a reference point to evaluate reality. I further propose that ownership status determines the relative weight of the two processes. This model reconciles opposite findings from myself and from New Look psychologists such as Bruner & Goodman (1947). Implications and future research directions will be discussed.', 1284462000, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D, INSEAD (European Institute of Business Administration), Fontainebleau, FranceAssistant Professor of MarketingFaculty of Business AdministrationThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(744, 808, 'Prof. Benjamin Munson', '(Research conducted with: Jan Edwards, Mary Beckman, Sarah Schellinger, Kari Urberg-Carlson, Fangang Li, and Eunjong Kong)Traditional views of phonological development have focused on children’s acquired knowledge of abstract phonological categories such as phonemes, distinctive features, or markedness and faithfulness constraints, depending on the dominant linguistic theory at the time the research is conducted. Such a view of phonological development makes many assumptions. For example, it assumes that children’s phonological learning is best described in terms of alphabetic transcription; that patterns of phonological development are the same across different languages; and that phonological development depends largely on the learner and not on the characteristics of the input they receive. In this talk, I will present analyses from a set of experiments that were conducted in collaboration with a large set of colleagues.The first set of experiments examines the utilities and pitfalls of using phonetic transcription as the primary tool to study speech-sound development. I will review evidence that the acquisition of speech sounds is a continuous process of phonetic differentiation that begins early in life, and extends far beyond the point at which children produce words that are rated to sound adult-like. I will present the results of a set of experiments aimed at developing perceptual techniques for measuring children''s gradual differentiation in speech sounds.The second set of experiments examines cross-linguistic studies of children''s speech-sound development. In particular, I will focus on a set of studies that show that apparent cross-linguistic differences in children''s phonological acquisition can be accounted for, in part, by cross-linguistic differences in adults'' perception of children''s'' speech.The final set of experiments examines associations between adults'' perception of children''s speech and their subsequent models to children. These experiments show that adults subtly modify their speech in response to children''s productions that they perceive to be incorrect. I argue these modifications serve the dual functions of giving the children hyper-correct input (similar to that of child-directed speech), as well as error-corrective feedback to children.', 1286881200, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D., The Ohio State UniversityAssociate ProfessorDepartment of Speech-Language-Hearing Sciences'),
(745, 809, 'Dr. Kay Deaux', 'Social categories are fundamental to our understanding of ourselves and other people. People readily organize their social world into categories such as gender, age, nationality, and they easily make distinctions between friends and enemies, relatives and strangers, or the wise and the foolish. People also define themselves in terms of social identities, many of which may overlap in some respects with the categories used by others, e.g. I am a woman, a professor, and an American. I will argue, however, that there are important differences between observers and actors in the ways that they use these social categories and in the functions that social categorization serves. Research in the areas of stereotyping, social identification, and stereotype threat will be discussed to support this analysis.', 1288090800, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Distinguished Professor EmeritaCity University of New York Graduate Center'),
(746, 810, 'Prof. Ronan Reilly', 'This paper analyses some aspects of the eye movement behaviour of readers of Thai and Chinese. The main focus is on readers’ landing site site distributions on words and how these are affected by the lack of clear word boundary information in both writing systems. Empirical evidence from Thai and Chinese readers suggest that readers can relatively accurately target word centres, which is important for fast and accurate word recognition. It is proposed that this targetting accuracy can be accounted for by a default targetting model (effectively, the prior landing site distribution in Bayesian terms) modulated by statistical clues about word beginnings available from word-initial character frequencies. A modification of the Glenmore model of eye movement control in reading (Reilly & Radach, 2006) is described that accounts for the pattern of data.Reilly, R.G., & Radach, R. (2006). Some empirical tests of an interactive activation model of eye movement control in reading. Cognitive Systems Research, 7, 34-55.', 1291114800, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Head of the Department of Computer ScienceNational University of Ireland, Maynooth'),
(747, 811, 'Prof. Tse Chi Shing', 'In this talk, Prof. Tse will overview the role of attentional control in the discrimination of individuals with early-stage Alzheimer''s disease (AD, as defined by Clinical Dementia Rating of 0.5) vs. healthy older adults. Two lines of research in early-stage AD discrimination will be discussed, including (a) the measures of intraindividual variability and response time distribution in a selective attention task (Duchek, Balota, Tse et al., 2009, Neuropsychology; Tse, Balota, Yap et al., 2010, Neuropsychology) and (b) the performance in a test-enhanced learning paradigm (Tse, Balota & Roediger, 2010, Psychology and Aging). The possibilities that these paradigms could be applied in educational and developmental studies will also be discussed.', 1297767600, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D., University at Albany, State University of New York, USAAssistant Professor, Department of Educational PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(748, 812, 'Prof. Anna Lau', 'The cultural fit proposition suggests that personality attributes that fit with prevailing cultural norms promote positive psychological adjustment. It also stands to reason that one''s own attributes may or may not fit with one''s own internalized cultural values. We tested an intra-personal cultural fit hypothesis suggesting that the association between emotion recognition ability and distress is moderated by the degree to which one holds interdependence values. Results provided some support for the hypothesized aptitude by values interaction, indicating that problems "reading the air" have greater costs for distress among Asian Americans who endorsed high interdependence values.', 1300186800, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D in Clinical Psychology, University of California, Los Angeles, USAAssociate Professor, University of California, Los Angeles, USAAdjunct Associate Professor, The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(749, 813, 'Prof. John Zhang', 'The thousands of written languages in the world are all alphabetic except written Chinese using a large number of block characters. It has been a debate for over a hundred years as to whether written Chinese can be or should be Romanized, i.e., replaced with a writing system using the Roman alphabet. This talk will present a new theory identifying written Chinese as a meaning-spelling system at the vocabulary level, in contrast to alphabetic scripts that are sound-spelling or pinyin systems. This theory deduces that the alphabetic and the Chinese scripts represent two and the only two destinations of written language evolution, with one deeply rooted in human audition and the other in human vision. Constituting a dichotomy, the two types of writing systems have complementary strengths and weaknesses, and it is neither necessary nor possible to Romanize the Chinese characters without significant reduction in communication efficiency.', 1301396400, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D, Princeton University, USAAssistant Professor, Department of Psychology, The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(750, 814, 'Dr. Yiu Kei Tsang', 'Morphemic ambiguity occurs when a morpheme has more than one meaning (e.g., the prefix "in-" in "inside" and "insane"). In this seminar, I present three studies which investigated the processing of ambiguous morpheme. First, I compared morphological processing in word recognition and production. Although ambiguous morphemes are involved, the temporal dynamics differed remarkably across tasks. Second, I contrasted the processing of ambiguous morphemes with opaque words (e.g., "intact", where "in-" did not contribute to word meaning). Results suggest that opaque words were treated like the less frequent meaning of the ambiguous morpheme. Therefore, by assuming a continuum of meaning productivity, effects of morphemic ambiguity and semantic transparency can be unified. Finally, the eye tracker was used to monitor how morphemic ambiguity was resolved. While all meanings were initially activated, context could moderate the strength of activation. Collectively, these experiments confirm a robust morphological processing in lexical access.', 1303210800, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D, CUHKInstructor, Department of Psychology, The Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(751, 815, 'Prof. John X. Zhang', 'All current written languages are alphabetic scripts (e.g., English) whose word recognition involves discrimination of one-dimensional linear combinations of several dozens of letters, except written Chinese whose vocabulary consists of a large number of block characters, the analysis of which relies on the extraction of two-dimensional form information at multiple levels including radical, character, and multiple-character word. Whether the dramatic contrast between the two types of orthography leads to distinctive mental processes is a fundamental question in psycholinguistic research unanswered in the past three decades albeit extensive efforts. This talk will present event-related potential evidence for the observation of a new brain wave N200, which seems to be specific to linguistic processing involved in recognizing written Chinese. The meaning-spelling theory, recently proposed by the speaker, argues that Chinese and alphabetic scripts differ by nature in that the former is more a visual language while the latter more an auditory language. The discovery of a Chinese-specific neural marker provides strong empirical support to this theory.', 1316516400, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D of Princeton UniversityAssistant ProfessorDepartment of PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(752, 816, 'Prof. Catherine A. McBride-Chang', 'An important theoretical question across areas of psychology is the extent to which models of behavior are culture-specific vs. culture-general. In this talk, I will consider this question in relation to children’s literacy acquisition. There are at least four aspects of Chinese literacy development that have no clear analogy to literacy development in alphabetic systems. These are 1) the unit of reading (character vs. word), 2) the place of radical-learning (especially semantic radicals) in literacy acquisition, 3) the relative prominence of morphological knowledge in early reading and writing processes, and 4) nonlinguistic aspects of learning Chinese (i.e., basic visual and copying skills). If Chinese literacy development does diverge from alphabetic literacy development in these ways, this may present challenges to universal models of children’s reading and writing development and point the way to new approaches to teaching Chinese very generally as well as remediating Chinese children with dyslexia more specifically.', 1317726000, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D of Southern CaliforniaProfessorDepartment of PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(753, 817, 'Prof. Helene H.L. Fung', 'The psychology and aging literature usually describes the process of aging as static and universal. This talk challenges this assumption by reporting a research program showing that many well-established aging phenomena can differ across cultures. Findings from my research program suggest that aging, at least in the areas of social relationships, cognition (visual attention and memory) and personality, does not manifest in exactly the same way among cultural groups such as Chinese, Americans, Canadians and Germans. Moreover, when cultural differences in aging occur, they are usually consistent with known cultural differences in values. These findings inspire me to argue that socioemotional development across adulthood may be part of a life-long socialization process: Individuals in each culture learn to be better members of their culture as they grow older. Cultural differences in aging (i.e., age by culture interactions) occur when people from different cultural contexts learn different ways to become better members of their cultures.', 1321354800, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D of StanfordProfessorDepartment of PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(754, 818, 'Dr. June C.Y. Lo', 'Sleep and wakefulness are regulated by (1) a circadian process generating an approximately 24h rhythm in sleep propensity, and (2) a homeostatic process, with sleep propensity increasing during wakefulness and dissipating during sleep. We investigated the role of sleep and circadian rhythms in the regulation of ongoing performance as well as memory consolidation. Our data revealed that cognitive performance during total sleep deprivation was affected by both the circadian and the homeostatic processes such that prior repeated partial sleep loss exacerbated the cognitive decline, but this effect was virtually absent in the evening and most prominent during the early morning hours. However, cognitive vulnerability during sleep loss was not uniform across all cognitive domains and varied widely across individuals with such individual differences predicted by a variable number tandem repeat polymorphism in a clock gene – PERIOD3. In contrast to the importance of the two processes in regulating ongoing cognitive performance during wakefulness , we only found evidence for a homeostatic, but not a circadian, modulation of sleep’s facilitative effect on the consolidation of declarative memory. These data provide evidence for the differential contribution of sleep and circadian rhythms to ongoing performance and memory consolidation.', 1326798000, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Postdoctoral Research Fellow in Cognition, Sleep, and Circadian RhythmsUniversity of Surrey, England'),
(755, 819, 'Prof. John X. Zhang', 'The centro-parietal N200 is a new brain wave we first observed three years ago. It is a negative deflection in event-related potentials (ERP) elicited by two-character Chinese words around 200 milliseconds after their presentation, most salient in central and parietal brain regions. Here we summarize the over thirty experiments we have conducted so far on this ERP response to present convincing evidence that it is a real discovery beyond any reasonable doubt. Evidence shows that the N200 is sensitive to orthographic but not semantic, or phonological manipulations and can also be demonstrated for single characters as basic units in written Chinese. Coding the visual form at the radical and character levels, as well as the word level, the N200 is argued to be a neural marker that distinguishes word recognition in Chinese and alphabetic scripts, a marker that researchers on reading have been looking for in the past three decades. This marker allows us for the first time to answer for the Chinese script one of the fundamental questions in reading research, i.e., when is the visual form of a word recognized? Albeit many years’ of investigation, answer to the same question for alphabetic scripts remains elusive.Presently, no theory seems able to accommodate the N200 phenomenon and its specificity to Chinese except the meaning-spelling theory the speaker proposed in 201l, which posits that Chinese and alphabetic scripts are rooted in different sensory modalities and constitute a dichotomy among all human writing systems. Characteristics of the centro-parietal N200, such as early onset, robustness, salience, and specificity to orthography and to the Chinese language, suggests a possibility of our leaping into a new level of understanding of visual word recognition, and possibly of reading in general.', 1329476400, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D. of Princeton UniversityAssistant ProfessorDepartment of PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(756, 820, 'Prof. Qian Wang', 'Chinese parenting and academic motivation are of great interest to developmental and cross-cultural psychologists. In particular, much research has been devoted to understanding why Chinese parents typically exert heightened control over their offspring, how parental control affects Chinese youth’s well-being, and why Chinese youth usually outperform their Western counterparts academically. In this talk, I will present some of my recent research along the aforementioned lines conducted among middle-school students in Mainland China and university students in Hong Kong. The research addressed the following issues: 1) the links from Chinese parents’ socialization goals to their parenting behaviors, 2) Chinese youth’s thoughts and feelings about parental control, 3) moderating conditions for the links from parental control to Chinese youth’s well-being, 4) the roles of various aspects of academic motivation ranging from intrinsic to extrinsic in predicting Chinese youth’s academic engagement, 5) the roles of beliefs about intelligence and school performance in predicting Chinese youth’s approach to schoolwork, and 6) the role of feeling guilty in the face of unsatisfactory performance in predicting Chinese youth’s academic engagement and achievement. I will discuss the findings from a perspective of “universalism without the uniformity” (Shweder & Sullivan, 1993) on the role of culture in parenting and child development.', 1334055600, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D. of Illinois, Urbana-ChampaignAssistant ProfessorDepartment of PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(757, 821, 'Prof. C.Y. Chiu', 'Globalization scholars have used the phrase "experiential compression of time and space" to characterize the cultural effects of globalization. Globalization has conferred many opportunities for encountering traditional and modern cultures at the same time and local and global cultures in the same space. Despite the increased attention given to cultural phenomena in social psychology, the field has neglected issues related to the cultural impacts of globalization. Using my research on the social cognitive consequences of activating two cultural representations simultaneously as an example, I argue for constructing a social psychology of globalization that offers nuanced understanding of people''s psychological responses to culture mixing. Although simultaneous activation of cultural representations does not determine an individual''s cultural identity, it enlarges the felt distinctions between different identity options and magnifies the effects of identity choice. Furthermore, in situations that emphasize appropriating intellectual resources from diverse cultures to foster creativity, simultaneous activation of cultural representations may facilitate creative performance.', 1334660400, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D. of Columbia UniversityProfessorNanyang Business SchoolNanyang Technological UniversityVisiting Professor of Social ScienceThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(758, 822, 'Prof. Neil Levy', 'What kind of consciousness - if any - is necessary for agents to be responsible for their actions? Some neuroscientists (Libet, Soon et al.) and psychologists (Wegner, Bargh) have argued that we are not conscious of initiating actions, and therefore cannot be responsible for them. Some philosophers (eg Churchland) have responded that we don''t need to be conscious of our actions in order to be responsible for them. In this paper, I argue that some kind of consciousness is necessary for moral responsibility. However, rather than neuroscience showing that we lack consciousness of our actions, a neuroscientific account of consciousness can underwrite our moral responsibility.', 1337079600, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D. of Monash UniversityDeputy DirectorOxford Centre for NeuroethicsHead of NeuroethicsFlorey Neuroscience InstitutesUniversity of Melbourne'),
(759, 823, 'Dr. James Minett', 'A brain-computer interface, or BCI, is a system that makes use of a direct connection between brain and computer to control external apparatus, such as a prosthetic limb or wheelchair. For individuals with neuro-degenerative disorders that prevent them from communicating by conventional means---such as by speech, writing, or sign language---BCIs can provide alternative channels for communication that enable text to be input to a computer by thought alone. In this talk, I will summarize the principles and methods by which electroencephalography (EEG) is currently used to implement BCIs to assist communication, both in English (and other languages with alphabetic writing system) and Chinese (the focus of my own research). I will discuss two main methods: one based on modulations of the P300 and other event-related potentials that are elicited by visual stimuli presented in an oddball paradigm, the other based on modulations of the sensorimotor (mu) rhythm that result from imagined body movements. I will also present interim results of an on-going study by our team in which we are exploring how lateralization and polarity reversal of the event-related potentials elicited by non-attended visual stimuli can be harnessed to increase BCI system performance.', 1347966000, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D. of City University of Hong KongPostdoctoral FellowDepartment of Electronic EngineeringThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(760, 824, 'Prof. Savio Wong', 'Do we make decisions with our brain or heart? Based on the studies of brain lesion patients, Antonio Damasio proposed the Somatic Marker Hypothesis that our body response is an indispensable part of emotion and plays a crucial role in decision-making. In this seminar, I will present the brain imaging and psychophysiological data demonstrating how our feeling and behavior are affected by physiological responses. The functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) data revealed that the insular cortex and the ventral medial prefrontal cortex not only modulate cardiovascular responses but also involve in emotion and decision-making. In addition, I will present some psychophysiological data showing the effect of body arousal on decision-making and the experience of empathy. At the end, I will discuss the implications of the Somatic Marker Hypothesis in the research of addiction, autism, and education.', 1348570800, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D. of The University of Hong KongAssistant ProfessorThe Hong Kong Institute of Education'),
(761, 825, 'Dr. John Robert Bola', 'Clinical practice guidelines around the world universally recommend treating nearly all cases of first-episode psychosis with antipsychotic medications for 6-24 months. However, about 40% of people recover without antipsychotic treatment when provided supportive, psychosocial treatment in a protected, low stress environment. Current knowledge is inadequate to discriminate the 40% not needing antipsychotics from the 60% benefiting from the medications. This presentation describes the background rationale and the preliminary design components for a scientific investigation to develop the knowledge that will enable the discrimination of these two important treatment-response subgroups in first-episode psychosis.', 1349780400, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D., University of California, BerkeleyAssociate ProfessorCity University of Hong Kong'),
(762, 826, 'Dr. Joy D. Osofsky, Ph.D.', 'Louisiana is vulnerable to both natural and technological disasters with the Gulf of Mexico being the major site in the United States for oil drilling. In August 2005, much of South Louisiana was devastated by Hurricane Katrina and failure of protective levees. In April 2010, many of the same communities still recovering were highly impacted by the Gulf Oil Spill. This presentation is focused on two research studies: 1) screening assessments of students carried out annually since Hurricane Katrina focusing on traumatic exposure and mental health symptoms; 2) a mental and behavioral health surveillance of adults and communities highly impacted by the Gulf Oil Spill carried out in 2010-2012. Patterns of symptoms over time as well as recovery and resilience will be discussed.', 1350385200, 0, 75, 59, 0, 'Barbara Lemann ProfessorDepartments of Pediatrics and PsychiatryLouisiana State University Health Sciences Center'),
(763, 827, 'Dr. Howard J. Osofsky, M.D., Ph.D.', 'Louisiana is vulnerable to both natural and technological disasters with the Gulf of Mexico being the major site in the United States for oil drilling. In August 2005, much of South Louisiana was devastated by Hurricane Katrina and failure of protective levees. In April 2010, many of the same communities still recovering were highly impacted by the Gulf Oil Spill. This presentation is focused on two research studies: 1) screening assessments of students carried out annually since Hurricane Katrina focusing on traumatic exposure and mental health symptoms; 2) a mental and behavioral health surveillance of adults and communities highly impacted by the Gulf Oil Spill carried out in 2010-2012. Patterns of symptoms over time as well as recovery and resilience will be discussed.', 1350385200, 0, 75, 59, 0, 'Kathleen and John Bricker ChairDepartment of PsychiatryLouisiana State University Health Sciences Center'),
(764, 828, 'Dr. Lobsang Rapgay, Ph.D.', 'There is an increasing need to go beyond current westernized forms of mindfulness by visiting the original teachings on mindfulness. Classical Mindfulness is based on the Four Foundations of Mindfulness that employs concentration (samatha) to acquire objective skills in developing experiential insight (vipassana).Cognitive psychology and neuroscience independently establishes the centrality of concentration (sustained attention) to all forms of learning. The talk will show how clinically classical mindfulness can directly address impairment in cognitive processing (particularly attentional and memory) in anxious patients, and how doing so can facilitate the effectiveness of CBT.', 1352718000, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Director of the Study on Sustained, Distributed Attention and Working Memory in Anxiety DisordersDepartment of Psychiatry, UCLAResearcher in Zaidel''s Laboratory of Cognitive NeuroscienceDepartment of Psychology, UCLADirector of the Clinical Training programMindfulness Awareness Research Center, UCLA'),
(765, 829, 'Prof. Zhansheng Chen', 'Money plays an important role in modern life, yet empirical investigations on the psychology of money are rare. A new line of research on money has demonstrated that calling people’s attention to money can lead them to reach a state of self-sufficiency, in which people value autonomy and prefer to be free of dependency. This presentation focuses on how reminding people of the concept of money influences emotion expression, person perception, and moral judgment.', 1353409200, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D., Purdue UniversityAssistant ProfessorThe University of Hong Kong'),
(766, 830, 'Prof. Ovid J.L. Tzeng', 'Reading and writing are two of the most remarkable achievements of humankind. Not only they shaped the executive functions of our cognitive system, but also they laid down changes in our brain such that a literate becomes biologically distinct as compared to the illiterate. One question has often been raised: Do the neural circuits for reading vary across different writing systems? Along the same line of reasoning, it has been proposed that reading of visually complex writing systems such as Chinese relies on areas outside the classical left-hemisphere network for alphabetic reading. Here, however, we show that, once potential confounds in cross-cultural comparisons are controlled for, no neuro-imaging evidence is available to suggest such differences. A recent study by Nakamura, Kuo, Pegado, Cohen, Tzeng, and Dehaene (2012), using functional magnetic resonance to scan the brain of Chinese and French readers while they were presented with handwritten stimuli, demonstrated that two universal circuits, a shape recognition and a gesture recognition system, are similarly activated with almost identical patterns of activation and repetition priming in both written languages. Specific brain regions related to cultural specific associations are also activated. However, these cultural effects are found to modulate a fixed set of invariant macroscopic brain circuits in response to surface features of orthography. I shall review the literature on the fMRI studies of writing in order to delineate the underlying general and specific neural bases of graphomotoric codes in writing.', 1330254000, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Siu Lien Ling Wong Visiting Fellow 2012/2013Chung Chi CollegeAcademician and Distinguished Fellow,Institute of Linguistics, Academia Sinica, Taiwan'),
(767, 831, 'Prof. Eugene Mullan', 'In the context of a rapidly changing healthcare environment IAPT has been a beacon of success. Since its inception in 2008, with the aim to provide a universal primary care psychological therapy service for people with depression and anxiety disorders, IAPT services have seen over 1 million patients and trained over 4,500 therapists in evidence-based CBT approaches.It has been highly successful as a policy intervention, and the government is now rolling it out across other patient groups. New training programmes and curricula developments for Children and Young People are the priority. More developments will follow, with proposals for curricula and service interventions for Older Adults, Personality Disorder and Long Term Conditions. Within 5 years the psychological therapies workforce has been transformed and IAPT is now central to government policy for effective service delivery and evidence-based approaches.This presentation will give an overview of the development, delivery and future directions for IAPT in the UK, along with the implications for Clinical Psychology practice.', 1363086000, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Director of Clinical Training (CEDAR)University of Exeter, UK'),
(768, 832, 'Dr. Jennifer Lau', 'Fears and worries are common, and can be disabling and costly. On the one hand, fear is as an adaptive emotion-state mediating our responses to danger. On the other hand, for many individuals fears are experienced as excessive and persistent, emerging in situations that are safe rather than threatening. A significant proportion of adults with persistent anxiety problems report that these begin early in life, marking late childhood and adolescence as developmentally-sensitive junctures for studying anxiety-risk but also anxiety-resilience.In this talk, I will use examples from my own work to touch on three key questions:    Why do some young people experience greater levels of fears and worries than others?    Why is the transition to adolescence marked as a period of vulnerability for the onset of persistent fears and worries?    Is adolescence also a period of exceptional plasticity - and if so, can we challenge early pathological emotional and social development through targeted interventions?These questions will be addressed through explanations at multiple levels, from genes to the social environment, and through interventions also targeting multiple levels, from neural mechanisms to cognitive biases.', 1368529200, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'University Lecturer and Tutorial Fellow in Experimental PsychologyUniversity of OxfordHeadResearching Emotional Disorders and Development (REDD) LabDirectorCalleva Research Centre for Evolution and Human ScienceDirector of Clinical Training (CEDAR)University of Exeter, UK'),
(769, 833, 'Dr. Karen R. Dobkins, Ph.D.', 'Early infancy is characterized by a period of exuberant neural connectivity followed by a retraction and reweighting of connections over the course of development. It has been proposed that this connectivity may produce a perceptual intermingling of the senses in infants that is unlike that experienced by typical adults. And, a lack of pruning of these exuberant connections during development is thought to explain the rare condition of "synesthesia" in about 2% of adults, wherein one sense involuntarily evokes an additional arbitrary sensation. We have been studying the perceptual consequences of neuronal intermingling in young infants and adults with "grapheme-color" synesthesia, wherein specific letters or numbers evoke idiosyncratic, largely individualized sensations of specific colors. Our results in typically developing infants (2 to 4 months) are consistent with them making strong associations between color and shapes (a precursor to graphemes), as well as between color and motion, which are significantly greater than the associations experienced by typical adults. Such findings – which suggest that all young infants experience synesthesia, provide a perceptual consequence of the exuberant neural connections seen in the infant brain.', 1380020400, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Professor of PsychologyUniversity of California, San Diego'),
(770, 834, 'Dr. William Gordon Hayward, Ph.D.', 'Humans live in social communities where most people tend to be one ethnicity. Therefore, we tend to have more experience at discriminating faces from "our own" group than from other ethnic groups, and we also form social judgments as to whether faces belong to "our own" social group or to "another" group. Not surprisingly, memory for own-race faces is generally superior to memory for other-race faces. How do experiential factors affect perception of own-race and other-race faces, and what is the link with memory differences? In this talk, I will review a large number of studies that have sought to assess the nature of perceptual processing for faces that belong to different ethnicities, and I will examine the extent to which we understand the link between perceptual differences and memory differences in race-based face processing.', 1382439600, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Head, Department of PsychologyThe University of Hong Kong'),
(771, 835, 'Prof. Takeshi Hamamura', 'Contrary to the stereotype of stoicism associated with several Asian cultures, studies have found heightened pain reactions among individuals of Asian ethnicity relative to those of European ethnicity both in North America and Europe. However, these findings may be due to conflation of ethnicity and acculturation in past research. In fact, studies that dissociate these two factors suggest the role of acculturation, but not ethnicity, in shaping pain responses. Such effect of acculturation in shaping pain has been observed both in lab and field settings and across a few pain modalities. This talk will introduce these findings as well as more recent findings that begin to illuminate why acculturation affects pain responses.', 1383649200, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D, UBCAssistant Professor, Department of PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(772, 836, 'Prof. Agnes S. Chan', 'The connection between the neural system and immune system have been received much attention recently as more and more empirical evidence suggesting that these two system are interactive with each other. Our research laboratory has studied this model on a group of children with autism, and the results suggested that the immune function and neural function are highly correlated (Han et al., 2011; Han et al., 2013). We also studied the hypothesis that some lifestyle interventions that changing the body can concurrently changing the neural function; in turn, improving the cognitive and psychological functions (Chan et al., 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013).', 1384858800, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D., UCSDProfessor, Department of PsychologyDirector, Chanwuyi Research Center for Neuropsychological Well-BeingThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
(773, 837, 'Dr. Jian Huang', 'Semantic processing during sentence comprehension involves retrieving the meanings of individual words and integrating those meanings into larger semantic units. However, the temporal and spatial dynamics of the neural mechanisms underlying these semantic processes remain unclear. The N400 component of the event-related brain potential (ERP) has long been considered as an important index of semantic processing. In this talk I will present findings from neuroimaging studies using various methods (i.e., ERP, functional magnetic resonance imaging or fMRI, and event-related optical signals or EROS) on the brain activation patterns related to semantic processing within, before, and after the N400 time window. I will also discuss the theoretical implications of the obtained results.', 1386068400, 0, 75, 59, NULL, 'Ph.D.PostDoc Fellow, Department of PsychologyThe Chinese University of Hong Kong'),
